Montenegro v England|home match]] against [[England national football team|England]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/disciplinary/index.html#post_4383669|title=UEFA Appeals Body decision \u2013 Football Association of Montenegro|publisher=[[UEFA]]|date=26 April 2019}}</ref>}}\n{{Cnote2|c|The North Macedonia v Kosovo match, originally scheduled for 26 March 2020, 20:45 ([[UTC+01:00|UTC+1]]) at the [[To\u0161e Proeski Arena]], [[Skopje]] was postponed on 17 March due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in North Macedonia|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/news/newsid=2641071.html|title=UEFA postpones EURO 2020 by 12 months|quote=All UEFA competitions and matches (including friendlies) for clubs and national teams for both men and women have been put on hold until further notice. The UEFA EURO 2020 play-off matches and international friendlies, scheduled for the end of March, will now be played in the international window at the start of June, subject to a review of the situation|publisher=[[UEFA]]|date=17 March 2020}}</ref>}}\n{{Cnote2|d|After stadiums in [[Adem Jashari Olympic Stadium|Mitrovica]] and [[Fadil Vokrri Stadium|Pristina]] were under renovation and do not meet UEFA standards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegrafi.com/keto-jane-11-stadiumet-e-superliges-dhe-asnjeri-nuk-ploteson-kushtet-foto/|title=K\u00ebto jan\u00eb 11 stadiumet e Superlig\u00ebs dhe asnj\u00ebri nuk i plot\u00ebson kushtet (Foto)|trans-title=These are the 11 Superleague stadiums and none meet the conditions (Photo)|language=Albanian|publisher=[[Telegrafi]]|date=3 May 2016}}</ref> Kosovo played the [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification&nbsp;\u2013 UEFA Group I#Matches|qualifying matches]] of the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] in [[Loro Bori\u00e7i Stadium]] ({{lang-sq|Stadiumi Loro Bori\u00e7i}}), a multi-use stadium in [[Shkod\u00ebr]], [[Albania]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rtklive.com/sq/news-single.php?ID=83148|title=Loro Bori\u00e7i, sht\u00ebpia e p\u00ebrkohshme e Kosov\u00ebs|trans-title=Loro Bori\u00e7i, the temporary home of Kosovo|language=Albanian|publisher=[[Radio Television of Kosovo]]|date=28 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/edirama.al/posts/10153918522541523|title=Loro Bori\u00e7i, i rilindur gati p\u00ebr kolaudim (Foto)|trans-title=Loro Bori\u00e7i, reborn ready for test (Photo)|language=Albanian|publisher=[[Edi Rama]]|website=[[Facebook]]|date=11 August 2016}}</ref>}}\n{{Cnote2 End}}\n\n===References===\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.ffk-kosova.com/}} {{in lang|sq|en}}\n*[http://www.national-football-teams.com/country/259/Kosovo.html Kosovo] at National Football Teams\n*[http://www.rsssf.com/tablesk/kosovo-intres.html Kosovo] at [[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]]\n\n{{Football in Kosovo}}\n{{National sports teams of Kosovo}}\n{{UEFA teams}}\n\n[[Category:Kosovo national football team]]\n[[Category:European national association football teams]]\n", "name_user": "Krelana", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kosovo_national_football_team"}
{"title_page": "Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4", "text_new": "{{short description|Finnish combat sniper}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4\n| image         = Simo hayha honorary rifle.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| caption       = H\u00e4yh\u00e4 after being awarded the honorary rifle model 28.\n| nickname      = \"White Death\"\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1905|12|17|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Rautj\u00e4rvi]], [[Viipuri Province]], Finland, Russian Empire\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2002|04|01|1905|12|17|df=yes}}\n| death_place   = [[Hamina]], Finland\n| placeofburial = \n| allegiance    = {{flag|Finland}}\n| branch        = Finnish Army\n| serviceyears  = 1925\u20131940\n| rank          = Alikersantti (Corporal) during the [[Winter War]], promoted to V\u00e4nrikki (Second Lieutenant) shortly afterward<ref name=\"HS\">{{cite news |author=Lappalainen, Jukka-Pekka |title=Kollaa kesti, niin my\u00f6s Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4 |newspaper=Helsingin Sanomat |url=https://www.hs.fi/ihmiset/art-2000004016250.html |accessdate=19 February 2011 |location=Helsinki |date=6 December 2001 |url-access=subscription|language=Finnish |trans-title=The Kollaa held out, so did Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4 }}</ref>\n| unit          = \n| commands      = \n| battles       = Winter War\n* [[Battle of Kollaa]]\n| awards        = {{nowrap|[[Order of the Cross of Liberty|Cross of Liberty]], 3rd class and 4th class<br />[[Order of the Cross of Liberty|Medal of Liberty]], 1st class and 2nd class<br />Cross of Kollaa Battle<ref name=\"HS\" />}}\n| relations     = \n| laterwork     = \n}}\n\n'''Simo \"Simuna\" H\u00e4yh\u00e4''' ({{IPA-fi|\u02c8simo \u02c8h\u00e6y\u032fh\u00e6}}; 17 December 1905&nbsp;\u2013 1 April 2002), was a [[Finland|Finnish]] [[sniper]]. He is believed to have killed over 500 men during the 1939\u201340 [[Winter War]], the highest number of [[List of snipers|sniper kills]] in any major war. He used a Finnish-produced [[Mosin\u2013Nagant#Finland|M/28-30]] rifle, a variant of the Mosin\u2013Nagant rifle, and a [[Suomi KP/-31]] sub machine gun.<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite news |author=Rayment, Sean |title=The long view |work=The Daily Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1517044/The-long-view.html |accessdate=30 March 2009 |location=London |date=30 April 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Saarelainen, Taipo |title=The White Death: History's Deadliest Sniper |work=Forces Network |url=https://www.forces.net/news/tri-service/white-death-historys-deadliest-sniper |location= |date=15 November 2016}}</ref><ref>Tapio A.M. Saarelainen: Sankarikorpraali Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4 (2006)</ref> His unit's captain Antti Rantamaa credited him with 259 confirmed kills by sniper rifle and an equal number of kills by sub machine gun during the Winter War. Later in his book, Rantamaa credited H\u00e4yh\u00e4 with 542 sniper kills.<ref name=\"book\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R948DQAAQBAJ&pg=PT35&dq=simo+hayha+219+kills&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjAr_bR0frSAhXGwLwKHRBhAzgQ6AEIKjAC#v=onepage&q=simo+hayha+219+kills&f=false|title=The White Sniper|first=Tapio|last=Saarelainen|date=31 October 2016|publisher=Casemate|accessdate=12 March 2019|via=Google Books}}</ref> H\u00e4yh\u00e4 never talked about it publicly but estimated in his private diary that he shot around 500.<ref name=\"iltalehti\">{{cite news |author=Kauppinen, Kari |title=Sotasankari Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4n ennenn\u00e4kem\u00e4t\u00f6n p\u00e4iv\u00e4kirja l\u00f6ytyi - \"T\u00e4ss\u00e4 on minun syntilistani\" |newspaper=Iltalehti|url=http://www.iltalehti.fi/kotimaa/201707172200270836_u0.shtml |accessdate=18 July 2017 |location=Helsinki |date=18 July 2017 |language=Finnish}}</ref><ref name=\"kivimaki\"/>\n\n==Early life==\nH\u00e4yh\u00e4 was born in the municipality of [[Rautj\u00e4rvi]] in the [[Viipuri Province]] of southern Finland near the border with Russia. He was the second youngest of eight children in a Lutheran family of farmers.<ref>[https://www.geni.com/people/Simo-H\u00e4yh\u00e4/6000000042734553943 About Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4]</ref> He was a farmer, hunter, and skier prior to his military service. He joined the Finnish voluntary militia [[White Guard (Finland)|White Guard]] (''Suojeluskunta'') at age 20, and he was successful in shooting competitions in the Viipuri Province. His home was reportedly full of trophies for marksmanship.<ref>{{cite book |last=Gilbert |first=Adrian |year=1996 |title=Sniper: The Skills, the Weapons, and the Experiences |publisher=St. Martin's Press |isbn=0-312-95766-1 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/sniperskillsweap00gilb/page/88 88] |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/sniperskillsweap00gilb/page/88 }}</ref> He was not keen to hog the spotlight, and correspondingly in the photos of his younger years he usually stood at the very back in group photos, until his later success started to force him to take center place.<ref name=\"muistikirja\"/>\n\n==Winter War service==\n[[File:Simo hayha second lieutenant 1940.png|thumb|right|H\u00e4yh\u00e4 in the 1940s, with visible damage to his left cheek after his 1940 wound]]\nH\u00e4yh\u00e4 served as a sniper for the [[Finnish Army]] during the 1939\u201340 [[Winter War]] between Finland and the Soviet Union. He was in the 6th Company of JR&nbsp;34 during the [[Battle of Kollaa]] in temperatures between {{convert|-40|\u00b0C}} and {{convert|-20|\u00b0C}}. H\u00e4yh\u00e4 was dressed completely in white camouflage; Soviet troops were not issued with white camouflage uniforms for most of the war, making them easily visible to snipers in winter conditions. [[Joseph Stalin]] [[Great Purge|had purged military experts]] in the late 1930s, and the Red Army was consequently highly disorganized.<ref>[pp. 145\u2013146 The Winter War: The Russo\u2013Finnish War of 1939\u201340 by William R. Trotter, Workman Publishing Company, New York (Aurum Press, London), 2002, First published 1991 in the United States under the title ''A Frozen Hell: The Russo\u2013Finnish Winter War of 1939\u201340'']</ref>\n\nAll of H\u00e4yh\u00e4's kills were accomplished in fewer than 100 days, an average of five per day at a time of year with very few daylight hours.<ref name=\"Jowett2006\">{{cite book |last=Jowett |first=Philip S. |title=Finland at War, 1939\u201345 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p58vtOKyVy8C |year=2006 |publisher=Osprey Publishing |isbn=978-1-84176-969-1 |pages=44\u201345}}</ref><ref name=\"Pegler2006\">{{cite book |last=Pegler |first=Martin |title=Out of Nowhere: A History of the Military Sniper |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-mkh931pIugC |year=2006 |publisher=Osprey Publishing |isbn=978-1-84603-140-3 |page=167}}</ref><ref name=\"FareySpicer2009\">{{cite book |last1=Farey |first1=Pat |last2=Spicer |first2=Mark |title=Sniping: An Illustrated History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l1a-kB-1MMAC|date=5 May 2009 |publisher=Zenith Press |isbn=978-0-7603-3717-2 |pages=117\u2013118}}</ref> A sniper's kill-count was based on the sniper himself, with the confirmation of his comrades, and only those who were killed for certain are considered. No count was taken when several snipers shot at the same target. Men killed with a submachine gun by a group leader were not counted.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.is.fi/kotimaa/art-2000000854160.html|title=Tarkka-ampuja Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4 ei koskaan saanut Mannerheim-risti\u00e4 - \"Harkitaan\"|first1=Timo|last1=Myllyniemi|first2=Tuomas|last2=Manninen|date=25 December 2014|website=Ilta-Sanomat|accessdate=12 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nFinnish sources describe that he was nicknamed \"''White Death''\" ({{lang-ru|\u0411\u0435\u043b\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0442\u044c}}, {{transl|ru|''Belaja smert''}}; {{lang-fi|valkoinen kuolema}}; {{lang-sv|den vita d\u00f6den}}) by the [[Red Army]].<ref name=\"book\"/> During the war, the \"White death\" was one of the leading themes of Finnish propaganda.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rdIgAQAAIAAJ|title=Journal of Information Warfare|first1=Edith Cowan University School of Management Information|last1=Systems|first2=Teamlink|last2=Australia|date=12 March 2019|publisher=Teamlink Australia Pty Limited|accessdate=12 March 2019|via=Google Books}}</ref> The Finnish newspapers frequently featured the invisible Finnish soldier, thus creating a hero of mythical proportions.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=yle>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110222064401/http://www.yle.fi/suuretsuomalaiset/100_suurinta/index.php?top100_id=74&nominee_id=0&place=0&gender=0&alive=0&province=0|title=Suuret Suomalaiset - 100 Suurinta suomalaista|date=22 February 2011|website=Web.archive.org|accessdate=12 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nH\u00e4yh\u00e4's division commander A. Svensson credited him with 219 confirmed sniper kills and an equal number of kills by [[submachine gun]], when he awarded him an honorary rifle on 17 February 1940. On 21 December 1939, he achieved his highest daily count of 25 kills.<ref>{{Citation|last=Simple History|title=Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4 'The White Death'  (World\u2019s Deadliest Sniper)|date=2018-02-15|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JOBxKnM9J2s|access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref> In his diary, military chaplain [[Antti Johannes Rantamaa|Antti Rantama]] reported 259 confirmed sniper kills and an equal number of kills by submachine gun from the beginning of the war until 7 March 1940, one day after H\u00e4yh\u00e4 was seriously wounded.<ref name=\"book\"/>\n\nSome of H\u00e4yh\u00e4's figures are from a Finnish Army document, counted from beginning of the war, 30 November 1939:\n* 22 December 1939: 138 sniper kills<ref>JR34:n toimintakertomus 30.11.39-1.12.40. SPK 1327. Finnish National Archive S\u00f6rn\u00e4inen; Alikersantista v\u00e4nrikiksi. Hurtti Ukko 1/1941</ref> in 22 days\n* 26 January 1940: 199 sniper kills<ref>Rantamaa, A. J. 1942. Parlamentin palkeilta Kollaanjoen kaltahille. WSOY, Porvoo. Pg. 84, 206</ref> (61 in 35 days)\n* 17 February 1940: 219 sniper kills<ref name=\"book\"/> (20 in 22 days)\n* 7 March 1940 (when H\u00e4yh\u00e4 was seriously wounded): total of 259 sniper kills<ref name=\"book\"/> (40 in 18 days)\n\nH\u00e4yh\u00e4 never discussed it publicly but his own private diary, discovered in 2017, shares a figure: he begins by stating that \"this is his sin list\", and estimates the total number shot by him to be around 500.<ref name=\"iltalehti\"/><ref name=\"kivimaki\"/> Historian Risto Marjomaa questions the large number, as confirmation of casualties was difficult.<ref name=\"marjomaa\">{{cite book |last1=Marjomaa |first1=Risto |title=Suomen kansallisbiografia 4 - Hirviluoto-Karjalainen |chapter=Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4 |date=2004 |publisher=Suomalaisen Kirjallisuuden Seura |url=http://biografiasampo.fi/henkilo/p2818 |accessdate=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nH\u00e4yh\u00e4 used his issued Civil Guard rifle, an early series [[SAKO]] [[Mosin\u2013Nagant#Finland|M/28-30]], serial number 35281, Civil Guard number S60974. It was a Finnish [[White Guard (Finland)|Civil Guard]] variant of the Mosin\u2013Nagant rifle known as \"Pystykorva\" (literally \"The Spitz\" due to the front sight's resemblance to the head of a [[spitz]]-type dog) chambered in the Finnish Mosin\u2013Nagant cartridge [[7.62\u00d753mmR|7.62\u00d753R]]. He preferred [[iron sights]] over [[telescopic sight]]s, as they enable a sniper to present a smaller target for the enemy (a sniper must raise his head a few centimeters higher when using a telescopic sight), can be relied on even in extreme cold, unlike telescopic sights which tend to cloud up in cold weather, and are easier to conceal: sunlight can reflect off a telescopic sight's lenses and reveal the sniper's position. H\u00e4yh\u00e4 also did not have prior training with scoped rifles, and therefore preferred not to switch to the Soviet scoped rifle (m/91-30 PE or PEM). He would frequently pack dense mounds of snow in front of his position to conceal himself, provide padding for his rifle, and reduce the characteristic puff of snow stirred up by the muzzle blast. He was known to keep snow in his mouth while sniping to prevent his breath in the cold air from giving away his position.<ref name=\"Stirling2012\">{{cite book |last=Stirling |first=Robert |title=Special Forces Sniper Skills |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gBGlAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA79 |date=20 December 2012 |publisher=Osprey Publishing |isbn=978-1-78096-003-6|pages=79\u201380}}</ref> H\u00e4yh\u00e4's diary discovered in 2017 also shares a story by him where they caught a Russian soldier, blindfolded him, spun him dizzy and took him to a party in the tent of [[Aarne Juutilainen|The Terror of Morocco]]. The Russian soldier was joyed by the carousing and was disgusted when he was sent back.<ref name=\"iltalehti\"/><ref name=\"kivimaki\">{{cite news|last1=Kivim\u00e4ki|first1=Petri|title=Tutkijan k\u00e4det alkoivat vapista \u2013 maailmankuulun sotalegendan Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4n muistelmat l\u00f6ytyiv\u00e4t sattumalta|url=https://yle.fi/uutiset/3-10113727|accessdate=14 March 2018|publisher=Yle.fi|date=14 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 March 1940, H\u00e4yh\u00e4 was hit in his lower left jaw by an [[explosive bullet]] fired by a Red Army soldier.<ref name=\"Saarelainen\">{{cite book |last= Saarelainen |first=Tapio |date=31 October 2016 |title= The White Sniper: Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=R948DQAAQBAJ&pg=PT42|publisher=Casemate |isbn= 9781612004297}}</ref> He was picked up by fellow soldiers who said that \"half his face was missing\". He regained consciousness on 13 March, the day that [[Moscow Peace Treaty|peace was declared]]. He read about his own death in the newspaper, and sent a letter to the paper to correct the misunderstanding.<ref name=\"muistikirja\"/> Shortly after the war, he was promoted from alikersantti (Corporal) to v\u00e4nrikki (Second lieutenant) by Finnish Field Marshal [[Carl Gustaf Emil Mannerheim]].<ref name=\"Feist2012\">{{cite book |last=Feist |first=Paul |title=The Redwood Stumper 2010: The Newsletter of the Redwood Gun Club, Arcata, CA |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5V_zSKwcLyUC&pg=PA36 |date=21 July 2012 |publisher=Redwood Gun Club |location=Arcata, CA |isbn=978-1-300-03973-0 |page=36 |chapter=The Winter War and a Winter Warrior}}</ref>\n\n==Later life==\n[[File:Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4's grave.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4's gravestone in Ruokolahti Church Graveyard, Karelia, Finland. The inscription reads: Home - Religion - Fatherland]]\nIt took several years for H\u00e4yh\u00e4 to recuperate from his wound. The bullet had crushed his jaw and removed most of his left cheek.<ref name=\"muistikirja\"/> Nonetheless, he made a full recovery and became a successful moose hunter and dog breeder after [[World War II]], and he even hunted with Finnish President [[Urho Kekkonen]].<ref name=\"Stirling2012\"/> However, he was also met with hate and even death threats.<ref name=muistikirja/> He spoke only sparsely about the war.<ref name=\"muistikirja\">{{cite news |last1=Silvander |first1=Lauri |title=Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4n muistikirja paljastaa tarkka-ampujan huumorintajun \u2013 \"Valkoinen kuolema\" esitt\u00e4\u00e4 n\u00e4kemyksens\u00e4 ammuttujen vihollisten lukum\u00e4\u00e4r\u00e4st\u00e4 |url=https://www.is.fi/suomi100/art-2000005409481.html |accessdate=19 August 2019 |publisher=Iltasanomat |date=14 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe was asked in 1998 how he had become such a good sniper: \"Practice.\" He was asked in 2002, just before his 96th birthday, if he regretted killing so many people. He replied, \"I only did what I was told to do, as well as I could.\" H\u00e4yh\u00e4 spent his last years in [[Ruokolahti]], a small municipality located in southeastern Finland near the Russian border.\n\nH\u00e4yh\u00e4 died in a war veterans' nursing home in [[Hamina]] in 2002 at age 96.<ref name=\"Feist2012\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://yle.fi/uutiset/ei_ne_osumat_vaan_se_asenne/6972008|title=Ei ne osumat, vaan se asenne|website=Yle.fi|accessdate=12 March 2019}}</ref> He was buried in [[Ruokolahti]].\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.mosinnagant.net/finland/simohayha.asp Meeting A Legend: Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4. Mosin\u2013Nagant.net 2002]\n* P. Sarjanen, ''{{lang|fi|Valkoinen kuolema}}''. {{ISBN|952-5170-05-5}}.\n* Tapio A. M. Saarelainen, ''{{lang|fi|Sankarikorpraali Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4}}''. {{ISBN|952-5026-52-3}}.\n* Tapio A. M. Saarelainen, ''{{lang|fi|The Sniper: Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4}}''. {{ISBN|978-952-5026-74-0}}.\n* [[William R. Trotter]], ''{{lang|en|Frozen Hell: The Russo-Finnish Winter War of 1939/40}}'', [[Algonquin Books]] of Chapel Hill, 2000. {{ISBN|978-0-945575-22-1}}.\n* [[Adrian Gilbert]], Tom C. McKenney, Dan Mills, [[Roger Moorhouse]], Charles Sasser, Tim Newark, ''{{lang|en|The Sniper Anthology: Snipers of the Second World War}}'', Pelican Publishing Company, 2012. {{ISBN|978-1-455616-82-4}}.\n{{WWIISniper}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:H\u00e4yh\u00e4, Simo}}\n[[Category:1905 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:Finnish military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Winter War]]\n[[Category:People from Rautj\u00e4rvi]]\n[[Category:People from Viipuri Province (Grand Duchy of Finland)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Cross of Liberty, 3rd Class]]\n[[Category:Finnish military snipers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Finnish combat sniper}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4\n| image         = Simo hayha honorary rifle.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| caption       = H\u00e4yh\u00e4 after being awarded the honorary rifle model 28.\n| nickname      = \"White Death\"\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1905|12|17|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Rautj\u00e4rvi]], [[Viipuri Province]], Finland, Russian Empire\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2002|04|01|1905|12|17|df=yes}}\n| death_place   = [[Hamina]], Finland\n| placeofburial = \n| allegiance    = {{flag|Finland}}\n| branch        = Finnish Army\n| serviceyears  = 1925\u20131940\n| rank          = Alikersantti (Corporal) during the [[Winter War]], promoted to V\u00e4nrikki (Second Lieutenant) shortly afterward<ref name=\"HS\">{{cite news |author=Lappalainen, Jukka-Pekka |title=Kollaa kesti, niin my\u00f6s Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4 |newspaper=Helsingin Sanomat |url=https://www.hs.fi/ihmiset/art-2000004016250.html |accessdate=19 February 2011 |location=Helsinki |date=6 December 2001 |url-access=subscription|language=Finnish |trans-title=The Kollaa held out, so did Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4 }}</ref>\n| unit          = \n| commands      = \n| battles       = Winter War\n* [[Battle of Kollaa]]\n| awards        = {{nowrap|[[Order of the Cross of Liberty|Cross of Liberty]], 3rd class and 4th class<br />[[Order of the Cross of Liberty|Medal of Liberty]], 1st class and 2nd class<br />Cross of Kollaa Battle<ref name=\"HS\" />}}\n| relations     = \n| laterwork     = \n}}\n\n'''Simo \"Simuna\" H\u00e4yh\u00e4''' ({{IPA-fi|\u02c8simo \u02c8h\u00e6y\u032fh\u00e6}}; 17 December 1905&nbsp;\u2013 1 April 2002), was a [[Finland|Finnish]] [[sniper]]. He is believed to have killed over 500 men during the 1939\u201340 [[Winter War]], the highest number of [[List of snipers|sniper kills]] in any major war. He used a Finnish-produced [[Mosin\u2013Nagant#Finland|M/28-30]] rifle, a variant of the Mosin\u2013Nagant rifle, and a [[Suomi KP/-31]] sub machine gun.<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite news |author=Rayment, Sean |title=The long view |work=The Daily Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1517044/The-long-view.html |accessdate=30 March 2009 |location=London |date=30 April 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Saarelainen, Taipo |title=The White Death: History's Deadliest Sniper |work=Forces Network |url=https://www.forces.net/news/tri-service/white-death-historys-deadliest-sniper |location= |date=15 November 2016}}</ref><ref>Tapio A.M. Saarelainen: Sankarikorpraali Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4 (2006)</ref> His unit's captain Antti Rantamaa credited him with 259 confirmed kills by sniper rifle and an equal number of kills by sub machine gun during the Winter War. Later in his book, Rantamaa credited Simo with 542 sniper kills.<ref name=\"book\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R948DQAAQBAJ&pg=PT35&dq=simo+hayha+219+kills&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjAr_bR0frSAhXGwLwKHRBhAzgQ6AEIKjAC#v=onepage&q=simo+hayha+219+kills&f=false|title=The White Sniper|first=Tapio|last=Saarelainen|date=31 October 2016|publisher=Casemate|accessdate=12 March 2019|via=Google Books}}</ref> H\u00e4yh\u00e4 never talked about it publicly but estimated in his private diary that he shot around 500.<ref name=\"iltalehti\">{{cite news |author=Kauppinen, Kari |title=Sotasankari Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4n ennenn\u00e4kem\u00e4t\u00f6n p\u00e4iv\u00e4kirja l\u00f6ytyi - \"T\u00e4ss\u00e4 on minun syntilistani\" |newspaper=Iltalehti|url=http://www.iltalehti.fi/kotimaa/201707172200270836_u0.shtml |accessdate=18 July 2017 |location=Helsinki |date=18 July 2017 |language=Finnish}}</ref><ref name=\"kivimaki\"/>\n\n==Early life==\nH\u00e4yh\u00e4 was born in the municipality of [[Rautj\u00e4rvi]] in the [[Viipuri Province]] of southern Finland near the border with Russia. He was the second youngest of eight children in a Lutheran family of farmers.<ref>[https://www.geni.com/people/Simo-H\u00e4yh\u00e4/6000000042734553943 About Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4]</ref> He was a farmer, hunter, and skier prior to his military service. He joined the Finnish voluntary militia [[White Guard (Finland)|White Guard]] (''Suojeluskunta'') at age 20, and he was successful in shooting competitions in the Viipuri Province. His home was reportedly full of trophies for marksmanship.<ref>{{cite book |last=Gilbert |first=Adrian |year=1996 |title=Sniper: The Skills, the Weapons, and the Experiences |publisher=St. Martin's Press |isbn=0-312-95766-1 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/sniperskillsweap00gilb/page/88 88] |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/sniperskillsweap00gilb/page/88 }}</ref> He was not keen to hog the spotlight, and correspondingly in the photos of his younger years he usually stood at the very back in group photos, until his later success started to force him to take center place.<ref name=\"muistikirja\"/>\n\n==Winter War service==\n[[File:Simo hayha second lieutenant 1940.png|thumb|right|H\u00e4yh\u00e4 in the 1940s, with visible damage to his left cheek after his 1940 wound]]\nH\u00e4yh\u00e4 served as a sniper for the [[Finnish Army]] during the 1939\u201340 [[Winter War]] between Finland and the Soviet Union. He was in the 6th Company of JR&nbsp;34 during the [[Battle of Kollaa]] in temperatures between {{convert|-40|\u00b0C}} and {{convert|-20|\u00b0C}}. H\u00e4yh\u00e4 was dressed completely in white camouflage; Soviet troops were not issued with white camouflage uniforms for most of the war, making them easily visible to snipers in winter conditions. [[Joseph Stalin]] [[Great Purge|had purged military experts]] in the late 1930s, and the Red Army was consequently highly disorganized.<ref>[pp. 145\u2013146 The Winter War: The Russo\u2013Finnish War of 1939\u201340 by William R. Trotter, Workman Publishing Company, New York (Aurum Press, London), 2002, First published 1991 in the United States under the title ''A Frozen Hell: The Russo\u2013Finnish Winter War of 1939\u201340'']</ref>\n\nAll of H\u00e4yh\u00e4's kills were accomplished in fewer than 100 days, an average of five per day at a time of year with very few daylight hours.<ref name=\"Jowett2006\">{{cite book |last=Jowett |first=Philip S. |title=Finland at War, 1939\u201345 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p58vtOKyVy8C |year=2006 |publisher=Osprey Publishing |isbn=978-1-84176-969-1 |pages=44\u201345}}</ref><ref name=\"Pegler2006\">{{cite book |last=Pegler |first=Martin |title=Out of Nowhere: A History of the Military Sniper |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-mkh931pIugC |year=2006 |publisher=Osprey Publishing |isbn=978-1-84603-140-3 |page=167}}</ref><ref name=\"FareySpicer2009\">{{cite book |last1=Farey |first1=Pat |last2=Spicer |first2=Mark |title=Sniping: An Illustrated History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l1a-kB-1MMAC|date=5 May 2009 |publisher=Zenith Press |isbn=978-0-7603-3717-2 |pages=117\u2013118}}</ref> A sniper's kill-count was based on the sniper himself, with the confirmation of his comrades, and only those who were killed for certain are considered. No count was taken when several snipers shot at the same target. Men killed with a submachine gun by a group leader were not counted.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.is.fi/kotimaa/art-2000000854160.html|title=Tarkka-ampuja Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4 ei koskaan saanut Mannerheim-risti\u00e4 - \"Harkitaan\"|first1=Timo|last1=Myllyniemi|first2=Tuomas|last2=Manninen|date=25 December 2014|website=Ilta-Sanomat|accessdate=12 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nFinnish sources describe that he was nicknamed \"''White Death''\" ({{lang-ru|\u0411\u0435\u043b\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0442\u044c}}, {{transl|ru|''Belaja smert''}}; {{lang-fi|valkoinen kuolema}}; {{lang-sv|den vita d\u00f6den}}) by the [[Red Army]].<ref name=\"book\"/> During the war, the \"White death\" was one of the leading themes of Finnish propaganda.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rdIgAQAAIAAJ|title=Journal of Information Warfare|first1=Edith Cowan University School of Management Information|last1=Systems|first2=Teamlink|last2=Australia|date=12 March 2019|publisher=Teamlink Australia Pty Limited|accessdate=12 March 2019|via=Google Books}}</ref> The Finnish newspapers frequently featured the invisible Finnish soldier, thus creating a hero of mythical proportions.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=yle>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110222064401/http://www.yle.fi/suuretsuomalaiset/100_suurinta/index.php?top100_id=74&nominee_id=0&place=0&gender=0&alive=0&province=0|title=Suuret Suomalaiset - 100 Suurinta suomalaista|date=22 February 2011|website=Web.archive.org|accessdate=12 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nH\u00e4yh\u00e4's division commander A. Svensson credited him with 219 confirmed sniper kills and an equal number of kills by [[submachine gun]], when he awarded him an honorary rifle on 17 February 1940. On 21 December 1939, he achieved his highest daily count of 25 kills.<ref>{{Citation|last=Simple History|title=Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4 'The White Death'  (World\u2019s Deadliest Sniper)|date=2018-02-15|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JOBxKnM9J2s|access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref> In his diary, military chaplain [[Antti Johannes Rantamaa|Antti Rantama]] reported 259 confirmed sniper kills and an equal number of kills by submachine gun from the beginning of the war until 7 March 1940, one day after H\u00e4yh\u00e4 was seriously wounded.<ref name=\"book\"/>\n\nSome of H\u00e4yh\u00e4's figures are from a Finnish Army document, counted from beginning of the war, 30 November 1939:\n* 22 December 1939: 138 sniper kills<ref>JR34:n toimintakertomus 30.11.39-1.12.40. SPK 1327. Finnish National Archive S\u00f6rn\u00e4inen; Alikersantista v\u00e4nrikiksi. Hurtti Ukko 1/1941</ref> in 22 days\n* 26 January 1940: 199 sniper kills<ref>Rantamaa, A. J. 1942. Parlamentin palkeilta Kollaanjoen kaltahille. WSOY, Porvoo. Pg. 84, 206</ref> (61 in 35 days)\n* 17 February 1940: 219 sniper kills<ref name=\"book\"/> (20 in 22 days)\n* 7 March 1940 (when H\u00e4yh\u00e4 was seriously wounded): total of 259 sniper kills<ref name=\"book\"/> (40 in 18 days)\n\nH\u00e4yh\u00e4 never discussed it publicly but his own private diary, discovered in 2017, shares a figure: he begins by stating that \"this is his sin list\", and estimates the total number shot by him to be around 500.<ref name=\"iltalehti\"/><ref name=\"kivimaki\"/> Historian Risto Marjomaa questions the large number, as confirmation of casualties was difficult.<ref name=\"marjomaa\">{{cite book |last1=Marjomaa |first1=Risto |title=Suomen kansallisbiografia 4 - Hirviluoto-Karjalainen |chapter=Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4 |date=2004 |publisher=Suomalaisen Kirjallisuuden Seura |url=http://biografiasampo.fi/henkilo/p2818 |accessdate=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nH\u00e4yh\u00e4 used his issued Civil Guard rifle, an early series [[SAKO]] [[Mosin\u2013Nagant#Finland|M/28-30]], serial number 35281, Civil Guard number S60974. It was a Finnish [[White Guard (Finland)|Civil Guard]] variant of the Mosin\u2013Nagant rifle known as \"Pystykorva\" (literally \"The Spitz\" due to the front sight's resemblance to the head of a [[spitz]]-type dog) chambered in the Finnish Mosin\u2013Nagant cartridge [[7.62\u00d753mmR|7.62\u00d753R]]. He preferred [[iron sights]] over [[telescopic sight]]s, as they enable a sniper to present a smaller target for the enemy (a sniper must raise his head a few centimeters higher when using a telescopic sight), can be relied on even in extreme cold, unlike telescopic sights which tend to cloud up in cold weather, and are easier to conceal: sunlight can reflect off a telescopic sight's lenses and reveal the sniper's position. H\u00e4yh\u00e4 also did not have prior training with scoped rifles, and therefore preferred not to switch to the Soviet scoped rifle (m/91-30 PE or PEM). He would frequently pack dense mounds of snow in front of his position to conceal himself, provide padding for his rifle, and reduce the characteristic puff of snow stirred up by the muzzle blast. He was known to keep snow in his mouth while sniping to prevent his breath in the cold air from giving away his position.<ref name=\"Stirling2012\">{{cite book |last=Stirling |first=Robert |title=Special Forces Sniper Skills |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gBGlAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA79 |date=20 December 2012 |publisher=Osprey Publishing |isbn=978-1-78096-003-6|pages=79\u201380}}</ref> H\u00e4yh\u00e4's diary discovered in 2017 also shares a story by him where they caught a Russian soldier, blindfolded him, spun him dizzy and took him to a party in the tent of [[Aarne Juutilainen|The Terror of Morocco]]. The Russian soldier was joyed by the carousing and was disgusted when he was sent back.<ref name=\"iltalehti\"/><ref name=\"kivimaki\">{{cite news|last1=Kivim\u00e4ki|first1=Petri|title=Tutkijan k\u00e4det alkoivat vapista \u2013 maailmankuulun sotalegendan Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4n muistelmat l\u00f6ytyiv\u00e4t sattumalta|url=https://yle.fi/uutiset/3-10113727|accessdate=14 March 2018|publisher=Yle.fi|date=14 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 March 1940, H\u00e4yh\u00e4 was hit in his lower left jaw by an [[explosive bullet]] fired by a Red Army soldier.<ref name=\"Saarelainen\">{{cite book |last= Saarelainen |first=Tapio |date=31 October 2016 |title= The White Sniper: Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=R948DQAAQBAJ&pg=PT42|publisher=Casemate |isbn= 9781612004297}}</ref> He was picked up by fellow soldiers who said that \"half his face was missing\". He regained consciousness on 13 March, the day that [[Moscow Peace Treaty|peace was declared]]. He read about his own death in the newspaper, and sent a letter to the paper to correct the misunderstanding.<ref name=\"muistikirja\"/> Shortly after the war, he was promoted from alikersantti (Corporal) to v\u00e4nrikki (Second lieutenant) by Finnish Field Marshal [[Carl Gustaf Emil Mannerheim]].<ref name=\"Feist2012\">{{cite book |last=Feist |first=Paul |title=The Redwood Stumper 2010: The Newsletter of the Redwood Gun Club, Arcata, CA |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5V_zSKwcLyUC&pg=PA36 |date=21 July 2012 |publisher=Redwood Gun Club |location=Arcata, CA |isbn=978-1-300-03973-0 |page=36 |chapter=The Winter War and a Winter Warrior}}</ref>\n\n==Later life==\n[[File:Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4's grave.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4's gravestone in Ruokolahti Church Graveyard, Karelia, Finland. The inscription reads: Home - Religion - Fatherland]]\nIt took several years for H\u00e4yh\u00e4 to recuperate from his wound. The bullet had crushed his jaw and removed most of his left cheek.<ref name=\"muistikirja\"/> Nonetheless, he made a full recovery and became a successful moose hunter and dog breeder after [[World War II]], and he even hunted with Finnish President [[Urho Kekkonen]].<ref name=\"Stirling2012\"/> However, he was also met with hate and even death threats.<ref name=muistikirja/> He spoke only sparsely about the war.<ref name=\"muistikirja\">{{cite news |last1=Silvander |first1=Lauri |title=Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4n muistikirja paljastaa tarkka-ampujan huumorintajun \u2013 \"Valkoinen kuolema\" esitt\u00e4\u00e4 n\u00e4kemyksens\u00e4 ammuttujen vihollisten lukum\u00e4\u00e4r\u00e4st\u00e4 |url=https://www.is.fi/suomi100/art-2000005409481.html |accessdate=19 August 2019 |publisher=Iltasanomat |date=14 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe was asked in 1998 how he had become such a good sniper: \"Practice.\" He was asked in 2002, just before his 96th birthday, if he regretted killing so many people. He replied, \"I only did what I was told to do, as well as I could.\" H\u00e4yh\u00e4 spent his last years in [[Ruokolahti]], a small municipality located in southeastern Finland near the Russian border.\n\nH\u00e4yh\u00e4 died in a war veterans' nursing home in [[Hamina]] in 2002 at age 96.<ref name=\"Feist2012\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://yle.fi/uutiset/ei_ne_osumat_vaan_se_asenne/6972008|title=Ei ne osumat, vaan se asenne|website=Yle.fi|accessdate=12 March 2019}}</ref> He was buried in [[Ruokolahti]].\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.mosinnagant.net/finland/simohayha.asp Meeting A Legend: Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4. Mosin\u2013Nagant.net 2002]\n* P. Sarjanen, ''{{lang|fi|Valkoinen kuolema}}''. {{ISBN|952-5170-05-5}}.\n* Tapio A. M. Saarelainen, ''{{lang|fi|Sankarikorpraali Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4}}''. {{ISBN|952-5026-52-3}}.\n* Tapio A. M. Saarelainen, ''{{lang|fi|The Sniper: Simo H\u00e4yh\u00e4}}''. {{ISBN|978-952-5026-74-0}}.\n* [[William R. Trotter]], ''{{lang|en|Frozen Hell: The Russo-Finnish Winter War of 1939/40}}'', [[Algonquin Books]] of Chapel Hill, 2000. {{ISBN|978-0-945575-22-1}}.\n* [[Adrian Gilbert]], Tom C. McKenney, Dan Mills, [[Roger Moorhouse]], Charles Sasser, Tim Newark, ''{{lang|en|The Sniper Anthology: Snipers of the Second World War}}'', Pelican Publishing Company, 2012. {{ISBN|978-1-455616-82-4}}.\n{{WWIISniper}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:H\u00e4yh\u00e4, Simo}}\n[[Category:1905 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:Finnish military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Winter War]]\n[[Category:People from Rautj\u00e4rvi]]\n[[Category:People from Viipuri Province (Grand Duchy of Finland)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Cross of Liberty, 3rd Class]]\n[[Category:Finnish military snipers]]\n", "name_user": "Barry Goldwater", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simo_H%C3%A4yh%C3%A4"}
