=\"2\" | Totals\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 49,854 \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 3,264 \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 53,118\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 100\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" |{{center|Sources:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ct.gov/sots/lib/sots/electionservices/registration_and_enrollment_stats/nov16r&e.pdf|title=Registration and Party Enrollment Statistics|date=November 1, 2016|website=ct.gov|publisher=Connecticut Secretary of the State|access-date=March 30, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170220021326/http://www.ct.gov/sots/lib/sots/electionservices/registration_and_enrollment_stats/nov16r%26e.pdf|archive-date=February 20, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===Districts===\nThe City of Norwalk currently has six taxing districts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Norwalk Tax District Map|url=http://www.norwalkct.org/DocumentCenter/View/4745|website=City of Norwalk|publisher=Government Websites by CivicPlus|accessdate=March 27, 2017}}</ref> The First, Second, Third and Sixth taxing districts are political entities with their respective voters electing officers, holding annual business meetings, approving budgets and to consider other matters, as specified in each of their charters.<ref>{{cite web|title=SPECIAL DISTRICT GOVERNMENTS|url=https://www2.census.gov/govs/cog/2007/ct.pdf|website=United States Census Bureau|publisher=U.S. Department of Commerce|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=SPECIAL TAXING DISTRICTS|url=https://www.cga.ct.gov/2011/rpt/2011-R-0347.htm|website=Connecticut General Assembly|publisher=Connecticut General Assembly|accessdate=March 23, 2017}}</ref> Election of Taxing District Commissioners and Treasurers by voters from the 1st, 2nd, 3rd, and 6th districts take place in odd numbered years.\n\nThe Fourth and Fifth districts are not counted as separate governments as they constitute the city proper.<ref>{{cite web|title=proper: see def #5|url=http://www.thefreedictionary.com/proper|website=The Free Dictionary|publisher=Farlex|accessdate=March 28, 2017}}</ref> Each taxing district has its own [[Property tax in the United States|property tax]] rate reflecting the mix of services each receives from the city.\nSecondly, municipal elections of Mayor, Common Council, Board of Education and other positions are also held in odd numbered years at thirteen polling places within five [[Electoral district|voting districts]] around the city.\n\nVoting districts are not the same for state and federal elections which are held on even numbered years at twelve polling locations.<ref>{{cite web|title=Where Do I Vote?|url=http://www.norwalkct.org/346/Where-Do-I-Vote|website=City of Norwalk|publisher=Government Websites by CivicPlus|accessdate=March 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Municipal====\n[[File:NorwalkCTCityHallFront09032007.JPG|upright=1.1|thumb|Norwalk City Hall and Concert Hall]]\nNorwalk's municipal government is a [[Mayor-Council|weak-mayor form]] of a [[mayor-council government]] with the mayor of Norwalk elected by its voters.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nlc.org/build-skills-and-networks/resources/cities-101/city-structures/forms-of-municipal-government | title=Forms of Municipal Government | publisher=National League of Cities | date=2013 | accessdate=March 23, 2016}}</ref>  The city's charter gives certain administrative powers exclusively to the Council and others jointly to the Council and Mayor. The Common Council is the law-writing body of the City of Norwalk.  Norwalk's [[city council|common council]] consists of fifteen council members, five elected [[at-large]] and ten elected [[Electoral district|by district]], two from each district.<ref>{{cite web|title=Common Council|url=http://www.norwalkct.org/286/Common-Council|website=Norwalk, the Sound of Connecticut|publisher=City of Norwalk|accessdate=March 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Representatives ===\nNorwalk is represented in the [[Connecticut General Assembly]] by five House Representatives corresponding to five Connecticut legislative districts and one senator from one Connecticut Senate district.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.norwalkct.org/DocumentCenter/View/3548 | title=State/Federal Voting Districts | publisher=City of Norwalk, Connecticut | work=Where Do I Vote? | date=November 30, 2011 | accessdate=March 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.senatedems.ct.gov/find/findlegislator.asp | title=Find Your Connecticut State Senator | publisher=Connecticut Senate Democrats | date=2016 | accessdate=March 24, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160321215035/http://www.senatedems.ct.gov/find/findlegislator.asp | archive-date=March 21, 2016 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nNorwalk, which lies within [[Connecticut's 4th congressional district]], is represented in the [[United States Congress]] by one congressional representative (Democrat [[Jim Himes]]) in the [[United States House of Representatives]] and, along with the rest of Connecticut, by two U.S. Senators (Democrats [[Richard Blumenthal]] and [[Chris Murphy]]) in the [[United States Senate]].\n\n==Education==\n{{main|Education in Norwalk, Connecticut}}\n[[Norwalk Public Schools]] operates public schools, while the community also has various private schools.\n\nNorwalk was granted a town charter by the [[Connecticut General Assembly|Connecticut General Court]] in 1651. On May 29, 1678, town records mention the establishment of community-supported teaching activities with a passage that reads:\n\"'At a town meeting... voted and agreed to hier a scole master to teach all the children in ye town to lerne to Rede and write; and that Mr. Cornish shall be hierd for that service and the townsmen are to hier him upon as reasonable terms as they can.\"\n\nThe school that was established in the 1670s was located near the Ludlow Square area of [[East Norwalk]] (near the former Roger Ludlow Junior High School).<ref name=\"beard\">{{cite journal|title=Norwalk's Old Schoolhouse|last=Beard|first=Patten|journal=Connecticut Circle Magazine|date=September 1954|url=http://www.norwalkhistoricalsociety.org/Schoolhouse1.html|access-date=February 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170705152336/http://www.norwalkhistoricalsociety.org/Schoolhouse1.html|archive-date=July 5, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Sports==\n[[Baseball]] and [[softball]] are popular amateur sports with active leagues across many age groups in Norwalk. There are four baseball fields and 16 [[Little League Baseball|Little League]] fields in the city.  Several of the fields, including [[Calf Pasture Beach]]  are illuminated for nighttime play. The fields at The Norwalk Little League team won the [[Little League World Series]] in [[1952 Little League World Series|1952]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.littleleague.org/series/history/divisions/llbbhistory.htm|title=Little League Baseball|accessdate=September 6, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071017034525/http://www.littleleague.org/series/history/divisions/llbbhistory.htm|archivedate=October 17, 2007|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.norwalkct.org/parksrec/NorwalkParkFacilities.pdf|format=PDF|title=Norwalk Park Facilities|accessdate=September 6, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081029193221/http://www.norwalkct.org/parksrec/NorwalkParkFacilities.pdf|archivedate=October 29, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\nThe 14-year-old Babe Ruth League team won the championship in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://brlworldseries.com/default.php?do=Tournament&id=8 |title=Babe Ruth World Series |accessdate=September 6, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080919081338/http://www.brlworldseries.com/default.php?do=Tournament&id=8 |archivedate=September 19, 2008 }}</ref>\nIn 2010, the 12-year-old Norwalk all-star team made it to the Cal Ripken league World Series and placed third in the country.  In 2011, the Norwalk American Senior Legion baseball team won the Connecticut State Championship. This had not been accomplished by any other Norwalk Legion team in the storied 83-year history. The team defeated Branford, Connecticut in the championship game. The girls' Norwalk Pride fast pitch softball team won the Connecticut State Championship in 2005, 2006, and 2007.\n\nThe Norwalk Biddy Basketball All-Star team Won the State and Regional titles and then went on to the World Championships in New Orleans, Louisiana in 1986 and placed 7th in the world.\n\nBeing a coastal city Norwalk is home to a great many water sports including [[competitive swimming]], recreational [[boating]] and [[fishing]], [[sailing]], [[windsurfing]], and [[kayaking]]. The [[Norwalk River]] and inner [[Norwalk Harbor]] host [[Rowing (sport)|rowing]] events and organizations.<ref name=\"rowing\">{{cite web|url=http://www.norwalkriverrowing.org/ |title=The Norwalk River Rowing Association |accessdate=September 6, 2008}} and the {{cite web|url=http://www.newcanaancrew.com/|title=New Canaan Crew|accessdate=September 6, 2008}} are two such rowing organizations.</ref>\n\nNorwalk resident [[Daniel Walsh (rower)|Daniel Walsh]] won a [[bronze medal]] in Beijing\nwith the U.S. Olympic rowing team in the [[2008 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"hine\">{{cite journal|title=Summer Bronze: Norwalk's Walsh Garners Olympic Medal |last=Hine |first=Tommy |journal=Norwalk Citizen~News |volume=12 |issue=34 |pages=A1, A15 |date=August 22, 2008 |url=http://www.norwalkcitizen-news.com/topstories/ci_10297724 |accessdate=August 27, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080915174056/http://www.norwalkcitizen-news.com/topstories/ci_10297724 |archivedate=September 15, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThere are three golf courses in the city of Norwalk: the Shorehaven Golf Club<ref>{{cite web|title=Shorehaven Golf Club|url=http://www.shorehavengc.org/Home|website=Shorehaven Golf Club|publisher=Jonas Club Software|accessdate=May 31, 2017}}</ref> is a private club in East Norwalk, the Silvermine Golf Club<ref>{{cite web|title=Silvermine Golf Club|url=http://www.silverminegolf.com/|website=Silvermine Golf Club|publisher=Silvermine Golf Club|accessdate=May 31, 2017}}</ref> is a private club in Silvermine (part of the course lies in the town of Wilton), and the Oak Hills Park golf course<ref>{{cite web|title=Oak Hills Park Golf Course|url=https://www.oakhillsgc.com/|website=Oak Hills Park Golf Course|publisher=1-2-1 Marketing|accessdate=May 31, 2017}}</ref> is a public course in West Norwalk.\n\nThe cross-town rivalry between the city's two largest high schools, [[Norwalk High School (Connecticut)|Norwalk High School]] and [[Brien McMahon High School]], is fierce, particularly for the [[American football|football]], basketball, [[soccer]] and [[field hockey]] teams in the fall; as well as [[lacrosse]], [[baseball]], and [[softball]] teams in the spring. [[Brien McMahon High School]]'s football\nteam won the FCIAC (Fairfield County Interscholastic Athletic Conference) and Class M State Football championship in 1994. McMahon High School's boys' lacrosse team won the state division 2 lacrosse championship in 2000.\n\nIn professional team sports, Norwalk is represented by the [[Connecticut Wildcats]] in the [[American National Rugby League]].\n\n==Media==\nNews sources in Norwalk include [[News 12 Networks|News 12 Connecticut]], a regional news channel for southwestern Connecticut and based in Norwalk.<ref>{{cite web|title=Contact Us|url=http://connecticut.news12.com/news/contact-us-1.3991806|website=News 12 Connecticut|accessdate=February 24, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224213427/http://connecticut.news12.com/news/contact-us-1.3991806|archive-date=February 24, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''[[The Hour (newspaper)|The Hour]]'' was an independent daily newspaper based in Norwalk and founded in 1871, which was purchased by [[Hearst Communications]] on April 12, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn93053878/|title=About The evening hour. (Norwalk, CT) 1895-190? \u00ab Chronicling America \u00ab Library of Congress|publisher=Chroniclingamerica.loc.gov|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref>  NancyonNorwalk.com is a self-published, nonprofit news site founded in 2010 that covers local issues.<ref>{{cite web | last = Ferentinos | first = Leah | title = Yale Law Group Steps Up to Defend NancyonNorwalk | publisher = The Hour | date = April 7, 2019  | url = https://www.thehour.com/opinion/article/Yale-law-group-steps-up-to-defend-NancyonNorwalk-13745109.php}}</ref>\n\n==Infrastructure==\n=== Transportation ===\n[[File:NorwalkTransitGillig.jpg|thumb|A Wheels bus at Wheels hub]]\n[[Public transport bus service]] within Norwalk is provided by [[Norwalk Transit District]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.norwalktransit.com/|title=Home|website=Norwalk Transit District|language=en-US|access-date=June 9, 2017}}</ref>  Norwalk Transit District operates fixed route public bus service in Norwalk and [[Westport, Connecticut|Westport]] with evening and Sunday shuttles (serving South Norwalk, Main Avenue and Connecticut Avenue) and commuter shuttles.  Access to other cities through bus services [[Milford, Connecticut|Milford]], [[Danbury, Connecticut|Danbury]], and Stamford. All fixed route buses meet at the Transportation Hub.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.norwalktransit.com/services/|title=Services|website=Norwalk Transit District|language=en-US|access-date=June 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:SouthNorwalkRRstaWestEntrance08112007.jpg|thumb|West entrance of the [[South Norwalk (Metro-North station)|South Norwalk train station]]]]\nThe [[Metro-North Railroad]]'s [[New Haven Line]] runs through and stops in Norwalk. The train goes West and East with [[Grand Central Terminal]] and [[New Haven Union Station]] being the final stops. The [[Danbury Branch]] runs from South Norwalk to [[Danbury, Connecticut|Danbury, CT]]. There are four stations in Norwalk, three of them on the main line which is: [[Rowayton (Metro-North station)|Rowayton]], [[South Norwalk (Metro-North station)|South Norwalk]] and [[East Norwalk (Metro-North station)|East Norwalk]]. The fourth station, [[Merritt 7 (Metro-North station)|Merritt 7]], is on the Danbury Branch. Metro-North provides [[Commuter rail|commuter]] service for all four stations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mnr/html/mnrmap.htm|title=MNR Map|last=|first=|date=|website=MTA|publisher=|access-date=March 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe structure at 47 Wall Street was formerly the Wall Street station of the Danbury Branch, which operated from 1896 to 1936. The city's [[Tram|trolley]] system barn also operated on Wall Street.<ref>{{cite web | last=Koch | first=Robert | title=A brief history of the train station that once served Wall Street | website=The Hour | date=September 19, 2016 | url=https://www.thehour.com/news/article/A-brief-history-of-the-train-station-that-once-9231874.php | access-date=December 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Interstate 95 in Connecticut|Interstate 95]] and the [[Merritt Parkway]] lead through Norwalk, and there are several exits within the Norwalk city limits, and are the major thoroughfare through the city. [[U.S. Route 1 in Connecticut|U.S. Route 1]] goes through the center of the city, mostly following local streets. The major north-south corridor in Norwalk is [[U.S. Route 7 in Connecticut|U.S. Route 7]], which is a expressway throughout most of the route in the city. The expressway section ends at Grist Mill Road in Norwalk from where Route 7 resumes northbound along Main Ave.  Other state routes include [[Connecticut Route 53|Route 53]], [[Connecticut Route 123|Route 123]], and [[Connecticut Route 136|Route 136]].\n\n=== Utilities ===\nElectric power and natural gas in most of Norwalk is provided by [[Eversource Energy]].\n* The First Taxing District<ref>{{cite web | url=http://firstdistrictwater.org/ | title=First District Water Department | date=2010 | accessdate=March 10, 2016}}</ref> provides water to the Third, Fourth and Fifth Taxing Districts.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.norwalkct.org/DocumentCenter/View/4745 | title=Norwalk Tax District Map | accessdate=March 10, 2016}}</ref>\n* The Second Taxing District<ref name=\"secondtaxingdistrict.com\">{{cite web | url=http://www.secondtaxingdistrict.com/about.htm | title=Second Taxing District of the City of Norwalk, Connecticut | accessdate=March 10, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306132649/http://www.secondtaxingdistrict.com/about.htm | archive-date=March 6, 2016 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> serves sections of South Norwalk, East Norwalk, West Norwalk, Rowayton and Silvermine.<ref name=\"secondtaxingdistrict.com\" /> and also owns and operates South Norwalk Electric and Water.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.snew.org/ | title=South Norwalk Electric and Water | accessdate=March 10, 2016}}</ref>\n* The Third Taxing District<ref>{{cite web | url=http://ttd.gov/ | title=Third Taxing District | publisher=JumarMarketing, LLC | date=2016 | accessdate=March 10, 2016}}</ref> provides electric power for East Norwalk.\nThe districts purchase wholesale power and arrange for its delivery to, and distribution within, their respective districts.  Power lines and meters in [[East Norwalk]], [[South Norwalk]], and parts of [[Rowayton]] are maintained by the districts. Both the second (SNEW) and third (TTD) district electric departments belong to the six member Connecticut Municipal Electric Energy Cooperative which pools their wholesale power purchasing to obtain lower rates for their customers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmeec.com/|title=CMEEC|accessdate=September 29, 2008}}</ref>\n\nConnecticut Light and Power (now Eversource Energy) operated a power plant, Norwalk Harbor Station on [[Manresa Island]], from 1960 to 1999 when it was acquired by [[NRG Energy]], which then began its deactivation in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rivard|first1=Nicole|title=NRG to deactivate Norwalk power plant|url=http://www.ctpost.com/news/article/NRG-to-deactivate-Norwalk-power-plant-4547795.php|website=ctpost|publisher=Hearst Media Services Connecticut, LLC|accessdate=May 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004 the third taxing district installed 3 diesel powered generators at the Norden complex on Norden Place that were initially licensed only for emergency power supply. By summer 2008 the generators, with a combined capacity of 6 Megawatts, had been upgraded to allow licensed operation as regular power providers for the grid (not just emergency power).<ref name=\"ttd_7_8\">{{cite journal|journal=Inside Your Third; the Newsletter for Norwalk's Third Taxing District |title=TTD Commission Invests in Norden Generators to Help to Control Electricity Prices|volume=7|issue=8|date=August 2008|page=pg. 1}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007 and 2008 the construction of the [[Middletown-Norwalk transmission line]] disrupted traffic along the Boston Post Road, but the completion of the line is hoped to help provide additional power to lower Fairfield County.  In addition a high-voltage undersea line runs from Manressa Island to Long Island to help provide electric power to [[Long Island Power Authority]] customers.  In 2008 the city government of Norwalk started initial investigations of whether the city might resume generating power for sale to electricity customers in the city.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Koch|first1=Robert|title=Power panel looking to fulfill a unique request|url=http://www.thehour.com/norwalk/article/Power-panel-looking-to-fulfill-a-unique-request-8262982.php|accessdate=May 31, 2017|work=The Hour|publisher=Hearst Media Services Connecticut, LLC|date=July 26, 2008}}</ref>\n\n=== Emergency services ===\n{{See also|Norwalk Fire Department}}\nNorwalk Police Department serves as the city's [[police department]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.norwalkct.org/index.aspx?nid=139 | title=Norwalk Police Department | publisher=CivicPlus | date=2016 | accessdate=May 18, 2016}}</ref> and Norwalk Fire Department serves Norwalk's fire protection district.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.norwalkct.org/index.aspx?nid=63 | title=Norwalk Fire Department | publisher=Civic Plus | date=2016 | accessdate=May 18, 2016}}</ref> Norwalk is served 24/7 by [[Norwalk Hospital]] and Norwalk Hospital EMS, a 911 paramedic service. The service consists of hospital-based paramedics and EMT-Is who serve Norwalk as well as New Canaan, Wilton, Weston, and Westport.\n\n==Notable people==\n{{Main|List of people from Norwalk, Connecticut}}\nNotable people from Norwalk include:\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Charli D'Amelio]], [[TikToker]] and social media personality<ref>{{cite web|title=Popular Norwalk Tik Tok icon uses star power for good|url=https://www.thehour.com/entertainment/article/Norwalk-Tik-Tok-star-amasses-millions-of-followers-14913464.php|website=The Hour|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[A. Scott Berg]], biographer<ref>{{cite web|title=Happy Birthday to Norwalk's A. Scott Berg|url=http://norwalk.dailyvoice.com/neighbors/happy-birthday-to-norwalks-a-scott-berg/510164/|website=Norwalk Daily Voice|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[D. J. Caruso|D.J. Caruso]], film director<ref>{{cite web|title=Happy Birthday to Norwalk's D.J. Caruso|url=http://norwalk.dailyvoice.com/neighbors/happy-birthday-to-norwalks-dj-caruso/563947/|website=Norwalk Daily Voice|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Johnny Gruelle]], artist and author<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lake|first1=Leslie|title=A Norwalk creation, Raggedy Ann & Andy celebrated at Library|url=http://www.thehour.com/news/article/A-Norwalk-creation-Raggedy-Ann-Andy-celebrated-8238927.php|website=The Hour|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref> \n* [[B. Kliban]], cartoonist<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/08/14/obituaries/b-kliban-55-a-cartoonist-who-drew-zany-cats.html | title=B. Kliban, 55, a Cartoonist Who Drew Zany Cats | work=The New York Times | date=August 14, 1990 | accessdate=February 24, 2017 | author=Flint, Peter B. }}</ref> \n* [[Mia Love]], US congresswoman from [[Utah]]<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.latimes.com/nation/politics/politicsnow/la-pn-mia-love-20141105-story.html |newspaper= LA Times |first1= Hohn M. |last1= Glionna |first2= Matt |last2= Pearce |date= November 5, 2014 |title= GOP hopes Mia Love's win a watershed moment for the party |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141115231319/http://www.latimes.com/nation/politics/politicsnow/la-pn-mia-love-20141105-story.html |archive-date= November 15, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n* [[John D. Magrath]],<ref>{{cite web|title=World War II, Medal of Honor, Recipients M-S|url=http://www.history.army.mil/html/moh/wwII-m-s.html|website=history.army.mil|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref> [[Medal of Honor]] recipient\n* [[Vince Mendoza]], music composer and conductor<ref>{{cite web|title=Happy Birthday to Norwalk's Vince Mendoza|url=http://norwalk.dailyvoice.com/neighbors/happy-birthday-to-norwalks-vince-mendoza/504113/|website=The Daily Voice|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Bob Miller (American football)|Bob Miller]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Yesterday's stars: Norwak's Miller was an NFL champ|url=http://www.thehour.com/sports/article/Yesterday-s-stars-Norwak-s-Miller-was-an-NFL-7991664.php|website=The Hour|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref> [[NFL]] player\n* [[Calvin Murphy]],<ref name = \"NBA bio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/history/players/murphy_bio.html |title=NBA Biography |accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref> NBA Hall of Famer\n* [[Artie Shaw]],<ref>{{cite book|last1=Grudens|first1=Richard|title=Jukebox Saturday Night: More Memories of the Big Band Era and Beyond|date=1999|publisher=celebrity profiles publishing|isbn=9781575791425|page=[https://archive.org/details/jukeboxsaturdayn0000grud/page/29 29]|url=https://archive.org/details/jukeboxsaturdayn0000grud|url-access=registration|quote=Artie Shaw Norwalk.|accessdate=May 31, 2017|ref=Dubious}}</ref> Big Band composer\n* [[Daniel J. Shea]],<ref name=\"virtualwall\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.virtualwall.org/ds/SheaDJ01a.htm |title=The Virtual Wall - Daniel Shea, PFC, Army, East Norwalk CT, 14May69 24W012 |accessdate=August 30, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414111630/http://virtualwall.org/ds/SheaDJ01a.htm |archivedate=April 14, 2016 }}</ref> [[Medal of Honor]] recipient\n* [[Horace Silver]], musician and jazz pianist<ref>{{cite news|last1=Atkins|first1=Ronald|title=Horace Silver obituary|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/jun/19/horace-silver|accessdate=May 31, 2017|work=thegurdian|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies.|date=June 19, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Mo Vaughn]], Major League Baseball player<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cavanaugh|first1=Jack|title=The Hottest Prospects in Boston Are a Couple of Guys from Norwalk|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/08/04/nyregion/the-hottest-prospects-in-boston-are-a-couple-of-guys-from-norwalk.html?pagewanted=all|website=The New York Times|accessdate=February 24, 2017|date=August 4, 1991}}</ref>\n* [[Chris Webby]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Norwalk's Chris Webby coy on being Halle Berry's beau|url=http://www.thehour.com/norwalk/article/Norwalk-s-Chris-Webby-coy-on-being-Halle-Berry-s-8006599.php|website=The Hour|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref> rapper\n {{div col end}}\n\n==In popular culture==\n* In [[J. D. Salinger]]'s novel ''[[The Catcher in the Rye]]'', [[Holden Caulfield]]'s parents are attending a party in Norwalk the night he sneaks into his apartment to visit his sister, Phoebe.<ref>{{cite web|author=MJC |url=http://www.cummingsstudyguides.net/Guides3/Catcher.html |title=The Catcher in the Rye: Free Study Guide |publisher=Cummingsstudyguides.net |date= |accessdate=February 14, 2012}}</ref>\n* In [[Jonathan Franzen]]'s novel ''[[The Corrections]]'', Chip Lambert holds a \"twelve-hour vigil\" at a [[Dunkin' Donuts]] in Norwalk (stalking Melissa Paquette in neighboring [[Westport, Connecticut|Westport]]).\n\n=== Films ===\nFull-length features and documentary films, filmed or set in Norwalk:\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[Hope Springs (2012 film)|Hope Springs]]'' (2012)<ref name=\"Hope Springs\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1535438/locations|title=Hope Springs (2012) \u2013 Filming locations|accessdate=August 2, 2012}}</ref>\n* ''[[Confessions of a Shopaholic (film)|Confessions of a Shopaholic]]'' (2009)<ref name=\"shopaholic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1093908/locations|title=Confessions of a Shopaholic (2009) \u2013 Filming locations|accessdate=June 1, 2008}}</ref> \u2014 filmed along Washington Street in SoNo\n* ''[[Birds of America (film)|Birds of America]]'' (2008)<ref name=\"birds_of_america\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1029134/locations|title=Bird of America (2008) \u2013 Filmin locations|accessdate=July 28, 2008}}</ref>\n* ''[[College Road Trip]]'' (2008) \u2014 scenes filmed in town in mid-July 2007; shooting locations were the former Norwalk police headquarters building in Matthews Park, on the Merritt Parkway and along the Route 7 connector.<ref>{{cite web|title=College Road Trip|url=http://movies.disney.com/college-road-trip|website=Disney|publisher=Disney Lifestyle|accessdate=May 31, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''[[Revolutionary Road (film)|Revolutionary Road]]'' (2008)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.silverminetavern.com/currentevents.htm|title=Current Events|publisher=Silverminetavern.com|author=Gizmo Graphics Web Design - Bruce C. brown|accessdate=February 14, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208150245/http://www.silverminetavern.com/currentevents.htm|archivedate=February 8, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Six Wives of Henry LeFay]]'' (2008) \u2014 filmed in 2007 on Wall Street in Norwalk Center<ref name=\"lefay\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1074214/locations|title=The Six Wives of Henry Lefay (2008) \u2013 Filming locations|accessdate=July 28, 2008}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Life Before Her Eyes (film)|The Life Before Her Eyes]]'' (2007) \u2014 [[Uma Thurman]] filmed a scene at [[Norwalk Community College]] in August 2006.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Life Before Her Eyes|url=http://www.magpictures.com/profile.aspx?id=2bfd3996-6346-46db-b478-22d0a558b4e2|website=Magnolia Pictures|publisher=2929 Entertainment|accessdate=May 31, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161231025342/http://www.magpictures.com/profile.aspx?id=2bfd3996-6346-46db-b478-22d0a558b4e2|archive-date=December 31, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Filming Locations|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0815178/locations?ref_=tt_dt_dt|website=Internet Movie Data base|publisher=1990-2017 IMDb.com, Inc.|accessdate=May 31, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''[[Satan's Little Helper]]'' (2004)<ref>{{cite web|title=Norwalk|url=http://www.lookct.com/cities/norwalk/|website=LookCT|accessdate=February 24, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170225053221/http://www.lookct.com/cities/norwalk/|archive-date=February 25, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Stepford Wives (2004 film)|The Stepford Wives]]'' (2004)<ref name=\"stepford_2004\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0327162/locations|title=The Stepford Wives (2004) \u2013 Filming locations|accessdate=June 1, 2008}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Object of My Affection]]'' (1998)<ref>{{cite web|title=The Object of My Affection (1998)|url=http://newenglandfilm.com/local_film/the-object-of-my-affection|website=NewEnglanFilm.com|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Stepford Wives (1975 film)|The Stepford Wives]]'' (1975)<ref name=\"stepford_1975\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0073747/locations|title=The Stepford Wives (1975) \u2013 Filming locations|accessdate=June 1, 2008}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Television===\nPartially or entirely recorded in Norwalk:\n* ''[[Oprah Winfrey Presents: Mitch Albom's For One More Day]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=Filming Locations|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1023504/locations?ref_=tt_dt_dt|website=Internet Movie Data base|publisher=IMDb.com, Inc.|accessdate=May 31, 2017}}</ref>\n*''[[House of Dark Shadows]]'' (1970 series) \u2014 \"Abandoned Monastery\" portions filmed at the Lockwood-Mathews Mansion<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0065856/locations|title=House of Dark Shadows (1970)|work=IMDb|accessdate=August 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Sister cities ==\n* {{flagdeco|Nicaragua}} [[Nagarote]] (Nicaragua) since 1986 (see [[Norwalk/Nagarote Sister City Project]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sistercityproject.org/aboutus.htm|title=About Us|publisher=Norwalk/Nagarote Sister City Project|accessdate=November 26, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129200001/http://www.sistercityproject.org/aboutus.htm|archive-date=November 29, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Connecticut}}\n{{Commons category}}\n{{wikivoyage|Norwalk (Connecticut)|Norwalk, Connecticut}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.norwalkct.org}}\n\n{{Geographic location\n|title =  \n|Northwest = [[New Canaan, CT]]\n|North = [[Wilton, CT]]\n|Northeast = \n|West = [[Darien, CT]]\n|Center = Norwalk\n|East = [[Westport, CT]]\n|Southwest = \n|South = \n|Southeast = \n}}\n{{Norwalk, Connecticut}}\n{{Fairfield County, Connecticut}}\n{{Connecticut}}\n{{New York metropolitan area}}\n{{New England}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Norwalk, Connecticut|Norwalk]]\n[[Category:Cities in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1651]]\n[[Category:Cities in the New York metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Cities in Fairfield County, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:1651 establishments in Connecticut]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Norwich, Connecticut|Norfolk, Connecticut|}}\n{{short description|City in Connecticut, United States}}\n{{Use American English|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                   = Norwalk\n| settlement_type        = [[City]]\n| image_skyline          = File:Connecticut shore aerial - Norwalk Harbor & vicinity 01 - white balanced (9607083547).jpg\n| image_alt              = Norwalk Harbor and vicinity\n| image_caption          = Aerial view of Norwalk Harbor and vicinity\n| image_seal             = File:NorwalkCTseal.jpg\n| seal_alt               = Official Seal\n| nickname               = Oyster Town\n| motto                  = {{lang-lat | E Pluribus Unum}}\n| image_map              = Fairfield County Connecticut incorporated and unincorporated areas Norwalk highlighted.svg\n| mapsize                = 230px\n| map_caption            = Location in [[Fairfield County, Connecticut|Fairfield County]] and [[Connecticut]]\n| coordinates            = {{coord|41|05|38|N|73|25|11|W|region:US-CT_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map            = USA#Connecticut\n| pushpin_label_position = top<!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n| pushpin_label          = Norwalk\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location in the United States and Connecticut\n| subdivision_type       = Country\n| subdivision_name       = [[United States]]\n| subdivision_type1      = [[U.S. state]]\n| subdivision_name1      = [[Connecticut]]\n| subdivision_type2      = [[County (United States)|County]]\n| subdivision_name2      = [[Fairfield County, Connecticut|Fairfield]]\n| subdivision_type3      = Metropolitan area \n| subdivision_name3      = [[Greater Bridgeport|Bridgeport-Stamford]]\n| established_title      = Settled\n| established_date       = February 26, 1640\n| established_title2     = [[Municipal corporation|Incorporated]]\n| established_date2      = September 11, 1651\n| established_title3     = Consolidated\n| established_date3      = June 6, 1913\n| founder                = [[Roger Ludlow]] and Daniel Patrick<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mccurdyfamilylineage.com/ancestry/p7213.htm|title=Captain Daniel Patrick|publisher=John Cardinal's Second Site v5.3.5.|accessdate=January 7, 2016|author=McCurdy, Kathy and Larry}}</ref>\n| government_type        = [[Mayor-council government|Weak-mayor-City Council]]\n| leader_party           = [[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]\n| leader_title           = Mayor\n| leader_name            = [[Harry Rilling]]\n| unit_pref              = Imperial\n| area_total_sq_mi       = 36.3\n| area_land_sq_mi        = 22.8\n| area_water_sq_mi       = 13.5\n| elevation_ft           = 43\n| population_total       = 85603\n| population_as_of       = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n| population_density_sq_mi = auto\n| population_footnotes = <ref>{{cite web|title=QuickFacts Norwalk city, Connecticut|url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/table/PST045216/0955990|website=United States Census Bureau|publisher=U.S. Department of Commerce|accessdate=June 2, 2017}}</ref>\n| population_blank1 = 89047\n| population_blank1_title = Est. (2018)\n| population_density_blank1_sq_mi= 3,879\n| pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=July 17, 2019}}</ref>\n| postal_code_type  = Zip codes\n| postal_code       = 06850\u201406860\n| area_code         = [[Area codes 203 and 475|203/475]]\n| area_code_type    = [[North American Numbering Plan|Area codes]]\n| website           = {{Official website|http://www.norwalkct.org/}}\n| etymology         = [[Mohegan-Pequot language]]\n| timezone          = [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern Standard Time]] ([[Eastern Time Zone|EST]])\n| utc_offset        = &minus;5\n| timezone_DST      = [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern Daylight Time]] ([[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]])\n|utc_offset_DST = &minus;4\n|blank1_name        = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank1_info        = {{FIPS|09|55990}}\n|blank2_name        = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank2_info        = {{GNIS4|0209405}}\n|blank3_name        = Major highways\n|blank3_info        = [[File:I-95.svg|25px|link=Interstate 95 in Connecticut]] [[File:US 7.svg|24px|link=U.S. Route 7 in Connecticut]] [[File:Merritt Pkwy Shield.svg|25px|link=Merritt Parkway]]\n|blank4_name        = [[Commuter rail|Commuter Rail]]\n|blank4_info        = [[File:MTA NYC logo.svg|25px|link=New Haven Line]]\n}}\n\n'''Norwalk''' is a U.S. city located in southwestern Connecticut, in southern [[Fairfield County, Connecticut|Fairfield County]], on the northern shore of [[Long Island Sound]]. Norwalk lies within both the [[New York-Newark, NY-NJ-CT-PA Combined Statistical Area|New York metropolitan area]] as well as the [[Bridgeport-Stamford-Norwalk, CT Metropolitan Statistical Area|Bridgeport metropolitan area]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Bridgeport-Stamford-Norwalk, CT Metropolitan NECTA|url=https://censusreporter.org/profiles/35000US71950-bridgeportstamfordnorwalk-ct-metropolitan-necta/|website=Census Reporter|publisher=Knight News|accessdate=May 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nNorwalk was settled in 1649, and is the [[List of municipalities of Connecticut by population|sixth most populous]] city in [[Connecticut]]. According to the [[2010 United States Census]] it has had a population of 85,603; with an estimated population of 89,047 in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=2010 Census Interactive Population Search|url=https://www.census.gov/2010census/popmap/ipmtext.php?fl=0955990|website=US Census 2010|publisher=US Census Bureau|accessdate=April 2, 2017}}{{Dead link|date=December 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.</ref><ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n\n== History ==\n{{main|History of Norwalk, Connecticut}}Norwalk was settled in 1649, incorporated September 1651, and named after the [[Mohegan-Pequot language|Algonquin]] word {{transl|alq|noyank}}, meaning \"point of land\", or more probably from the native American name \"Naramauke\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Connecticut Towns in the Order of Their Establishment; With the Origin of Their Names|url=http://www.sots.ct.gov/sots/cwp/view.asp?a=3188&q=392440|website=State of Connecticut|publisher=Connecticut Secretary of the State|accessdate=February 1, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202180215/http://www.sots.ct.gov/sots/cwp/view.asp?a=3188&q=392440|archive-date=February 2, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Battle of Norwalk]] took place during the Revolutionary War,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehour.com/norwalk/article/Norwalk-was-scene-of-largest-battle-fought-in-8268805.php|title=Norwalk was scene of 'largest battle' fought in Conn.|work=The Hour|access-date=2018-06-25}}</ref> and lead to the burning of most of the town.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ixYiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=VnUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1942,4309138|title=The Hour - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com|access-date=2018-06-25}}</ref> In 1836, the borough of Norwalk was created, covering the central area of the town.<ref>{{Citation|title=Norwalk (Connecticut)|url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/1911_Encyclop%C3%A6dia_Britannica/Norwalk_(Connecticut)|work=1911 Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|volume=Volume 19|access-date=2018-06-25}}</ref> In 1853, the first ever train disaster in the United States [[Norwalk rail accident|happened]] over the [[Norwalk River]].<ref name=\"reed\">{{cite book|title=Train Wrecks: A Pictorial History of Accidents on the Main Line|last=Reed|first=Robert C.|publisher=Bonanza Books|year=1967|location=New York}}</ref> During the 19th and early 20th century, Norwalk was a major railroad stop for the [[New York, New Haven and Hartford Railroad|New York, New Haven, and Hartford Railroad]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehour.com/news/article/A-brief-history-of-the-train-station-that-once-9231874.php|title=A brief history of the train station that once served Wall Street|work=The Hour|access-date=2018-06-25}}</ref> The [[South Norwalk|city of South Norwalk]] and the remaining parts of the town of Norwalk were both combined in 1910 to form the current city.<ref name=\"ray_stewart_pp170_173\">Deborah Wing Ray, Gloria P. Stewart (1979) pp. 170-173.</ref>\n\nThe [[Ku Klux Klan]] had a brief presence in Norwalk during the 1920s, but quickly fell apart due to internal issues.<ref>DiGiovanni, the Rev. (now Monsignor) Stephen M., ''The Catholic Church in Fairfield County: 1666-1961,'' 1987, William Mulvey Inc., New Canaan, Chapter II: The New Catholic Immigrants, 1880-1930; subchapter: \"The True American: White, Protestant, Non-Alcoholic,\" p. 82; DiGiovanni, in turn, cites (Footnote 210, page 258) Chalmers, David A., ''Hooded Americanism, The History of the Ku Klux Klan (New York, 1981), p. 268''</ref> In 1955, [[1955 Connecticut floods|multiple hurricanes]] hit the city, causing flooding in [[Norwalk Harbor]].<ref>There were three major storms in that affected Norwalk in 1955: [[Hurricane Connie]], [[Hurricane Diane]], and an unnamed storm in October. See {{cite web|url=http://www.cslib.org/flood1955.htm|title=The Connecticut Floods of 1955|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140712205408/http://www.cslib.org/flood1955.htm|archivedate=2014-07-12|url-status=dead|accessdate=2008-04-01}}</ref> During the 1970s, efforts were taken to historically preserve South Norwalk, resulting in the creation of the [[South Main and Washington Streets Historic District|Washington Street Historic District]].<ref name=\"nrhpinv3\">{{cite web|url={{NRHP url|id=77001393}}|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination: South Main & Washington Street|author=Bruce Clouette|date=March 28, 1977|publisher=National Park Service}} and {{NRHP url|id=77001393|title=''Accompanying 13 photos, from 1977''|photos=y}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|36.3|sqmi|km2}}, of which, {{convert|22.8|sqmi|km2}} is land and {{convert|13.5|sqmi|km2}} (37.24%) is water.\n\n===Climate===\n<div style=\"width:75%;\">\n{{Norwalk, CT weather box}}\n</div>\n\n=== Topography ===\nNorwalk's topography is dominated by its coastline along [[Long Island Sound]], the [[Norwalk River]] and its eastern and western banks, and the [[Norwalk Islands]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/uconnlibrariesmagic/4731537582/|title=Norwalk South Quadrangle 1984|publisher=University of Connecticut|accessdate=January 20, 2017}}</ref> The highest elevation is 315 feet above sea level on the fairway of the 16th hole of the Silvermine Golf Course,<ref>http://cteco.uconn.edu/maps/town/Contour_Map/Contour_Map_North_Norwalk.pdf</ref> and the low elevation is sea level on Long Island Sound.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1790= 11942\n|1800= 5146\n|1810= 2983\n|1820= 3004\n|1830= 3972\n|1840= 3863\n|1850= 4651\n|1860= 7852\n|1870= 12119\n|1880= 13956\n|1890= 17747\n|1900= 19932\n|1910= 24211\n|1920= 27743\n|1930= 36019\n|1940= 39849\n|1950= 49460\n|1960= 67775\n|1970= 79288\n|1980= 77767\n|1990= 78331\n|2000= 82951\n|2010= 85603\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=89047\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=1790 population included<br>Stamford and Greenwich.<br><ref>{{cite web|title=Population of Connecticut Towns 1970-2010|url=http://www.sots.ct.gov/sots/cwp/view.asp?a=3188&q=392400|website=Connecticut Secretary of the State|publisher=State of Connecticut|accessdate=March 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113205742/http://www.sots.ct.gov/sots/cwp/view.asp?a=3188&q=392400|archive-date=January 13, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n}}\nAs of the [[census]] of 2010, there were 85,603 people,<ref>{{cite web |title=Has the Population in Norwalk Increased? |url=https://patch.com/connecticut/norwalk/has-population-norwalk-increased-0 |website=Norwalk, CT Patch |accessdate=3 August 2018 |date=22 May 2015}}</ref> 35,415 households,<ref>{{cite web |title=Household Number |url=https://www.norwalkct.org/DocumentCenter/View/2241/Fair-Housing-Newspaper-Columns-May-2011-to-Februa?bidId= |accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref> and 21,630 families residing in the city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/table/SBO030212/0955990|title=Norwalk city, Connecticut, 2010|last=|first=|date=|website=www.census.gov|language=en|access-date=March 30, 2017}}{{dead link|date=March 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> The [[population density]] was 2,358.2 inhabitants per square mile (910.7/km\u00b2). There were 35,415 housing units at an average density of 975.6 per square mile (376.6/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 68.7% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 14.2% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.4%[[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 4.8% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.1% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 9.0% from other races, and 2.8% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] people of any race were 24.3% of the population.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/QTP11/1600000US0955990|title=American FactFinder - Results|last=Bureau|first=U.S. Census|website=factfinder.census.gov|language=en|access-date=March 31, 2017|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213114945/https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/QTP11/1600000US0955990|archive-date=February 13, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThere were 35,415 households out of which 27.9% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 47.1% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 11.0% had a female householder with no husband present, and 38.4% were non-families. 33.0% of all households were made up of individuals and 8.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size in the city was 2.55 and the average family size was 3.16.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/QTH1/1600000US0955990|title=American FactFinder - Results|last=Bureau|first=U.S. Census|website=factfinder.census.gov|language=en|access-date=March 31, 2017|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213110815/https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/QTH1/1600000US0955990|archive-date=February 13, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe population's spread gives 22% under the age of 18, with 7.3% from 18 to 24, 31.7% from 25 to 44, 31.2% from 45 to 64, and 12.8% aged 65 years or older. The median age is 40 years. For every 100 females, there are 96.2 males.<ref name=\":1\" />\n{{See also|List of Connecticut locations by per capita income}}\nThe median income for a household in the city was $76,161, and the median income for a family was $103,032. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $43,303.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP03/1600000US0955990|title=American FactFinder - Results|last=Bureau|first=U.S. Census|website=factfinder.census.gov|language=en|access-date=March 31, 2017|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213113004/https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP03/1600000US0955990|archive-date=February 13, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref> About 5.7% of families and 8.4% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 10.2% of those under age 18 and 8.2% of those age 65 or over.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/S1702/1600000US0955990|title=American FactFinder - Results|last=Bureau|first=U.S. Census|website=factfinder.census.gov|language=en|access-date=March 31, 2017|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213114816/https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/S1702/1600000US0955990|archive-date=February 13, 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|title=U.S. Census website|last=Bureau|first=U.S. Census|website=[[United States Census Bureau]]|language=en|access-date=March 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\n{{See also|List of companies based in Norwalk, Connecticut}}\n[[Pepperidge Farm]], [[Xerox]], [[Frontier Communications]], and [[Booking Holdings]] have headquarters in Norwalk.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pepperidgefarm.com/contact-us/|title=Contact Us - Pepperidge Farm|work=Pepperidge Farm|access-date=June 7, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.courant.com/business/hc-xerox-connecticut-20161216-story.html|title=Xerox To Keep Connecticut Headquarters, State Offers $4.4 Million Loan|last=Singer|first=Stephen|work=courant.com|access-date=June 7, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Arts and culture==\n===Events===\n* St. George [[Greek Orthodox]] Festival, held in late August, features [[Greeks|Greek]] delicacies, [[Pontic Greek]] dance exhibitions and a large carnival.\n* Round Hill Highland Games, a festival of [[Scottish people|Scottish]] culture and athletic events, was started in 1923 in [[Greenwich, Connecticut|Greenwich]] but was interrupted during World War II, then restarted in 1952. It has been held in Norwalk's Cranbury Park on or around July 4 for a number of years. In 2006, the 83rd annual event attracted 4,000 people to hear [[bagpipes]] and watch the [[caber toss]], the [[hammer throw]], and other events, with athletes often wearing wool [[kilt]]s. Games for children are offered. Food and Scottish items are available for sale. Organizers say the event is the third-oldest Scottish games festival in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roundhill.org |title=roundhill.org |publisher=roundhill.org |date= |accessdate=May 1, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Places of worship===\n* [[Beth Israel Synagogue (Norwalk, Connecticut)|Beth Israel Synagogue]]\n* [[St. Jerome Church (Norwalk, Connecticut)|Saint Jerome Church]]\n* [[Saint Joseph Church (Norwalk, Connecticut)|Saint Joseph Church]]\n* [[St. Ladislaus Church (South Norwalk, Connecticut)|Saint Ladislaus Church]]\n* [[Saint Mary Church (Norwalk, Connecticut)|Saint Mary Church]]\n* [[St. Matthew Church (Norwalk, Connecticut)|Saint Matthew Church]]\n* [[St. Philip Church (Norwalk, Connecticut)|St. Philip Church]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Saint Philip Church|url=http://www.stphilipnorwalk.org/|website=Saint Philip Church|publisher=Our Sunday Visitor|accessdate=May 31, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Saint Thomas the Apostle Church (Connecticut)|Saint Thomas the Apostle Church]]\n\n===Attractions===\n[[File:NorwalkCTNorwalkMuseum80122007.JPG|thumb|Norwalk's [[Former Norwalk City Hall|former city hall]]]]{{Div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Norwalk Oyster Festival]]\n* Norwalk Boat Show<ref>{{cite web|title=Norwalk Boat Show|url=http://www.boatshownorwalk.com/|publisher=NMMA|accessdate=February 10, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Lockwood-Mathews Mansion]] Museum<ref>{{cite web|title=Lockwood-Mathews Mansion Museum|url=https://www.lockwoodmathewsmansion.com/|website=Lockwood-Mathews Mansion Museum|accessdate=February 10, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Maritime Aquarium at Norwalk]].\n* [[Mill Hill Historic Park|The Mill Hill Historic Park and Museum]]\n* Norwalk Film Festival\n* Norwalk Historical Society Museum<ref>{{cite web|title=Norwalk Historical Society Museum|url=http://norwalkhistoricalsociety.org/about/visit-us/|website=Norwalk Historical Society|accessdate=February 11, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427191005/http://norwalkhistoricalsociety.org/about/visit-us/|archive-date=April 27, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Norwalk Islands]]\n* Norwalk Symphony Orchestra<ref>{{cite web|title=Norwalk Symphony Orchestra|url=http://www.norwalksymphony.org/|publisher=Norwalk Symphony Orchestra Governing Board & Staff|accessdate=February 5, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Norwalk Youth Symphony]]\n* [[Sheffield Island Light]] (house)\n* SoNo Switchtower Museum<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westctnrhs.org/tower.htm |title=Welcome to the SONO Switch Tower Museum! |publisher=Westctnrhs.org |date= |accessdate=May 1, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Stepping Stones Museum for Children]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Notable places on the National Register of Historic Places===\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Norwalk Green Historic District]]\n* [[Joseph Loth Company Building]]\n* [[Lockwood-Mathews Mansion]]\n* [[Rock Ledge (Norwalk, Connecticut)|Rock Ledge]]\n* [[Norwalk City Hall|Norwalk's Former City Hall]]\n* [[Sheffield Island Light]]\n* [[Pecks Ledge Light|Peck Ledge Lighthouse]]\n* [[Greens Ledge Light]]\n* [[Beth Israel Synagogue (Norwalk, Connecticut)|Beth Israel Synagogue]]\n* [[Village Creek (Norwalk, Connecticut)|Village Creek]]\n* [[White Barn Theatre]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Government==\n===Politics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"float:right; margin:1em; font-size:95%;\"\n|+ Norwalk city vote<br/> by party in presidential elections<ref>https://authoring.ct.gov//SOTS/Election-Services/Statement-Of-Vote-PDFs/General-Elections-Statement-of-Vote-1922</ref>\n|- style=\"background:lightgrey;\"\n! Year\n! [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n! [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n! [[Third party (United States)|Third parties]]\n|-\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|[[2016 United States presidential election|2016]]\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''63.86%''' ''24,414''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|32.23% ''12,324''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Independent}}|3.91% ''1,494''\n|-\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|[[2012 United States presidential election|2012]]\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''63.01%''' ''22,369''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|35.98% ''12,773''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Independent}}|1.01% ''357''\n|-\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|[[2008 United States presidential election|2008]]\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''65.51%''' ''24,489