t-align:center;\"| 100\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" |{{center|Sources:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ct.gov/sots/lib/sots/electionservices/registration_and_enrollment_stats/nov16r&e.pdf|title=Registration and Party Enrollment Statistics|date=November 1, 2016|website=ct.gov|publisher=Connecticut Secretary of the State|access-date=March 30, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170220021326/http://www.ct.gov/sots/lib/sots/electionservices/registration_and_enrollment_stats/nov16r%26e.pdf|archive-date=February 20, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===Districts===\nThe City of Norwalk currently has six taxing districts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Norwalk Tax District Map|url=http://www.norwalkct.org/DocumentCenter/View/4745|website=City of Norwalk|publisher=Government Websites by CivicPlus|accessdate=March 27, 2017}}</ref> The First, Second, Third and Sixth taxing districts are political entities with their respective voters electing officers, holding annual business meetings, approving budgets and to consider other matters, as specified in each of their charters.<ref>{{cite web|title=SPECIAL DISTRICT GOVERNMENTS|url=https://www2.census.gov/govs/cog/2007/ct.pdf|website=United States Census Bureau|publisher=U.S. Department of Commerce|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=SPECIAL TAXING DISTRICTS|url=https://www.cga.ct.gov/2011/rpt/2011-R-0347.htm|website=Connecticut General Assembly|publisher=Connecticut General Assembly|accessdate=March 23, 2017}}</ref> Election of Taxing District Commissioners and Treasurers by voters from the 1st, 2nd, 3rd, and 6th districts take place in odd numbered years.\n\nThe Fourth and Fifth districts are not counted as separate governments as they constitute the city proper.<ref>{{cite web|title=proper: see def #5|url=http://www.thefreedictionary.com/proper|website=The Free Dictionary|publisher=Farlex|accessdate=March 28, 2017}}</ref> Each taxing district has its own [[Property tax in the United States|property tax]] rate reflecting the mix of services each receives from the city.\nSecondly, municipal elections of Mayor, Common Council, Board of Education and other positions are also held in odd numbered years at thirteen polling places within five [[Electoral district|voting districts]] around the city.\n\nVoting districts are not the same for state and federal elections which are held on even numbered years at twelve polling locations.<ref>{{cite web|title=Where Do I Vote?|url=http://www.norwalkct.org/346/Where-Do-I-Vote|website=City of Norwalk|publisher=Government Websites by CivicPlus|accessdate=March 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Municipal====\n[[File:NorwalkCTCityHallFront09032007.JPG|upright=1.1|thumb|Norwalk City Hall and Concert Hall]]\nNorwalk's municipal government is a [[Mayor-Council|weak-mayor form]] of a [[mayor-council government]] with the mayor of Norwalk elected by its voters.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nlc.org/build-skills-and-networks/resources/cities-101/city-structures/forms-of-municipal-government | title=Forms of Municipal Government | publisher=National League of Cities | date=2013 | accessdate=March 23, 2016}}</ref>  The city's charter gives certain administrative powers exclusively to the Council and others jointly to the Council and Mayor. The Common Council is the law-writing body of the City of Norwalk.  Norwalk's [[city council|common council]] consists of fifteen council members, five elected [[at-large]] and ten elected [[Electoral district|by district]], two from each district.<ref>{{cite web|title=Common Council|url=http://www.norwalkct.org/286/Common-Council|website=Norwalk, the Sound of Connecticut|publisher=City of Norwalk|accessdate=March 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Representatives ===\nNorwalk is represented in the [[Connecticut General Assembly]] by five House Representatives corresponding to five Connecticut legislative districts and one senator from one Connecticut Senate district.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.norwalkct.org/DocumentCenter/View/3548 | title=State/Federal Voting Districts | publisher=City of Norwalk, Connecticut | work=Where Do I Vote? | date=November 30, 2011 | accessdate=March 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.senatedems.ct.gov/find/findlegislator.asp | title=Find Your Connecticut State Senator | publisher=Connecticut Senate Democrats | date=2016 | accessdate=March 24, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160321215035/http://www.senatedems.ct.gov/find/findlegislator.asp | archive-date=March 21, 2016 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nNorwalk, which lies within [[Connecticut's 4th congressional district]], is represented in the [[United States Congress]] by one congressional representative (Democrat [[Jim Himes]]) in the [[United States House of Representatives]] and, along with the rest of Connecticut, by two U.S. Senators (Democrats [[Richard Blumenthal]] and [[Chris Murphy]]) in the [[United States Senate]].\n\n==Education==\n{{main|Education in Norwalk, Connecticut}}\n[[Norwalk Public Schools]] operates public schools, while the community also has various private schools.\n\nNorwalk was granted a town charter by the [[Connecticut General Assembly|Connecticut General Court]] in 1651. On May 29, 1678, town records mention the establishment of community-supported teaching activities with a passage that reads:\n\"'At a town meeting... voted and agreed to hier a scole master to teach all the children in ye town to lerne to Rede and write; and that Mr. Cornish shall be hierd for that service and the townsmen are to hier him upon as reasonable terms as they can.\"\n\nThe school that was established in the 1670s was located near the Ludlow Square area of [[East Norwalk]] (near the former Roger Ludlow Junior High School).<ref name=\"beard\">{{cite journal|title=Norwalk's Old Schoolhouse|last=Beard|first=Patten|journal=Connecticut Circle Magazine|date=September 1954|url=http://www.norwalkhistoricalsociety.org/Schoolhouse1.html|access-date=February 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170705152336/http://www.norwalkhistoricalsociety.org/Schoolhouse1.html|archive-date=July 5, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Sports==\n[[Baseball]] and [[softball]] are popular amateur sports with active leagues across many age groups in Norwalk. There are 4 baseball fields and 16 [[Little League Baseball|Little League]] fields in the city.  Several of the fields, including [[Calf Pasture Beach]]  are illuminated for nighttime play. The fields at The Norwalk Little League team won the [[Little League World Series]] in [[1952 Little League World Series|1952]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.littleleague.org/series/history/divisions/llbbhistory.htm|title=Little League Baseball|accessdate=September 6, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071017034525/http://www.littleleague.org/series/history/divisions/llbbhistory.htm|archivedate=October 17, 2007|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.norwalkct.org/parksrec/NorwalkParkFacilities.pdf|format=PDF|title=Norwalk Park Facilities|accessdate=September 6, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081029193221/http://www.norwalkct.org/parksrec/NorwalkParkFacilities.pdf|archivedate=October 29, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\nThe 14-year-old Babe Ruth League team won the championship in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://brlworldseries.com/default.php?do=Tournament&id=8 |title=Babe Ruth World Series |accessdate=September 6, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080919081338/http://www.brlworldseries.com/default.php?do=Tournament&id=8 |archivedate=September 19, 2008 }}</ref>\nIn 2010, the 12-year-old Norwalk all star team made it to the Cal Ripken league World Series and placed 3rd in the country.  In 2011, the Norwalk American Senior Legion baseball team won the Connecticut State Championship. This had not been accomplished by any other Norwalk Legion team in the storied 83-year history. The team defeated Branford, CT in the championship game.  The girls Norwalk Pride fast pitch softball team won the Connecticut State Championship in 2005, 2006, and 2007.\n\nThe Norwalk Biddy Basketball All Star team Won the State and Regional titles and then went on to the World Championships in New Orleans, LA in 1986 and placed 7th in the world.\n\nBeing a coastal city Norwalk is home to a great many water sports including [[competitive swimming]], recreational [[boating]] and [[fishing]], [[sailing]], [[windsurfing]], and [[kayaking]].\nThe [[Norwalk River]] and inner [[Norwalk Harbor]] host [[Rowing (sport)|rowing]]\nevents and organizations.<ref name=\"rowing\">{{cite web|url=http://www.norwalkriverrowing.org/\n|title=The Norwalk River Rowing Association\n|accessdate=September 6, 2008}} and the {{cite web|url=http://www.newcanaancrew.com/|title=New Canaan Crew|accessdate=September 6, 2008}} are two such rowing organizations.</ref>\nNorwalk resident [[Daniel Walsh (rower)|Daniel Walsh]] won a [[bronze medal]] in Beijing\nwith the U.S. Olympic rowing team in the [[2008 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"hine\">{{cite journal|title=Summer Bronze: Norwalk's Walsh Garners Olympic Medal |last=Hine |first=Tommy |journal=Norwalk Citizen~News |volume=12 |issue=34 |pages=A1, A15 |date=August 22, 2008 |url=http://www.norwalkcitizen-news.com/topstories/ci_10297724 |accessdate=August 27, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080915174056/http://www.norwalkcitizen-news.com/topstories/ci_10297724 |archivedate=September 15, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThere are three golf courses in the city of Norwalk: The Shorehaven Golf Club<ref>{{cite web|title=Shorehaven Golf Club|url=http://www.shorehavengc.org/Home|website=Shorehaven Golf Club|publisher=Jonas Club Software|accessdate=May 31, 2017}}</ref> is a private club in East Norwalk, the Silvermine Golf Club<ref>{{cite web|title=Silvermine Golf Club|url=http://www.silverminegolf.com/|website=Silvermine Golf Club|publisher=Silvermine Golf Club|accessdate=May 31, 2017}}</ref> is a private club in Silvermine (part of the course lies in the town of Wilton), and the Oak Hills Park golf course<ref>{{cite web|title=Oak Hills Park Golf Course|url=https://www.oakhillsgc.com/|website=Oak Hills Park Golf Course|publisher=1-2-1 Marketing|accessdate=May 31, 2017}}</ref> is a public course in West Norwalk.\n\nThe cross town rivalry between the city's two largest high schools', [[Norwalk High School (Connecticut)]] and [[Brien McMahon High School]], sports teams can be rather fierce, particularly for the [[American football|football]], basketball, [[soccer]] and [[field hockey]] teams in the fall; as well as [[lacrosse]], [[baseball]], and [[softball]] teams in the spring.[[Brien McMahon High School]]'s football\nteam won the FCIAC (Fairfield County Interscholastic Athletic Conference) and Class M State Football championship in 1994. McMahon high school's boys lacrosse team went on to win the state division 2 lacrosse championship in 2000.\n\nIn professional team sports, Norwalk is represented by the [[Connecticut Wildcats]] in the [[American National Rugby League]].\n\n==Media==\nNews sources in Norwalk include [[News 12 Networks|News 12 Connecticut]], a regional news channel for southwestern Connecticut and based in Norwalk.<ref>{{cite web|title=Contact Us|url=http://connecticut.news12.com/news/contact-us-1.3991806|website=News 12 Connecticut|accessdate=February 24, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224213427/http://connecticut.news12.com/news/contact-us-1.3991806|archive-date=February 24, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''[[The Hour (newspaper)|The Hour]]'' was an independent daily newspaper based in Norwalk and founded in 1871, which was purchased by [[Hearst Communications]] on April 12, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn93053878/|title=About The evening hour. (Norwalk, CT) 1895-190? \u00ab Chronicling America \u00ab Library of Congress|publisher=Chroniclingamerica.loc.gov|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref>  NancyonNorwalk.com is a self-published, nonprofit news site founded in 2010 that covers local issues.<ref>{{cite web | last = Ferentinos | first = Leah | title = Yale Law Group Steps Up to Defend NancyonNorwalk | publisher = The Hour | date = April 7, 2019  | url = https://www.thehour.com/opinion/article/Yale-law-group-steps-up-to-defend-NancyonNorwalk-13745109.php}}</ref>\n\n==Infrastructure==\n=== Transportation ===\n[[File:NorwalkTransitGillig.jpg|thumb|A Wheels bus at Wheels hub]]\n[[Public transport bus service]] within Norwalk is provided by [[Norwalk Transit District]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.norwalktransit.com/|title=Home|website=Norwalk Transit District|language=en-US|access-date=June 9, 2017}}</ref>  Norwalk Transit District operates fixed route public bus service in Norwalk and [[Westport, Connecticut|Westport]] with evening and Sunday shuttles (serving South Norwalk, Main Avenue and Connecticut Avenue) and commuter shuttles.  Access to other cities through bus services [[Milford, Connecticut|Milford]], [[Danbury, Connecticut|Danbury]], and Stamford. All fixed route buses meet at the Transportation Hub.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.norwalktransit.com/services/|title=Services|website=Norwalk Transit District|language=en-US|access-date=June 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:SouthNorwalkRRstaWestEntrance08112007.jpg|thumb|West entrance of the [[South Norwalk (Metro-North station)|South Norwalk train station]]]]\nThe [[Metro-North Railroad]]'s [[New Haven Line]] runs through and stops in Norwalk. The train goes West and East with [[Grand Central Terminal]] and [[New Haven Union Station]] being the final stops. The [[Danbury Branch]] runs from South Norwalk to [[Danbury, Connecticut|Danbury, CT]]. There are four stations in Norwalk, three of them on the main line which is: [[Rowayton (Metro-North station)|Rowayton]], [[South Norwalk (Metro-North station)|South Norwalk]] and [[East Norwalk (Metro-North station)|East Norwalk]]. The fourth station, [[Merritt 7 (Metro-North station)|Merritt 7]], is on the Danbury Branch. Metro-North provides [[Commuter rail|commuter]] service for all four stations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mnr/html/mnrmap.htm|title=MNR Map|last=|first=|date=|website=MTA|publisher=|access-date=March 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe structure at 47 Wall Street was formerly the Wall Street station of the Danbury Branch, which operated from 1896 to 1936. The city's [[Tram|trolley]] system barn also operated on Wall Street.<ref>{{cite web | last=Koch | first=Robert | title=A brief history of the train station that once served Wall Street | website=The Hour | date=September 19, 2016 | url=https://www.thehour.com/news/article/A-brief-history-of-the-train-station-that-once-9231874.php | access-date=December 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Interstate 95 in Connecticut|Interstate 95]] and the [[Merritt Parkway]] lead through Norwalk, and there are several exits within the Norwalk city limits, and are the major thoroughfare through the city. [[U.S. Route 1 in Connecticut|U.S. Route 1]] goes through the center of the city, mostly following local streets. The major north-south corridor in Norwalk is [[U.S. Route 7 in Connecticut|U.S. Route 7]], which is a expressway throughout most of the route in the city. The expressway section ends at Grist Mill Road in Norwalk from where Route 7 resumes northbound along Main Ave.  Other state routes include [[Connecticut Route 53|Route 53]], [[Connecticut Route 123|Route 123]], and [[Connecticut Route 136|Route 136]].\n\n=== Utilities ===\nElectric power and natural gas in most of Norwalk is provided by [[Eversource Energy]].\n* The First Taxing District<ref>{{cite web | url=http://firstdistrictwater.org/ | title=First District Water Department | date=2010 | accessdate=March 10, 2016}}</ref> provides water to the Third, Fourth and Fifth Taxing Districts.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.norwalkct.org/DocumentCenter/View/4745 | title=Norwalk Tax District Map | accessdate=March 10, 2016}}</ref>\n* The Second Taxing District<ref name=\"secondtaxingdistrict.com\">{{cite web | url=http://www.secondtaxingdistrict.com/about.htm | title=Second Taxing District of the City of Norwalk, Connecticut | accessdate=March 10, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306132649/http://www.secondtaxingdistrict.com/about.htm | archive-date=March 6, 2016 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> serves sections of South Norwalk, East Norwalk, West Norwalk, Rowayton and Silvermine.<ref name=\"secondtaxingdistrict.com\" /> and also owns and operates South Norwalk Electric and Water.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.snew.org/ | title=South Norwalk Electric and Water | accessdate=March 10, 2016}}</ref>\n* The Third Taxing District<ref>{{cite web | url=http://ttd.gov/ | title=Third Taxing District | publisher=JumarMarketing, LLC | date=2016 | accessdate=March 10, 2016}}</ref> provides electric power for East Norwalk.\nThe districts purchase wholesale power and arrange for its delivery to, and distribution within, their respective districts.  Power lines and meters in [[East Norwalk]], [[South Norwalk]], and parts of [[Rowayton]] are maintained by the districts. Both the second (SNEW) and third (TTD) district electric departments belong to the six member Connecticut Municipal Electric Energy Cooperative which pools their wholesale power purchasing to obtain lower rates for their customers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmeec.com/|title=CMEEC|accessdate=September 29, 2008}}</ref>\n\nConnecticut Light and Power (now Eversource Energy) operated a power plant, Norwalk Harbor Station on [[Manresa Island]], from 1960 to 1999 when it was acquired by [[NRG Energy]], which then began its deactivation in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rivard|first1=Nicole|title=NRG to deactivate Norwalk power plant|url=http://www.ctpost.com/news/article/NRG-to-deactivate-Norwalk-power-plant-4547795.php|website=ctpost|publisher=Hearst Media Services Connecticut, LLC|accessdate=May 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004 the third taxing district installed 3 diesel powered generators at the Norden complex on Norden Place that were initially licensed only for emergency power supply. By summer 2008 the generators, with a combined capacity of 6 Megawatts, had been upgraded to allow licensed operation as regular power providers for the grid (not just emergency power).<ref name=\"ttd_7_8\">{{cite journal|journal=Inside Your Third; the Newsletter for Norwalk's Third Taxing District |title=TTD Commission Invests in Norden Generators to Help to Control Electricity Prices|volume=7|issue=8|date=August 2008|page=pg. 1}}</ref><br>\nIn 2007 and 2008 the construction of the [[Middletown-Norwalk transmission line]] disrupted traffic along the Boston Post Road, but the completion of the line is hoped to help provide additional power to lower Fairfield County.  In addition a high-voltage undersea line runs from Manressa Island to Long Island to help provide electric power to [[Long Island Power Authority]] customers.  In 2008 the city government of Norwalk started initial investigations of whether the city might resume generating power for sale to electricity customers in the city.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Koch|first1=Robert|title=Power panel looking to fulfill a unique request|url=http://www.thehour.com/norwalk/article/Power-panel-looking-to-fulfill-a-unique-request-8262982.php|accessdate=May 31, 2017|work=The Hour|publisher=Hearst Media Services Connecticut, LLC|date=July 26, 2008}}</ref>\n\n=== Emergency services ===\n{{See also|Norwalk Fire Department}}\nNorwalk Police Department serves as the city's [[police department]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.norwalkct.org/index.aspx?nid=139 | title=Norwalk Police Department | publisher=CivicPlus | date=2016 | accessdate=May 18, 2016}}</ref> and Norwalk Fire Department serves Norwalk's fire protection district.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.norwalkct.org/index.aspx?nid=63 | title=Norwalk Fire Department | publisher=Civic Plus | date=2016 | accessdate=May 18, 2016}}</ref> Norwalk is served 24/7 by [[Norwalk Hospital]] and Norwalk Hospital EMS, a 911 paramedic service. The service consists of hospital-based paramedics and EMT-Is who serve Norwalk as well as New Canaan, Wilton, Weston, and Westport.\n\n==Notable people==\n{{Main|List of people from Norwalk, Connecticut}}\nNotable people from Norwalk include:\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Charli D'Amelio]], [[TikToker]] and social media personality<ref>{{cite web|title=Popular Norwalk Tik Tok icon uses star power for good|url=https://www.thehour.com/entertainment/article/Norwalk-Tik-Tok-star-amasses-millions-of-followers-14913464.php|website=The Hour|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> {{div col end}}\n* [[A. Scott Berg]], biographer<ref>{{cite web|title=Happy Birthday to Norwalk's A. Scott Berg|url=http://norwalk.dailyvoice.com/neighbors/happy-birthday-to-norwalks-a-scott-berg/510164/|website=Norwalk Daily Voice|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[D. J. Caruso|D.J. Caruso]], film director<ref>{{cite web|title=Happy Birthday to Norwalk's D.J. Caruso|url=http://norwalk.dailyvoice.com/neighbors/happy-birthday-to-norwalks-dj-caruso/563947/|website=Norwalk Daily Voice|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Johnny Gruelle]], artist and author<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lake|first1=Leslie|title=A Norwalk creation, Raggedy Ann & Andy celebrated at Library|url=http://www.thehour.com/news/article/A-Norwalk-creation-Raggedy-Ann-Andy-celebrated-8238927.php|website=The Hour|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref> \n* [[B. Kliban]], cartoonist<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/08/14/obituaries/b-kliban-55-a-cartoonist-who-drew-zany-cats.html | title=B. Kliban, 55, a Cartoonist Who Drew Zany Cats | work=The New York Times | date=August 14, 1990 | accessdate=February 24, 2017 | author=Flint, Peter B. }}</ref> \n* [[Mia Love]], US congresswoman from [[Utah]]<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.latimes.com/nation/politics/politicsnow/la-pn-mia-love-20141105-story.html |newspaper= LA Times |first1= Hohn M. |last1= Glionna |first2= Matt |last2= Pearce |date= November 5, 2014 |title= GOP hopes Mia Love's win a watershed moment for the party |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141115231319/http://www.latimes.com/nation/politics/politicsnow/la-pn-mia-love-20141105-story.html |archive-date= November 15, 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n* [[John D. Magrath]],<ref>{{cite web|title=World War II, Medal of Honor, Recipients M-S|url=http://www.history.army.mil/html/moh/wwII-m-s.html|website=history.army.mil|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref> [[Medal of Honor]] recipient\n* [[Vince Mendoza]], music composer and conductor<ref>{{cite web|title=Happy Birthday to Norwalk's Vince Mendoza|url=http://norwalk.dailyvoice.com/neighbors/happy-birthday-to-norwalks-vince-mendoza/504113/|website=The Daily Voice|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[NFL]] player [[Bob Miller (American football)|Bob Miller]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Yesterday's stars: Norwak's Miller was an NFL champ|url=http://www.thehour.com/sports/article/Yesterday-s-stars-Norwak-s-Miller-was-an-NFL-7991664.php|website=The Hour|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref>\n* NBA Hall of Famer [[Calvin Murphy]]<ref name = \"NBA bio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/history/players/murphy_bio.html |title=NBA Biography |accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Artie Shaw]],<ref>{{cite book|last1=Grudens|first1=Richard|title=Jukebox Saturday Night: More Memories of the Big Band Era and Beyond|date=1999|publisher=celebrity profiles publishing|isbn=9781575791425|page=[https://archive.org/details/jukeboxsaturdayn0000grud/page/29 29]|url=https://archive.org/details/jukeboxsaturdayn0000grud|url-access=registration|quote=Artie Shaw Norwalk.|accessdate=May 31, 2017|ref=Dubious}}</ref> Big Band composer\n* [[Daniel J. Shea]],<ref name=\"virtualwall\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.virtualwall.org/ds/SheaDJ01a.htm |title=The Virtual Wall - Daniel Shea, PFC, Army, East Norwalk CT, 14May69 24W012 |accessdate=August 30, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414111630/http://virtualwall.org/ds/SheaDJ01a.htm |archivedate=April 14, 2016 }}</ref> [[Medal of Honor]] recipient\n* [[Horace Silver]], musician and jazz pianist<ref>{{cite news|last1=Atkins|first1=Ronald|title=Horace Silver obituary|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/jun/19/horace-silver|accessdate=May 31, 2017|work=thegurdian|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies.|date=June 19, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Mo Vaughn]], Major League Baseball player<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cavanaugh|first1=Jack|title=The Hottest Prospects in Boston Are a Couple of Guys from Norwalk|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/08/04/nyregion/the-hottest-prospects-in-boston-are-a-couple-of-guys-from-norwalk.html?pagewanted=all|website=The New York Times|accessdate=February 24, 2017|date=August 4, 1991}}</ref>\n* [[Chris Webby]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Norwalk's Chris Webby coy on being Halle Berry's beau|url=http://www.thehour.com/norwalk/article/Norwalk-s-Chris-Webby-coy-on-being-Halle-Berry-s-8006599.php|website=The Hour|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref> rapper\n\n==In popular culture==\n* In [[J. D. Salinger]]'s novel ''[[The Catcher in the Rye]]'', [[Holden Caulfield]]'s parents are attending a party in Norwalk the night he sneaks into his apartment to visit his sister, Phoebe.<ref>{{cite web|author=MJC |url=http://www.cummingsstudyguides.net/Guides3/Catcher.html |title=The Catcher in the Rye: Free Study Guide |publisher=Cummingsstudyguides.net |date= |accessdate=February 14, 2012}}</ref>\n* In [[Jonathan Franzen]]'s novel ''[[The Corrections]]'', Chip Lambert holds a \"twelve-hour vigil\" at a [[Dunkin' Donuts]] in Norwalk (stalking Melissa Paquette in neighboring [[Westport, Connecticut|Westport]]).\n\n=== Films ===\nFull-length features and documentary films, filmed or set in Norwalk:\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[Hope Springs (2012 film)|Hope Springs]]'' (2012)<ref name=\"Hope Springs\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1535438/locations|title=Hope Springs (2012) \u2013 Filming locations|accessdate=August 2, 2012}}</ref>\n* ''[[Confessions of a Shopaholic (film)|Confessions of a Shopaholic]]'' (2009)<ref name=\"shopaholic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1093908/locations|title=Confessions of a Shopaholic (2009) \u2013 Filming locations|accessdate=June 1, 2008}}</ref> \u2014 filmed along Washington Street in SoNo\n* ''[[Birds of America (film)|Birds of America]]'' (2008)<ref name=\"birds_of_america\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1029134/locations|title=Bird of America (2008) \u2013 Filmin locations|accessdate=July 28, 2008}}</ref>\n* ''[[College Road Trip]]'' (2008) \u2014 scenes filmed in town in mid-July 2007; shooting locations were the former Norwalk police headquarters building in Matthews Park, on the Merritt Parkway and along the Route 7 connector.<ref>{{cite web|title=College Road Trip|url=http://movies.disney.com/college-road-trip|website=Disney|publisher=Disney Lifestyle|accessdate=May 31, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''[[Revolutionary Road (film)|Revolutionary Road]]'' (2008)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.silverminetavern.com/currentevents.htm|title=Current Events|publisher=Silverminetavern.com|author=Gizmo Graphics Web Design - Bruce C. brown|accessdate=February 14, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208150245/http://www.silverminetavern.com/currentevents.htm|archivedate=February 8, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Six Wives of Henry LeFay]]'' (2008) \u2014 filmed in 2007 on Wall Street in Norwalk Center<ref name=\"lefay\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1074214/locations|title=The Six Wives of Henry Lefay (2008) \u2013 Filming locations|accessdate=July 28, 2008}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Life Before Her Eyes (film)|The Life Before Her Eyes]]'' (2007) \u2014 [[Uma Thurman]] filmed a scene at [[Norwalk Community College]] in August 2006.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Life Before Her Eyes|url=http://www.magpictures.com/profile.aspx?id=2bfd3996-6346-46db-b478-22d0a558b4e2|website=Magnolia Pictures|publisher=2929 Entertainment|accessdate=May 31, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161231025342/http://www.magpictures.com/profile.aspx?id=2bfd3996-6346-46db-b478-22d0a558b4e2|archive-date=December 31, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Filming Locations|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0815178/locations?ref_=tt_dt_dt|website=Internet Movie Data base|publisher=1990-2017 IMDb.com, Inc.|accessdate=May 31, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''[[Satan's Little Helper]]'' (2004)<ref>{{cite web|title=Norwalk|url=http://www.lookct.com/cities/norwalk/|website=LookCT|accessdate=February 24, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170225053221/http://www.lookct.com/cities/norwalk/|archive-date=February 25, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Stepford Wives (2004 film)|The Stepford Wives]]'' (2004)<ref name=\"stepford_2004\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0327162/locations|title=The Stepford Wives (2004) \u2013 Filming locations|accessdate=June 1, 2008}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Object of My Affection]]'' (1998)<ref>{{cite web|title=The Object of My Affection (1998)|url=http://newenglandfilm.com/local_film/the-object-of-my-affection|website=NewEnglanFilm.com|accessdate=February 24, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Stepford Wives (1975 film)|The Stepford Wives]]'' (1975)<ref name=\"stepford_1975\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0073747/locations|title=The Stepford Wives (1975) \u2013 Filming locations|accessdate=June 1, 2008}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Television===\nPartially or entirely recorded in Norwalk:\n* ''[[Oprah Winfrey Presents: Mitch Albom's For One More Day]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=Filming Locations|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1023504/locations?ref_=tt_dt_dt|website=Internet Movie Data base|publisher=IMDb.com, Inc.|accessdate=May 31, 2017}}</ref>\n*''[[House of Dark Shadows]]'' (1970 series) \u2014 \"Abandoned Monastery\" portions filmed at the Lockwood-Mathews Mansion<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0065856/locations|title=House of Dark Shadows (1970)|work=IMDb|accessdate=August 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Sister cities ==\n* {{flagdeco|Nicaragua}} [[Nagarote]] (Nicaragua) since 1986 (see [[Norwalk/Nagarote Sister City Project]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sistercityproject.org/aboutus.htm|title=About Us|publisher=Norwalk/Nagarote Sister City Project|accessdate=November 26, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129200001/http://www.sistercityproject.org/aboutus.htm|archive-date=November 29, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Connecticut}}\n{{Commons category}}\n{{wikivoyage|Norwalk (Connecticut)|Norwalk, Connecticut}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.norwalkct.org}}\n\n{{Geographic location\n|title =  \n|Northwest = [[New Canaan, CT]]\n|North = [[Wilton, CT]]\n|Northeast = \n|West = [[Darien, CT]]\n|Center = Norwalk\n|East = [[Westport, CT]]\n|Southwest = \n|South = \n|Southeast = \n}}\n{{Norwalk, Connecticut}}\n{{Fairfield County, Connecticut}}\n{{Connecticut}}\n{{New York metropolitan area}}\n{{New England}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Norwalk, Connecticut|Norwalk]]\n[[Category:Cities in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1651]]\n[[Category:Cities in the New York metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Cities in Fairfield County, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:1651 establishments in Connecticut]]\n", "name_user": "Jessicapierce", "label": "safe", "comment": "minor copy edits", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norwalk,_Connecticut"}
{"title_page": "24 Hour Fitness", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name = 24 Hour Fitness\n| logo = 24 Hour Fitness logo.svg\n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| genre = [[Physical fitness|Fitness]]\n| foundation = 1983\n| founder = [[Mark S. Mastrov]]\n| location_city = [[San Ramon, California|San Ramon]], [[California]]\n| location_country = [[United States]]\n| location = <!-- this parameter modifies \"Headquarters\" -->\n| locations = 400+ <ref>{{cite press release |title=About Us |url=http://www.24hourfitness.com/company/about_us/ |publisher= |date= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n| origins =\n| key_people = Tony Ueber, CEO\n| area_served = 17  U.S. states\n| industry =\n| products =\n| services =\n| revenue =\n| operating_income =\n| net_income =\n| num_employees = 22,000+\n| parent =\n| divisions =\n| subsid =\n| owner = [[AEA Investors]], Ontario Teachers' Pension Plan\n| slogan =\n| homepage =[http://www.24hourfitness.com 24hourfitness.com]\n| dissolved =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n[[File:24 Hour Fitness headquarters.jpg|thumb|right|24 Hour Fitness headquarters in San Ramon]]\n\n'''24 Hour Fitness''' is a privately owned and operated [[Physical fitness|fitness]] center chain headquartered in [[San Ramon, California]]. It is the second largest fitness chain in the US based on revenue after [[LA Fitness]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/macquarie-note-on-planet-fitness-google-trends-2017-2-1001726498|title=One gym is taking the workout world by storm (PLNT) {{!}} Markets Insider|last=GmbH|first=finanzen net|website=markets.businessinsider.com|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref> and the fourth in number of clubs (behind LA Fitness, [[Anytime Fitness]] & [[Gold's Gym]]),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.insidermonkey.com/blog/11-biggest-fitness-chains-in-america-362130/|title=11 Biggest Fitness Chains in America|website=Insider Monkey|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref> operating 420 clubs in only 13 U.S. states with four million clients to LA Fitness's 725 clubs in 30 states. As of March 12, 2011, it was the largest privately owned fitness chain in the U.S.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.abcfinancial.com/abc-articles/americas-top-10-fitness-clubs|title=America\u2019s Top 10 Fitness Clubs|last=Ross|first=Kevin|website=blog.abcfinancial.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref>\n\nThe company was founded by [[Mark S. Mastrov]] and owned by AEA Investors. Their motto is \"Improving lives through fitness.\"\n\n==History==\n===Early history and founding===\n24 Hour Fitness was founded in 1983 by [[Mark Mastrov]]. Mastrov had been using a local gym for rehab after a knee injury, and turned the gym into a 24-hour nautilus facility after buying out the owner.<ref name=\"CNBC\">{{cite news |last1=Ryan |first1=Kevin |title=Fitness gurus who turned a workout passion into a business empire |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/09/26/fitness-gurus-who-turned-workouts-into-business-success-stories.html |accessdate=30 May 2018 |publisher=CNBC |date=27 September 2017}}</ref> The company was originally named \"24 Hour Nautilus.\"<ref name=\"SFGate\">{{cite news |title=24 Hour Nautilus changing its name |url=https://www.sfgate.com/business/article/24-Hour-Nautilus-changing-its-name-3131538.php |accessdate=30 May 2018 |publisher=SF Gate |date=29 July 1996}}</ref>\n\nThe company combined 24 Hour Nautilus, 24 Hour Family Fitness Centers, and Gold's Gyms of Hawaii under the brand name 24 Hour Fitness in 1996.<ref name=\"SFGate\"/>\n\n===2004-2008: Olympics and other sponsorships===\nIn 2004, 24 Hour Fitness became a sponsor of the 2004-2008 United States [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] teams. The sponsorship grants memberships to some U.S. Olympic hopefuls, and includes upgrades to some U.S. Olympic Training Centers across the country, including renovation of the facility in [[Colorado Springs, Colorado]], in 2004 to be followed by [[Lake Placid, New York]], and [[Chula Vista, California]].\n\n24 Hour Fitness partnered with [[NBC]] to develop a reality show, ''[[The Biggest Loser (U.S. TV series)|The Biggest Loser]]'', which features 12 to 22 [[overweight]] contestants competing to lose weight over several million dollars. The show first aired in late 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clubindustry.com/profits/planet-fitness-sponsor-biggest-loser|title=Planet Fitness to Sponsor \u2018The Biggest Loser\u2019|date=2011-10-11|website=Club Industry|language=en|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref>\n\nBeginning in 2005, 24 Hour Fitness partnered with cyclist [[Lance Armstrong]] co-sponsored the [[Discovery Channel Pro Cycling Team]]. That same year, 24 Hour Fitness opened its first Lance Armstrong Signature Club. 24 Hour Fitness cut their ties with Armstrong in 2012 after the his [[Lance Armstrong doping case|doping scandal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clubindustry.com/profits/24-hour-fitness-cuts-ties-lance-armstrong|title=24 Hour Fitness Cuts Ties with Lance Armstrong|date=2012-10-18|website=Club Industry|language=en|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref>\n\n===2009 to present: Acquisition and other operations===\n24 Hour Fitness formerly had some 15 clubs in [[Singapore]] and [[China]]. Besides the United States, it had centres in [[Singapore]] and [[Hong Kong]], [[Beijing]] and [[Shanghai]] in [[China]]) through its wholly owned subsidiary [[California Fitness]] (CalFit).   Its European clubs closed in the early 2000s.  CalFit has been sold to Ansa Group,a Hong Kong company in 2012, providing continuity and retaining the name and memberships without the bad closure experiences of CalWowX, whereby becoming an exclusively US gym chain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://clubsolutionsmagazine.com/2012/08/24-hour-fitness-sells-california-fitness-2/|title=24 Hour Fitness Sells California Fitness|last=Zabonick-Chonko|first=Rachel|date=2012-08-23|website=Club Solutions Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref>\n\nIts former affiliate and spinoff [[California Fitness#California Wow Xperience|California Wow Xperience]] (CalWowX), a California Fitness offshoot, formerly had member swap agreements with both 24 Hour, then only California Fitness, and at its height ran gyms located in [[Bangkok]], [[Chiang Mai]] and [[Pattaya]] in [[Thailand]], including one female-only club.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/comment/insight-opinion/article/1990053/california-fitness-was-pumped-growth-not-fit-purpose|title=California Fitness was pumped for growth, but not fit for purpose|date=2016-07-15|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2012, the owner of 24 Hour Fitness put the 416 location gym chain on the auction block with a price tag reported to have been close to $2 billion.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ross|first=Andrew|title=24 Hour Fitness, healthy chain, for sale|url=http://www.sfgate.com/business/bottomline/article/24-Hour-Fitness-healthy-chain-for-sale-3755709.php|accessdate=14 April 2013|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle|date=Aug 2, 2012}}</ref> After being courted by various interests for over six months, ultimately in January 2012, the board of directors took 24 Hour Fitness off the market. Offers reportedly fell short of the asking price.<ref name=Biz>{{cite news |last=Young |first=Eric |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/news/2013/09/13/24-hour-fitness-names-new-ceo.html |title=24 Hour Fitness names new CEO |newspaper=San Francisco Business Times |publisher=bizjournals.com |date=September 13, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Dezember|first=Ryan|title=24 Hour Fitness Sale Misfires|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324156204578276341617012504|accessdate=14 April 2013|newspaper=Wall Street Journal|date=Jan 31, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, Forstmann Little & Co. reportedly sold 24 Hour Fitness Worldwide Inc. for $1.85 billion to an investment group led by AEA Investors LP and the Ontario Teachers' Pension Plan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.law360.com/articles/543498/forstmann-little-earns-1-85b-in-sale-of-24-hour-fitness|title=Forstmann Little Earns $1.85B In Sale Of 24 Hour Fitness - Law360|website=www.law360.com}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, the company expanded to the [[Chicago metropolitan area]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clubindustry.com/news/24-hour-fitness-open-four-chicago-area-clubs-2020|title=24 Hour Fitness to Open Four Chicago-Area Clubs in 2020|date=2020-01-29|website=Club Industry|language=en|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, due to the coronavirus gym closings and heavy debt load, the company is expected to [[file bankruptcy within the next few months]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/18/24-hour-fitness-weighs-bankruptcy-amid-coronavirus-pandemic|title=24 Hour Fitness weighs bankruptcy as coronavirus pushes fitness industry to brink|date=2020-04-18|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\n\nAs of 2017, 24 Hour Fitness has over 4 million members and more than 420 clubs in 13 states, with more than 22,000 employees. Its major competitors in the US are [[Anytime Fitness]], [[Gold's Gym]], Aspen Fitness, and [[LA Fitness]].<ref name=\"DMagGO\">{{cite news |last1=Hunter |first1=Glenn |title=It's 'Game On' for Growing 24 Hour Fitness |url=https://www.dmagazine.com/publications/d-ceo/2017/december/24-hour-fitness-chris-roussos/ |accessdate=5 June 2018 |publisher=D Magazine}}</ref>\n\nThe company also owns co-branded centers along with celebrities such a [[Lance Armstrong]], [[Mark White (soccer)]], and [[Jackie Chan]].<ref name=\"DP\">{{cite news |last1=Arellano |first1=Kristi |title=Peddling a name |url=https://www.denverpost.com/2005/08/17/peddling-a-name/ |accessdate=11 June 2018 |publisher=The Denver Post |date=17 August 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Criticisms==\n\nOn July 31, 2007, 24 Hour Fitness settled a class-action lawsuit brought against it by 1.8 million current and former members. The plaintiffs claimed damages for the continuation of automatic withdrawals by 24 Hour Fitness long after their monthly memberships were canceled by request.<ref name=\"24 Hour Fitness\">{{cite news|title=Settles in Class-Action Law Suit|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/stories/2007/07/30/daily15.html?page=all|accessdate=6 March 2013|newspaper=San Francisco Business Times|date=Jul 31, 2007<!--, 1:00pm PDT-->}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=24 Hour Fitness Health Club Membership Cancellation and Electronic Funds Transfer EFT Class Action Settlement|url=http://classactionlawsuitsinthenews.com/class-action-notices/24-hour-fitness-health-club-membership-cancellation-and-electronic-funds-transfer-eft-class-action-settlement/|website=Class Action Law Suits in the News|accessdate=7 March 2013}}</ref> In ''McCardle vs 24 Hour Fitness USA, Inc.'', the Alameda County Court ruled in favor of the plaintiffs of the class-action lawsuit. In 2010, the court found that 24 Hour Fitness did not act in good faith after denying members who purchased an \"All Club\" membership access to rebranded locations without charging additional fees not disclosed in the original contract.<ref>{{cite web|title=Courts Find for Plaintiffs Against 24 Hour Fitness|url=http://www.mccardleclassaction.com/pdf/mcardexd.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130929024030/http://www.mccardleclassaction.com/pdf/mcardexd.pdf|archivedate=29 September 2013|website=Superior Court of the State of California|location= County of Alameda|accessdate=6 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Case Settlement Website|url=http://www.mccardleclassaction.com/CaseDocs.html|website=Gilardi & Co. LLC.|accessdate=7 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nSix former employees of 24 Hour Fitness filed a separate class-action lawsuit on July 13, 2010. This lawsuit was brought in the State of California pursuant to allegations that 24 Hour Fitness discriminated based on race and gender in their promotion practices. The claimants are either females, minorities, or both.<ref>{{cite web|author=Lewis|author2=Feinberg|author3=Lee|author4=Renaker|author5=Jackson|last-author-amp=yes|title=Discrimination Class Action Filed|url=http://www.maldef.org/legal/fulcher_v_24_hour_fitness.pdf|website=Alameda County Clerk of Civil Court|accessdate=6 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Watt|first=Brian|title=24 Hour Fitness employees file discrimination suit|url=http://www.scpr.org/news/2010/07/13/17254/fitness-suit/|accessdate=7 March 2013|newspaper=Southern California Public Radio|date=July 13, 2010<!--, 6:30pm-->}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2013|03|02|df=US}}, 805 complaints had been registered against 24 Hour Fitness with the [[Better Business Bureau]] in the previous three years, 276 in the previous 12 months. 24 Hour Fitness has an A+ rating with the private [[non-governmental organization]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbb.org/san-diego/Business-Reviews/health-clubs/24hour-fitness-usa-inc-in-carlsbad-ca-9000777/complaints|title=BBB Business Profile - 24 Hour Fitness USA Inc - Reviews and Complaints|website=www.bbb.org}}</ref>\n<!-- \nIn May 2013, at the new [[Costa Mesa, California]], Super Sport club, a member of the media observed staff evicting a member for placing [[Menthol#Applications|menthol in the sauna]], and the manager telling him he would not be allowed to return.<ref name=\"Menthol in the Sauna\">{{cite news|author =Associated Press|title=club's manager Mike Rubin was seen yelling at wet and almost naked member|url=http://www.mediadev.net/24%20hour%20fitness%20costa%20mesa%20ejects%20member%20for%20menthol%20use.txt|accessdate=25 May 2013|newspaper=AP: Media Development Net|date=May 23, 2013}}</ref> -->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|24 Hour Fitness}}\n*[http://www.24hourfitness.com/ Official Site]\n\n[[Category:Health care companies established in 1983]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1983]]\n[[Category:Health clubs in the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in San Ramon, California]]\n[[Category:Private equity portfolio companies]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in California]]\n[[Category:1983 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Health care companies based in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name = 24 Hour Fitness\n| logo = 24 Hour Fitness logo.svg\n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| genre = [[Physical fitness|Fitness]]\n| foundation = 1983\n| founder = [[Mark S. Mastrov]]\n| location_city = [[San Ramon, California|San Ramon]], [[California]]\n| location_country = [[United States]]\n| location = <!-- this parameter modifies \"Headquarters\" -->\n| locations = 400+ <ref>{{cite press release |title=About Us |url=http://www.24hourfitness.com/company/about_us/ |publisher= |date= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n| origins =\n| key_people = Tony Ueber, CEO\n| area_served = 17  U.S. states\n| industry =\n| products =\n| services =\n| revenue =\n| operating_income =\n| net_income =\n| num_employees = 22,000+\n| parent =\n| divisions =\n| subsid =\n| owner = [[AEA Investors]], Ontario Teachers' Pension Plan\n| slogan =\n| homepage =[http://www.24hourfitness.com 24hourfitness.com]\n| dissolved =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n[[File:24 Hour Fitness headquarters.jpg|thumb|right|24 Hour Fitness headquarters in San Ramon]]\n\n'''24 Hour Fitness''' is a privately owned and operated [[Physical fitness|fitness]] center chain headquartered in [[San Ramon, California]]. It is the second largest fitness chain in the US based on revenue after [[LA Fitness]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/macquarie-note-on-planet-fitness-google-trends-2017-2-1001726498|title=One gym is taking the workout world by storm (PLNT) {{!}} Markets Insider|last=GmbH|first=finanzen net|website=markets.businessinsider.com|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref> and the fourth in number of clubs (behind LA Fitness, [[Anytime Fitness]] & [[Gold's Gym]]),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.insidermonkey.com/blog/11-biggest-fitness-chains-in-america-362130/|title=11 Biggest Fitness Chains in America|website=Insider Monkey|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref> operating 420 clubs in only 13 U.S. states with four million clients to LA Fitness's 725 clubs in 30 states. As of March 12, 2011, it was the largest privately owned fitness chain in the U.S.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.abcfinancial.com/abc-articles/americas-top-10-fitness-clubs|title=America\u2019s Top 10 Fitness Clubs|last=Ross|first=Kevin|website=blog.abcfinancial.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref>\n\nThe company was founded by [[Mark S. Mastrov]] and owned by AEA Investors. Their motto is \"Improving lives through fitness.\"\n\n==History==\n===Early history and founding===\n24 Hour Fitness was founded in 1983 by [[Mark Mastrov]]. Mastrov had been using a local gym for rehab after a knee injury, and turned the gym into a 24-hour nautilus facility after buying out the owner.<ref name=\"CNBC\">{{cite news |last1=Ryan |first1=Kevin |title=Fitness gurus who turned a workout passion into a business empire |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/09/26/fitness-gurus-who-turned-workouts-into-business-success-stories.html |accessdate=30 May 2018 |publisher=CNBC |date=27 September 2017}}</ref> The company was originally named \"24 Hour Nautilus.\"<ref name=\"SFGate\">{{cite news |title=24 Hour Nautilus changing its name |url=https://www.sfgate.com/business/article/24-Hour-Nautilus-changing-its-name-3131538.php |accessdate=30 May 2018 |publisher=SF Gate |date=29 July 1996}}</ref>\n\nThe company combined 24 Hour Nautilus, 24 Hour Family Fitness Centers, and Gold's Gyms of Hawaii under the brand name 24 Hour Fitness in 1996.<ref name=\"SFGate\"/>\n\n===2004-2008: Olympics and other sponsorships===\nIn 2004, 24 Hour Fitness became a sponsor of the 2004-2008 United States [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] teams. The sponsorship grants memberships to some U.S. Olympic hopefuls, and includes upgrades to some U.S. Olympic Training Centers across the country, including renovation of the facility in [[Colorado Springs, Colorado]], in 2004 to be followed by [[Lake Placid, New York]], and [[Chula Vista, California]].\n\n24 Hour Fitness partnered with [[NBC]] to develop a reality show, ''[[The Biggest Loser (U.S. TV series)|The Biggest Loser]]'', which features 12 to 22 [[overweight]] contestants competing to lose weight over several million dollars. The show first aired in late 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clubindustry.com/profits/planet-fitness-sponsor-biggest-loser|title=Planet Fitness to Sponsor \u2018The Biggest Loser\u2019|date=2011-10-11|website=Club Industry|language=en|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref>\n\nBeginning in 2005, 24 Hour Fitness partnered with cyclist [[Lance Armstrong]] co-sponsored the [[Discovery Channel Pro Cycling Team]]. That same year, 24 Hour Fitness opened its first Lance Armstrong Signature Club. 24 Hour Fitness cut their ties with Armstrong in 2012 after the his [[Lance Armstrong doping case|doping scandal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clubindustry.com/profits/24-hour-fitness-cuts-ties-lance-armstrong|title=24 Hour Fitness Cuts Ties with Lance Armstrong|date=2012-10-18|website=Club Industry|language=en|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref>\n\n===2009 to present: Acquisition and other operations===\n24 Hour Fitness formerly had some 15 clubs in [[Singapore]] and [[China]]. Besides the United States, it had centres in [[Singapore]] and [[Hong Kong]], [[Beijing]] and [[Shanghai]] in [[China]]) through its wholly owned subsidiary [[California Fitness]] (CalFit).   Its European clubs closed in the early 2000s.  CalFit has been sold to Ansa Group,a Hong Kong company in 2012, providing continuity and retaining the name and memberships without the bad closure experiences of CalWowX, whereby becoming an exclusively US gym chain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://clubsolutionsmagazine.com/2012/08/24-hour-fitness-sells-california-fitness-2/|title=24 Hour Fitness Sells California Fitness|last=Zabonick-Chonko|first=Rachel|date=2012-08-23|website=Club Solutions Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref>\n\nIts former affiliate and spinoff [[California Fitness#California Wow Xperience|California Wow Xperience]] (CalWowX), a California Fitness offshoot, formerly had member swap agreements with both 24 Hour, then only California Fitness, and at its height ran gyms located in [[Bangkok]], [[Chiang Mai]] and [[Pattaya]] in [[Thailand]], including one female-only club.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/comment/insight-opinion/article/1990053/california-fitness-was-pumped-growth-not-fit-purpose|title=California Fitness was pumped for growth, but not fit for purpose|date=2016-07-15|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2012, the owner of 24 Hour Fitness put the 416 location gym chain on the auction block with a price tag reported to have been close to $2 billion.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ross|first=Andrew|title=24 Hour Fitness, healthy chain, for sale|url=http://www.sfgate.com/business/bottomline/article/24-Hour-Fitness-healthy-chain-for-sale-3755709.php|accessdate=14 April 2013|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle|date=Aug 2, 2012}}</ref> After being courted by various interests for over six months, ultimately in January 2012, the board of directors took 24 Hour Fitness off the market. Offers reportedly fell short of the asking price.<ref name=Biz>{{cite news |last=Young |first=Eric |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/news/2013/09/13/24-hour-fitness-names-new-ceo.html |title=24 Hour Fitness names new CEO |newspaper=San Francisco Business Times |publisher=bizjournals.com |date=September 13, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Dezember|first=Ryan|title=24 Hour Fitness Sale Misfires|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324156204578276341617012504|accessdate=14 April 2013|newspaper=Wall Street Journal|date=Jan 31, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, Forstmann Little & Co. has reportedly sold 24 Hour Fitness Worldwide Inc. to a group of investors for $1.85 billion to an investment group led by AEA Investors LP and the Ontario Teachers' Pension Plan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.law360.com/articles/543498/forstmann-little-earns-1-85b-in-sale-of-24-hour-fitness|title=Forstmann Little Earns $1.85B In Sale Of 24 Hour Fitness - Law360|website=www.law360.com}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, the company expanded to the [[Chicago metropolitan area]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clubindustry.com/news/24-hour-fitness-open-four-chicago-area-clubs-2020|title=24 Hour Fitness to Open Four Chicago-Area Clubs in 2020|date=2020-01-29|website=Club Industry|language=en|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, due to the coronavirus gym closings and heavy debt load, the company is expected to [[file bankruptcy within the next few months]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/18/24-hour-fitness-weighs-bankruptcy-amid-coronavirus-pandemic|title=24 Hour Fitness weighs bankruptcy as coronavirus pushes fitness industry to brink|date=2020-04-18|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\n\nAs of 2017, 24 Hour Fitness has over 4 million members and more than 420 clubs in 13 states, with more than 22,000 employees. Its major competitors in the US are [[Anytime Fitness]], [[Gold's Gym]], Aspen Fitness, and [[LA Fitness]].<ref name=\"DMagGO\">{{cite news |last1=Hunter |first1=Glenn |title=It's 'Game On' for Growing 24 Hour Fitness |url=https://www.dmagazine.com/publications/d-ceo/2017/december/24-hour-fitness-chris-roussos/ |accessdate=5 June 2018 |publisher=D Magazine}}</ref>\n\nThe company also owns co-branded centers along with celebrities such a [[Lance Armstrong]], [[Mark White (soccer)]], and [[Jackie Chan]].<ref name=\"DP\">{{cite news |last1=Arellano |first1=Kristi |title=Peddling a name |url=https://www.denverpost.com/2005/08/17/peddling-a-name/ |accessdate=11 June 2018 |publisher=The Denver Post |date=17 August 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Criticisms==\n\nOn July 31, 2007, 24 Hour Fitness settled a class-action lawsuit brought against it by 1.8 million current and former members. The plaintiffs claimed damages for the continuation of automatic withdrawals by 24 Hour Fitness long after their monthly memberships were canceled by request.<ref name=\"24 Hour Fitness\">{{cite news|title=Settles in Class-Action Law Suit|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/stories/2007/07/30/daily15.html?page=all|accessdate=6 March 2013|newspaper=San Francisco Business Times|date=Jul 31, 2007<!--, 1:00pm PDT-->}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=24 Hour Fitness Health Club Membership Cancellation and Electronic Funds Transfer EFT Class Action Settlement|url=http://classactionlawsuitsinthenews.com/class-action-notices/24-hour-fitness-health-club-membership-cancellation-and-electronic-funds-transfer-eft-class-action-settlement/|website=Class Action Law Suits in the News|accessdate=7 March 2013}}</ref> In ''McCardle vs 24 Hour Fitness USA, Inc.'', the Alameda County Court ruled in favor of the plaintiffs of the class-action lawsuit. In 2010, the court found that 24 Hour Fitness did not act in good faith after denying members who purchased an \"All Club\" membership access to rebranded locations without charging additional fees not disclosed in the original contract.<ref>{{cite web|title=Courts Find for Plaintiffs Against 24 Hour Fitness|url=http://www.mccardleclassaction.com/pdf/mcardexd.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130929024030/http://www.mccardleclassaction.com/pdf/mcardexd.pdf|archivedate=29 September 2013|website=Superior Court of the State of California|location= County of Alameda|accessdate=6 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Case Settlement Website|url=http://www.mccardleclassaction.com/CaseDocs.html|website=Gilardi & Co. LLC.|accessdate=7 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nSix former employees of 24 Hour Fitness filed a separate class-action lawsuit on July 13, 2010. This lawsuit was brought in the State of California pursuant to allegations that 24 Hour Fitness discriminated based on race and gender in their promotion practices. The claimants are either females, minorities, or both.<ref>{{cite web|author=Lewis|author2=Feinberg|author3=Lee|author4=Renaker|author5=Jackson|last-author-amp=yes|title=Discrimination Class Action Filed|url=http://www.maldef.org/legal/fulcher_v_24_hour_fitness.pdf|website=Alameda County Clerk of Civil Court|accessdate=6 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Watt|first=Brian|title=24 Hour Fitness employees file discrimination suit|url=http://www.scpr.org/news/2010/07/13/17254/fitness-suit/|accessdate=7 March 2013|newspaper=Southern California Public Radio|date=July 13, 2010<!--, 6:30pm-->}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2013|03|02|df=US}}, 805 complaints had been registered against 24 Hour Fitness with the [[Better Business Bureau]] in the previous three years, 276 in the previous 12 months. 24 Hour Fitness has an A+ rating with the private [[non-governmental organization]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbb.org/san-diego/Business-Reviews/health-clubs/24hour-fitness-usa-inc-in-carlsbad-ca-9000777/complaints|title=BBB Business Profile - 24 Hour Fitness USA Inc - Reviews and Complaints|website=www.bbb.org}}</ref>\n<!-- \nIn May 2013, at the new [[Costa Mesa, California]], Super Sport club, a member of the media observed staff evicting a member for placing [[Menthol#Applications|menthol in the sauna]], and the manager telling him he would not be allowed to return.<ref name=\"Menthol in the Sauna\">{{cite news|author =Associated Press|title=club's manager Mike Rubin was seen yelling at wet and almost naked member|url=http://www.mediadev.net/24%20hour%20fitness%20costa%20mesa%20ejects%20member%20for%20menthol%20use.txt|accessdate=25 May 2013|newspaper=AP: Media Development Net|date=May 23, 2013}}</ref> -->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|24 Hour Fitness}}\n*[http://www.24hourfitness.com/ Official Site]\n\n[[Category:Health care companies established in 1983]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1983]]\n[[Category:Health clubs in the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in San Ramon, California]]\n[[Category:Private equity portfolio companies]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in California]]\n[[Category:1983 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Health care companies based in California]]\n", "name_user": "Femdork", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e2009 to present: Acquisition and other operations:delete 'has' ; delete 'to a group of investors' in:  In May 2014, Forstmann Little & Co. reportedly sold 24 Hour Fitness Worldwide Inc. for $1.85 billion to an investment group led by AEA Investors LP and the Ontario Teachers' Pension Plan.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/24_Hour_Fitness"}
{"title_page": "AAdvantage", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox loyalty program\n|logo=AAdvantage logo.png\n|website={{url|aa.com/aadvantage}}\n|producttype=[[Frequent-flyer program]]\n|currentowner=[[American Airlines]]\n|name=AAdvantage\n|introduced=May 1, 1981}}\n\n'''AAdvantage''' is the [[frequent-flyer program]] of [[American Airlines]]. Launched May 1, 1981, it was the second such [[loyalty program]] in the world (after the first at [[Texas International Airlines]] in 1979), and remains the largest with more than 67 million members as of October 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thetravelinsider.info/airlinemismanagement/airlinederegulation2.htm|title=A History of US Airline Deregulation Part 4 :  1979 \u2013 2010 :  The Effects of Deregulation \u2013 Lower Fares, More Travel, Frequent Flier Programs |author=David M Rowell |date=August 13, 2010 |publisher=The Travel Insider|accessdate=September 21, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100816114115/http://www.thetravelinsider.info/airlinemismanagement/airlinederegulation2.htm| archivedate= August 16, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=American Airlines AAdvantage Program Details |url=https://www.aa.com/aa/i18nForward.do?p=/AAdvantage/programDetails/main.jsp&anchorEvent=false |website=Aa.com |accessdate=May 28, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090303121352/http://www.aa.com/aa/i18nForward.do?p=%2FAAdvantage%2FprogramDetails%2Fmain.jsp&anchorEvent=false |archivedate=March 3, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nMiles accumulated in the program allow members to redeem tickets, upgrade service class, or obtain free or discounted car rentals, hotel stays, merchandise, or other products and services through partners. The most active members, based on the amount and price of travel booked, are designated AAdvantage Gold, AAdvantage Platinum, AAdvantage Platinum Pro, and AAdvantage Executive Platinum elite members, with privileges such as separate check-in, priority upgrade and standby processing, or free upgrades. They also receive similar privileges from AA's partner airlines, particularly those in [[oneworld]].<ref>[http://www.aa.com/aa/i18nForward.do?p=/AAdvantage/partners/airlines/oneWorld.jsp#elite oneworld Alliance] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081220083602/http://www.aa.com/aa/i18nForward.do?p=%2FAAdvantage%2Fpartners%2Fairlines%2FoneWorld.jsp#elite |date=December 20, 2008 }}. Aa.com (2010-10-01). Retrieved on November 4, 2010.</ref> AAdvantage co-branded credit cards are also available and offer other benefits. These cards are issued by Barclaycard and CitiCards, subsidiary of [[Citigroup]] in the United States, by [[Butterfield Bank]] and [[Scotiabank]] in the Caribbean.\n\nAAdvantage allows one-way redemption, starting at 5,000 miles.<ref>[https://archive.is/20131218060310/http://www.aa.com/i18n/disclaimers/aadvantageAllPartnerChart.jsp ]</ref>\n\n== History ==\nIncreased competition following the 1978 [[Airline Deregulation Act]] prompted airline marketing professionals to develop ways to reward repeat customers and build brand loyalty. The first idea at American, a special \"loyalty fare\", was modified and expanded to offer free first class tickets and upgrades to first class for companions, or discounted coach tickets. Membership was seeded by searching AA's SABRE computer reservations system for recurring phone numbers. The 130,000 most frequent flyers, plus an additional 60,000 members of AA's Admirals Club were pre-enrolled and sent letters with their new account numbers. The name was selected by AA's advertising agency, and is consistent with other American Airlines programs featuring \"AA\" in the name and logo. The logo was designed by [[Massimo Vignelli]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vignelli.com/clients/corpro.html |title=Poster |website=Vignelli.com |accessdate=2016-09-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171207102220/http://www.vignelli.com/clients/corpro.html |archive-date=December 7, 2017 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nLess than a week later, rival [[United Airlines]] launched its [[MileagePlus]] program; other airlines followed in the ensuing months and years. The rapid appearance of competition changed the nature of the program, and as airlines began to compete on the features of their frequent flyer programs, AAdvantage liberalized its rules, established partnerships with hotel and rental car agencies, and offered promotions such as extra free beverages. In 1982 AAdvantage also became the first program to cooperate with an international carrier; members could accrue and redeem miles on British Airways flights to Europe.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Big 2\u20135 \u2013 Celebrating 25 Years of Frequent Flyer Programs |url=http://www.insideflyer.com/articles/o2.php?key=89 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130126105757/http://www.insideflyer.com/articles/o2.php?key=89 |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 26, 2013 |publisher=Frequent Flyer Network |website=Insideflyer.com |accessdate=June 28, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, major airlines, including American, offered triple miles. This led to increases in the number of miles needed for awards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://milecards.com/7753/the-united-mile-bubble-of-1988-what-it-means-today/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=January 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171016070918/http://milecards.com/7753/the-united-mile-bubble-of-1988-what-it-means-today/ |archive-date=October 16, 2017 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> During this time, miles, which originally had no expiration, began to have an expiration of three years, later reduced to 18 months, where an account would be closed if there was no activity during this time.\n\nIn 2005 American Airlines joined other major U.S. carriers in introducing an online shopping portal allowing shoppers to earn AAdvantage miles when shopping online.\n\nIn 2016, AAdvantage began crediting miles based on the amount of the airfare, not the distance traveled. This change was accompanied by increases in miles needed for an award.<ref>https://thepointsguy.com/2016/05/aadvantage-miles-distance-price/</ref>\n== Membership tiers ==\n\nThere are five membership tiers in AAdvantage: standard, Gold, Platinum, Platinum Pro and Executive Platinum.<ref>https://www.aa.com/i18n/aadvantage-program/aadvantage-program-updates.jsp</ref> \n\nGold status requires 25,000 flown elite qualifying miles or 30 flown elite qualifying segments plus $3,000 elite qualifying dollars. Gold status confers priority boarding, expedited security, complimentary same-day standby, discounted Admirals Club membership, and ability to earn and redeem 500-mile upgrades. All fares receive one free checked bag. Gold status also confers a 40% mileage bonus to all flown segments, a 500-mile minimum on each segment, complimentary auto-requested upgrades on flights 500 miles or less, complimentary preferred seats, 50% off Main Cabin Extra seats (complimentary at check-in), 24-hour upgrade window for flights over 500 miles with ability to upgrade one companion traveling on the same flight with 500-mile upgrades. Gold status provides oneworld Ruby status when flying a oneworld partner airline.\n\nPlatinum status requires 50,000 flown elite qualifying miles or 60 flown elite qualifying segments plus $6,000 elite qualifying dollars. Platinum status confers priority boarding, expedited security, priority baggage delivery, complimentary same-day standby, discounted Admirals Club membership, and ability to earn and redeem 500-mile upgrades. All fares receive one free checked bag except flights to many Central American and Caribbean nations, for which a $25 fee still applies.<ref>https://www.aa.com/i18n/travel-info/baggage/checked-baggage-policy.jsp</ref> Platinum status also confers a 60% mileage bonus to all flown segments, a 500-mile minimum on each segment, complimentary auto-requested upgrades on flights 500 miles or less, complimentary preferred seats, complimentary Main Cabin Extra seats, 48-hour upgrade window for flights over 500 miles with ability to upgrade one companion traveling on the same flight with 500-mile upgrades. It also confers a greater standing on upgrade lists and a special phone line. Platinum status provides oneworld Sapphire status when flying a oneworld partner airline.\n\nPlatinum Pro status requires 75,000 flown elite qualifying miles or 90 flown elite qualifying segments plus $9,000 elite qualifying dollars. Platinum Pro status confers priority boarding, expedited security, priority baggage delivery, complimentary same-day standby, discounted Admirals Club membership, and unlimited, auto-requested complimentary upgrades on flights regardless of number of miles. All fares receive two free checked bags. Platinum status also confers an 80% mileage bonus to all flown segments, a 500-mile minimum on each segment, complimentary preferred seats, complimentary Main Cabin Extra seats, 72-hour upgrade window for flights with ability to upgrade one companion traveling on the same flight with 500-mile upgrades. It also confers a greater standing on upgrade lists and a special phone line. Platinum Pro status provides oneworld Sapphire status when flying a oneworld partner airline.\n\nExecutive Platinum status requires 100,000 flown elite qualifying miles or 120 flown elite qualifying segments plus $15,000 elite qualifying dollars. Executive Platinum status confers priority boarding, expedited security, priority baggage delivery, complimentary same-day standby, complimentary same-day flight change, discounted Admirals Club membership, unlimited, auto-requested complimentary upgrades on flights regardless of number of miles, waived ticket service change, guaranteed availability in the Main Cabin, waitlist priority for purchased First or Business Class, complimentary alcoholic beverage and snack in Main Cabin. All fares receive three free checked bags. Executive Platinum status also confers a 120% mileage bonus to all flown segments, a 500-mile minimum on each segment, complimentary preferred seats, complimentary Main Cabin Extra seats, 100-hour upgrade window for flights with ability to upgrade one companion traveling on the same flight with 500-mile upgrades. It also confers a greater standing on upgrade lists and a special phone line. Executive Platinum status provides oneworld Emerald status when flying a oneworld partner airline.\n\nIndividuals who accumulate 1,000,000 miles earned on American receive lifetime Gold status. Individuals who accumulate 2,000,000 miles earned on American receive lifetime Platinum status.<ref>{{cite web |title=AAdvantage Elite Program|url=https://www.aa.com/i18n/AAdvantage/eliteStatus/main.jsp?from=Nav|website=Aa.com|format=JSP|accessdate=July 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBeginning January 1, 2016, elite qualifying points were removed from AAdvantage's tier qualification system, while elite qualifying miles and flown segments will continue to be used to determine tier status and qualification. Beginning January 1, 2017, elite qualifying dollars were added to AAdvantage's tier qualification status.<ref>{{cite web | title=AAdvantage Program Updates|url=https://www.aa.com/i18n/aadvantage-program/aadvantage-program-updates.jsp?from=Nav|website=Aa.com|format=JSP|accessdate=January 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Partnerships ==\nIn addition to its oneworld and [[American Eagle (airline brand)|American Eagle]] partnerships, American Airlines offers frequent flier partnerships with the following airlines:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com/i18n/aadvantage-program/miles/partners/partner-airlines.jsp|title=Partner airlines \u2013 Earn and redeem miles \u2013 American Airlines|website=www.aa.com|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n;Airlines\n* [[Air Tahiti Nui]]\n* [[Alaska Airlines]] (including [[Horizon Air]])\n* [[Cape Air]]\n* [[China Southern Airlines]]\n* [[Etihad Airways]]\n* [[Fiji Airways]]\n* [[Hawaiian Airlines]]\n* [[Interjet]]\n* [[Seaborne Airlines]]\n\n== Miles expiration ==\nMiles credited to AAdvantage originally had no expiration. In 1989, miles expired if there was no account activity for three years.<ref name=\"loyaltylobby1\">{{cite web|last=Ollila |first=John |url=http://loyaltylobby.com/2012/07/15/american-airlines-no-expiration-miles-award-chart-promise-lasted-for-23-years/ |title=American Airlines\u2019 No Expiration Miles & Award Chart Promise Lasted for 23 Years |website=LoyaltyLobby.com |date=2012-07-15 |accessdate=2016-09-09}}</ref> In 2012, miles expired if there was no activity for 18 months. Miles that were considered to have no expiration were subject to a 25% bonus but were then subject to the expiration policy.<ref>{{cite web|author=Terry Maxon |url=http://aviationblog.dallasnews.com/2012/07/american-airlines-to-do-away-with-non-expiring-aadvantage-miles.html/ |title=American Airlines to do away with non-expiring AAdvantage miles &#124; &#124; Dallas Morning News |publisher=Aviationblog.dallasnews.com |date=2012-07-13 |accessdate=2016-09-09}}</ref><ref name=\"loyaltylobby1\"/><ref>[http://www.farecomparecom/news/american-airlines-discontinues-aadvantage-miles-with-no-expiration-date/#/] {{dead link|date=September 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe AAdvantage program has an expiration policy that if no miles are gained or used during an 18-month period, the miles expire.<ref>{{cite web |title=AAdvantage Miles Expiration|url=http://www.aa.com/i18n/utility/FAQs/AAdvantage/ReactivateMiles.jsp|website=Aa.com|format=JSP|accessdate=December 3, 2015}}</ref> Expired miles cannot be used for [https://www.i-customerservicenumber.com/how-to-book-award-travel-on-american-airlines/ award travel]. To reactivate the previously earned miles, the AAdvantage plan ask members to pay from $200\u2013$600.<ref>{{cite web |title=Reactivate AAdvantage Miles|url=http://www.aa.com/i18n/AAdvantage/earnMiles/reactivate-miles.jsp|website=Aa.com|format=JSP|accessdate=December 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|American Airlines}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Frequent-flyer program}}\n{{American Airlines}}\n{{Customer loyalty programs}}\n\n[[Category:Frequent flyer programs]]\n[[Category:Frequent flyer programs associated with credit cards]]\n[[Category:American Airlines]]\n\n[[ru:AAdvantage]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox loyalty program\n|logo=AAdvantage logo.png\n|website={{url|aa.com/aadvantage}}\n|producttype=[[Frequent-flyer program]]\n|currentowner=[[American Airlines]]\n|name=AAdvantage\n|introduced=May 1, 1981}}\n\n'''AAdvantage''' is the [[frequent-flyer program]] of [[American Airlines]]. Launched May 1, 1981, it was the second such [[loyalty program]] in the world (after the first at [[Texas International Airlines]] in 1979), and remains the largest with more than 67 million members as of October 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thetravelinsider.info/airlinemismanagement/airlinederegulation2.htm|title=A History of US Airline Deregulation Part 4 :  1979 \u2013 2010 :  The Effects of Deregulation \u2013 Lower Fares, More Travel, Frequent Flier Programs |author=David M Rowell |date=August 13, 2010 |publisher=The Travel Insider|accessdate=September 21, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100816114115/http://www.thetravelinsider.info/airlinemismanagement/airlinederegulation2.htm| archivedate= August 16, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=American Airlines AAdvantage Program Details |url=https://www.aa.com/aa/i18nForward.do?p=/AAdvantage/programDetails/main.jsp&anchorEvent=false |website=Aa.com |accessdate=May 28, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090303121352/http://www.aa.com/aa/i18nForward.do?p=%2FAAdvantage%2FprogramDetails%2Fmain.jsp&anchorEvent=false |archivedate=March 3, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nMiles accumulated in the program allow members to redeem tickets, upgrade service class, or obtain free or discounted car rentals, hotel stays, merchandise, or other products and services through partners. The most active members, based on the amount and price of travel booked, are designated AAdvantage Gold, AAdvantage Platinum, AAdvantage Platinum Pro, and AAdvantage Executive Platinum elite members, with privileges such as separate check-in, priority upgrade and standby processing, or free upgrades. They also receive similar privileges from AA's partner airlines, particularly those in [[oneworld]].<ref>[http://www.aa.com/aa/i18nForward.do?p=/AAdvantage/partners/airlines/oneWorld.jsp#elite oneworld Alliance] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081220083602/http://www.aa.com/aa/i18nForward.do?p=%2FAAdvantage%2Fpartners%2Fairlines%2FoneWorld.jsp#elite |date=December 20, 2008 }}. Aa.com (2010-10-01). Retrieved on November 4, 2010.</ref> AAdvantage co-branded credit cards are also available and offer other benefits. These cards are issued by Barclaycard and CitiCards, subsidiary of [[Citigroup]] in the United States, by [[Butterfield Bank]] and [[Scotiabank]] in the Caribbean.\n\nAAdvantage allows one-way redemption, starting at 5,000 miles.<ref>[https://archive.is/20131218060310/http://www.aa.com/i18n/disclaimers/aadvantageAllPartnerChart.jsp ]</ref>\n\n== History ==\nIncreased competition following the 1978 [[Airline Deregulation Act]] prompted airline marketing professionals to develop ways to reward repeat customers and build brand loyalty. The first idea at American, a special \"loyalty fare\", was modified and expanded to offer free first class tickets and upgrades to first class for companions, or discounted coach tickets. Membership was seeded by searching AA's SABRE computer reservations system for recurring phone numbers. The 130,000 most frequent flyers, plus an additional 60,000 members of AA's Admirals Club were pre-enrolled and sent letters with their new account numbers. The name was selected by AA's advertising agency, and is consistent with other American Airlines programs featuring \"AA\" in the name and logo. The logo was designed by [[Massimo Vignelli]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vignelli.com/clients/corpro.html |title=Poster |website=Vignelli.com |accessdate=2016-09-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171207102220/http://www.vignelli.com/clients/corpro.html |archive-date=December 7, 2017 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nLess than a week later, rival [[United Airlines]] launched its [[MileagePlus]] program; other airlines followed in the ensuing months and years. The rapid appearance of competition changed the nature of the program, and as airlines began to compete on the features of their frequent flyer programs, AAdvantage liberalized its rules, established partnerships with hotel and rental car agencies, and offered promotions such as extra free beverages. In 1982 AAdvantage also became the first program to cooperate with an international carrier; members could accrue and redeem miles on British Airways flights to Europe.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Big 2\u20135 \u2013 Celebrating 25 Years of Frequent Flyer Programs |url=http://www.insideflyer.com/articles/o2.php?key=89 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130126105757/http://www.insideflyer.com/articles/o2.php?key=89 |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 26, 2013 |publisher=Frequent Flyer Network |website=Insideflyer.com |accessdate=June 28, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, major airlines, including American, offered triple miles. This led to increases in the number of miles needed for awards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://milecards.com/7753/the-united-mile-bubble-of-1988-what-it-means-today/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=January 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171016070918/http://milecards.com/7753/the-united-mile-bubble-of-1988-what-it-means-today/ |archive-date=October 16, 2017 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> During this time, miles, which originally had no expiration, began to have an expiration of three years, later reduced to 18 months, where an account would be closed if there was no activity during this time.\n\nIn 2005 American Airlines joined other major U.S. carriers in introducing an online shopping portal allowing shoppers to earn AAdvantage miles when shopping online.\n\nIn 2016, AAdvantage began crediting miles based on the amount of the airfare, not the distance traveled. This change was accompanied by increases in miles needed for an award.<ref>https://thepointsguy.com/2016/05/aadvantage-miles-distance-price/</ref>\n== Membership tiers ==\n\nThere are five membership tiers in AAdvantage: standard, Gold, Platinum, Platinum Pro and Executive Platinum.<ref>https://www.aa.com/i18n/aadvantage-program/aadvantage-program-updates.jsp</ref> \n\nGold status requires 25,000 flown elite qualifying miles or 30 flown elite qualifying segments plus $3,000 elite qualifying dollars. Gold status confers priority boarding, expedited security, complimentary same-day standby, discounted Admirals Club membership, and ability to earn and redeem 500-mile upgrades. All fares receive one free checked bag. Gold status also confers a 40% mileage bonus to all flown segments, a 500-mile minimum on each segment, complimentary auto-requested upgrades on flights 500 miles or less, complimentary preferred seats, 50% off Main Cabin Extra seats (complimentary at check-in), 24-hour upgrade window for flights over 500 miles with ability to upgrade one companion traveling on the same flight with 500-mile upgrades. Gold status provides oneworld Ruby status when flying a oneworld partner airline.\n\nPlatinum status requires 50,000 flown elite qualifying miles or 60 flown elite qualifying segments plus $6,000 elite qualifying dollars. Platinum status confers priority boarding, expedited security, priority baggage delivery, complimentary same-day standby, discounted Admirals Club membership, and ability to earn and redeem 500-mile upgrades. All fares receive one free checked bag except flights to many Central American and Caribbean nations, for which a $25 fee still applies.<ref>https://www.aa.com/i18n/travel-info/baggage/checked-baggage-policy.jsp</ref> Platinum status also confers a 60% mileage bonus to all flown segments, a 500-mile minimum on each segment, complimentary auto-requested upgrades on flights 500 miles or less, complimentary preferred seats, complimentary Main Cabin Extra seats, 48-hour upgrade window for flights over 500 miles with ability to upgrade one companion traveling on the same flight with 500-mile upgrades. It also confers a greater standing on upgrade lists and a special phone line. Platinum status provides oneworld Sapphire status when flying a oneworld partner airline.\n\nPlatinum Pro status requires 75,000 flown elite qualifying miles or 90 flown elite qualifying segments plus $9,000 elite qualifying dollars. Platinum Pro status confers priority boarding, expedited security, priority baggage delivery, complimentary same-day standby, discounted Admirals Club membership, and unlimited, auto-requested complimentary upgrades on flights regardless of number of miles. All fares receive two free checked bags. Platinum status also confers an 80% mileage bonus to all flown segments, a 500-mile minimum on each segment, complimentary preferred seats, complimentary Main Cabin Extra seats, 72-hour upgrade window for flights with ability to upgrade one companion traveling on the same flight with 500-mile upgrades. It also confers a greater standing on upgrade lists and a special phone line. Platinum Pro status provides oneworld Sapphire status when flying a oneworld partner airline.\n\nExecutive Platinum status requires 100,000 flown elite qualifying miles or 120 flown elite qualifying segments plus $15,000 elite qualifying dollars. Executive Platinum status confers priority boarding, expedited security, priority baggage delivery, complimentary same-day standby, complimentary same-day flight change, discounted Admirals Club membership, unlimited, auto-requested complimentary upgrades on flights regardless of number of miles, waived ticket service change, guaranteed availability in the Main Cabin, waitlist priority for purchased First or Business Class, complimentary alcoholic beverage and snack in Main Cabin. All fares receive three free checked bags. Executive Platinum status also confers a 120% mileage bonus to all flown segments, a 500-mile minimum on each segment, complimentary preferred seats, complimentary Main Cabin Extra seats, 100-hour upgrade window for flights with ability to upgrade one companion traveling on the same flight with 500-mile upgrades. It also confers a greater standing on upgrade lists and a special phone line. Executive Platinum status provides oneworld Emerald status when flying a oneworld partner airline.\n\nIndividuals who accumulate 1,000,000 miles earned on American receive lifetime Gold status. Individuals who accumulate 2,000,000 miles earned on American receive lifetime Platinum status.<ref>{{cite web |title=AAdvantage Elite Program|url=https://www.aa.com/i18n/AAdvantage/eliteStatus/main.jsp?from=Nav|website=Aa.com|format=JSP|accessdate=July 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBeginning January 1, 2016, elite qualifying points were removed from AAdvantage's tier qualification system, while elite qualifying miles and flown segments will continue to be used to determine tier status and qualification. Beginning January 1, 2017, elite qualifying dollars were added to AAdvantage's tier qualification status.<ref>{{cite web | title=AAdvantage Program Updates|url=https://www.aa.com/i18n/aadvantage-program/aadvantage-program-updates.jsp?from=Nav|website=Aa.com|format=JSP|accessdate=January 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Partnerships ==\nIn addition to its oneworld and [[American Eagle (airline brand)|American Eagle]] partnerships, American Airlines offers frequent flier partnerships with the following airlines:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com/i18n/aadvantage-program/miles/partners/partner-airlines.jsp|title=Partner airlines \u2013 Earn and redeem miles \u2013 American Airlines|website=www.aa.com|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n;Airlines\n* [[Air Tahiti Nui]]\n* [[Alaska Airlines]] (including [[Horizon Air]])\n* [[Cape Air]]\n* [[China Southern Airlines]]\n* [[Etihad Airways]]\n* [[Fiji Airways]]\n* [[Hawaiian Airlines]]\n* [[Interjet]]\n* [[Seaborne Airlines]]\n\n== Miles expiration ==\nMiles credited to AAdvantage originally had no expiration. In 1989, miles expired if there was no account activity for three years.<ref name=\"loyaltylobby1\">{{cite web|last=Ollila |first=John |url=http://loyaltylobby.com/2012/07/15/american-airlines-no-expiration-miles-award-chart-promise-lasted-for-23-years/ |title=American Airlines\u2019 No Expiration Miles & Award Chart Promise Lasted for 23 Years |website=LoyaltyLobby.com |date=2012-07-15 |accessdate=2016-09-09}}</ref> In 2012, miles expired if there was no activity for 18 months. Miles that were considered to have no expiration were subject to a 25% bonus but were then subject to the expiration policy.<ref>{{cite web|author=Terry Maxon |url=http://aviationblog.dallasnews.com/2012/07/american-airlines-to-do-away-with-non-expiring-aadvantage-miles.html/ |title=American Airlines to do away with non-expiring AAdvantage miles &#124; &#124; Dallas Morning News |publisher=Aviationblog.dallasnews.com |date=2012-07-13 |accessdate=2016-09-09}}</ref><ref name=\"loyaltylobby1\"/><ref>[http://www.farecomparecom/news/american-airlines-discontinues-aadvantage-miles-with-no-expiration-date/#/] {{dead link|date=September 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe AAdvantage program has an expiration policy that if no miles are gained or used during an 18-month period, the miles expire.<ref>{{cite web |title=AAdvantage Miles Expiration|url=http://www.aa.com/i18n/utility/FAQs/AAdvantage/ReactivateMiles.jsp|website=Aa.com|format=JSP|accessdate=December 3, 2015}}</ref> Expired miles cannot be used for [https://www.i-customerservicenumber.com/how-to-book-award-travel-on-american-airlines/ award travel]. To reactivate the previously earned miles, the AAdvantage plan ask members to pay from $200\u2013$600.<ref>{{cite web |title=Reactivate AAdvantage Miles|url=http://www.aa.com/i18n/AAdvantage/earnMiles/reactivate-miles.jsp|website=Aa.com|format=JSP|accessdate=December 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|American Airlines}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{American Airlines}}\n{{Customer loyalty programs}}\n\n[[Category:Frequent flyer programs]]\n[[Category:Frequent flyer programs associated with credit cards]]\n[[Category:American Airlines]]\n\n[[ru:AAdvantage]]\n", "name_user": "SCZMGE", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AAdvantage"}
{"title_page": "The Stand", "text_new": "{{short description|1978 novel by Stephen King}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox book| <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name         = The Stand\n| title_orig   =\n| translator   =\n| image        = The Stand cover.jpg\n| caption      = First edition cover\n| author       = [[Stephen King]]\n| cover_artist = John Cayea\n| country      = United States\n| language     = English\n| series       =\n| genre        = [[Apocalyptic and post-apocalyptic fiction|Post-apocalyptic]], [[Fantasy literature|fantasy]], [[horror fiction|horror]]\n| publisher    = [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]\n| release_date = October 3, 1978\n| media_type   = Print ([[hardcover]] and [[paperback]])\n| pages        = 823\n| isbn         = 978-0-385-12168-2\n| preceded_by  =\n| followed_by  =\n}}\n\n'''''The Stand''''' is a [[Apocalyptic and post-apocalyptic fiction|post-apocalyptic]] [[dark fantasy]] novel written by American author [[Stephen King]] and first published in 1978 by [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]. The plot centers on a [[pandemic]] of a weaponized strain of [[influenza]] that kills almost the entire world population. The few survivors, united in groups, establish a new social system and engage in confrontation with each other. In writing the book, King sought to create an epic in the spirit of ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]'' that was set in contemporary America. The book was difficult for King to write because of the large number of characters and storylines.\n\nIn 1990, ''The Stand'' was reprinted as a ''Complete and Uncut Edition''. King restored some fragments of texts that were initially reduced, revised the order of the chapters, shifted the novel's setting from 1980 to 10 years forward, and accordingly corrected a number of cultural references. The ''Complete and Uncut Edition'' of ''The Stand'' is considered to be King's longest stand-alone work. The book has sold 4.5 million copies.\n\n''The Stand'' was highly appreciated by literary critics and is considered one of King's best novels. It has been included in lists of the best books of all time by ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', the [[Modern Library]], [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] and the [[BBC]]. Reviewers praised the believability of the story, the relevance of the issues raised and the liveliness of the characters, but criticized the protractedness of individual episodes, the plot dualism and the deliberate denouement. A [[The Stand (1994 miniseries)|self-titled miniseries]] based on the novel was broadcast on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] in 1994. From 2008 to 2012, [[Marvel Comics]] published a [[The Stand (comics)|series of comics]] written by [[Roberto Aguirre-Sacasa]] and illustrated by [[Mike Perkins]]. A [[The Stand (upcoming miniseries)|miniseries]] to air on [[CBS All Access]] is in development.\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Plot==\nAn extremely contagious and lethal strain of [[influenza]], resistant to antibodies and vaccines, is developed as a [[Biological warfare|biological weapon]] within a secret [[United States Department of Defense|U.S. Department of Defense]] laboratory, and is accidentally released. The ''Complete and Uncut Edition'' includes a prologue detailing the development of the virus and the security breach that causes its release. The laboratory staff die, but security guard Charles Campion manages to escape and takes his family out of state. After a couple of days, his car crashes at a gas station in Arnette, Texas. The gas station employees and ambulance workers are infected when they take the dying Campion out of his car and to a hospital. The gas station owner infects his cousin, a highway patrolman, and the virus rapidly spreads uncontrollably from there. The [[United States Army]] attempts to isolate Arnette, going as far as to execute unarmed civilians, but the efforts are in vain \u2013 the virus, christened by journalists as the \"superflu\" or \"Captain Trips\", spreads across the country and travels beyond its borders, triggering a global [[pandemic]] of apocalyptic proportions. Approximately 99.4% of the world's population is infected and killed within a month. A prism of several personal tragedies describes the collapse of society, explosions of violence, the inability of the government and [[martial law]] to stop the pandemic, and the near-extinction of humanity. Many survivors of the virus also die, unable to accept the loss of their loved ones or survive in a world where they must fend for themselves.\n\nStuart Redman, one of the gas station employees, proves immune to the virus. He is forcibly held in a specialized center in Stovington, Vermont, in the hope that a treatment can be made. Redman escapes after the center's staff dies; he is forced to kill one of the members in self-defense. He meets with sociology professor Glen Bateman, pregnant college student Frannie Goldsmith, and teenage outcast Harold Lauder. Larry Underwood, a disillusioned pop singer, joins the group in the wake of his mother's death. Stuart and Frannie are drawn to each other and become lovers, to Harold's disappointment and resentment. The group share a common dream in which they see a 106-year-old black woman living in [[Hemingford, Nebraska|Hemingford Home, Nebraska]].<ref>King used Hemingford, NE for both novels, ''The Stand'', and ''It'', America's heartland location for Mother Abagail. '''The Denver Post''', ''USA Weekend'', March 19\u201320, 2010, usaweekend.com, page 2.</ref> The woman, Abagail Freemantle \u2013 better known as \"Mother Abagail\" \u2013 becomes the group's spiritual leader. She brings the group to [[Boulder, Colorado]], to which other survivors are attracted by her telepathic appeals. New additions to the group include Nick Andros, a [[deaf-mute]] deputy from Shoyo, Arkansas; Tom Cullen, a kind-hearted, mentally challenged man from May, Oklahoma; Nadine Cross, a teacher from New Hampshire; and Ralph Brentner, a good-natured farmer from Oklahoma. The group attempts to build a new society. They call their land the \"Free Zone\", organize funeral brigades and restore a supply of electricity.\n\nMeanwhile, in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]], [[Randall Flagg]], a \"dark man\" possessing supernatural abilities, creates his own society from people called by his visions. The people worship Flagg as a messiah and joyfully submit to his fascist dictatorship, in which drug addicts are crucified. Flagg rescues potentially cannibalistic prisoner Lloyd Henreid and makes him his right-hand man. A [[Pyromania|pyromaniac]] nicknamed \"the Trashcan Man\", after destroying oil tanks in [[Gary, Indiana]] and meeting a madman named \"the Kid\", joins Flagg's group and becomes a weapons specialist. Flagg prepares for war with Boulder. Mother Abagail, feeling that she has become prideful due to her pleasure at being a public figure, disappears into the wilderness on a journey of spiritual reconciliation. During her absence, the Free Zone's leadership committee decides to secretly send three people to Flagg's territory to act as spies. Harold and Nadine, tempted by Flagg through their dreams, stage an attack on the committee with a bomb. The explosion kills several people, but most of the committee members avoid the explosion thanks to Mother Abagail's return. Before dying of exhaustion, Mother Abagail reports God's will \u2013 Stuart, Glen, Larry and Ralph must go to Las Vegas and destroy Flagg.\n\nStuart breaks his leg en route and persuades the others to go on without him, telling them that God will provide for him if that is what is meant to happen. The remaining three are soon taken prisoner by Flagg's army. When Glen refuses to grovel before Flagg, he is killed by Lloyd. Flagg gathers his entire collective to witness the execution of Ralph and Larry. Moments before they are to be killed, the Trashcan Man arrives with a retrieved [[nuclear warhead]]. Flagg conjures a magical ball of energy in an attempt to silence a dissenter, but it is transformed into a giant glowing hand \u2014 \"the Hand of God\" \u2014 which detonates the bomb, destroying Las Vegas and killing all of Flagg's followers, in addition to Larry and Ralph. The inhabitants of Boulder anxiously await the birth of Frannie's baby. They fear that the child may not possess an immunity to the superflu and may die, implying a permanent end to humanity. Soon after she gives birth to her son, Stuart returns to Boulder, having been rescued first by a dog, Kojak, and then by Tom, the only survivor of the three Free Zone spies. The baby, Peter, manages to fight off the superflu. Stuart and Frannie decide to leave Boulder and move to [[Ogunquit]] as society is slowly reestablished. The ''Complete and Uncut Edition'' includes an [[epilogue]] in which Flagg, having survived the nuclear explosion, wakes up somewhere in the Southern Hemisphere. Regaining his former strength, he begins recruiting adherents among a preliterate, dark-skinned people.\n\n==Characters==\n{{Main|List of The Stand characters}}\n\n== Background ==\nIn [[Danse Macabre (book)|''Danse Macabre'']], King writes about the origins of ''The Stand'' at some length. One source was [[Patty Hearst]]'s case. The original idea was to create a novel about the episode because \"it seemed that only a novel might really succeed in explaining all the contradictions\".\n\nThe author also mentions [[George R. Stewart]]'s novel ''[[Earth Abides]]'', which describes the odyssey of one of the last human survivors after the population is nearly annihilated by a plague, as one of the main inspirations:\n\n<blockquote>\nWith my Patty Hearst book, I never found the right way in... and during that entire six-week period, something else was nagging very quietly at the back of my mind. It was a news story I had read about an accidental CBW spill in Utah. (...) This article called up memories of a novel called ''Earth Abides'', by George R. Stewart.\n</blockquote>\n\n<blockquote>\n(...) and one day while sitting at my typewriter, (...) I wrote\u2014just to write something: The world comes to an end but everybody in the SLA is somehow immune. Snake bit them. I looked at that for a while and then typed: No more gas shortages. That was sort of cheerful, in a horrible sort of way.\n<ref>{{Cite book\n  | last = King\n  | first = Stephen\n  | authorlink = Stephen King\n  | title = Stephen King's Danse Macabre\n  | publisher = Berkeley Trade\n  | page = 370\n  | isbn = 0-425-18160-X }}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n''The Stand'' was also planned by King as an epic ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]''\u2013type story in a contemporary American setting:\n\n<blockquote>For a long time\u2014ten years, at least\u2014I had wanted to write a fantasy epic like ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]'', only with an American setting. I just couldn't figure out how to do it. Then . . . after my wife and kids and I moved to Boulder, Colorado, I saw a ''[[60 Minutes]]'' segment on CBW (chemical-biological warfare). I never forgot the gruesome footage of the test mice shuddering, convulsing, and dying, all in twenty seconds or less. That got me remembering a chemical spill in Utah, that [[Dugway sheep incident|killed a bunch of sheep]] (these were canisters on their way to some burial ground; they fell off the truck and ruptured). I remembered a news reporter saying, 'If the winds had been blowing the other way, there was [[Salt Lake City]].' This incident later served as the basis of a movie called ''[[Rage (1972 film)|Rage]]'', starring [[George C. Scott]], but before it was released, I was deep into ''The Stand'', finally writing my American fantasy epic, set in a plague-decimated USA. Only instead of a hobbit, my hero was a Texan named Stu Redman, and instead of a Dark Lord, my villain was a ruthless drifter and supernatural madman named [[Randall Flagg]]. The land of [[Mordor]] ('where the shadows lie,' according to [[Tolkien]]) was played by Las Vegas.<ref>{{cite web\n  | last = King\n  | first = Stephen\n  | title = ''Stand: The Complete and Uncut Edition'': The Inspiration\n  | url=http://www.stephenking.com/library/novel/stand:_the_complete__uncut_edition_the_inspiration.html\n  | accessdate = 2008-08-24 }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nWhile writing ''The Stand'', King nearly stopped because of [[writer's block]].<ref>''On Writing'', Stephen King, 2000.</ref> Eventually, he reached the conclusion that the heroes were becoming too complacent, and were beginning to repeat all the same mistakes of their old society. In an attempt to resolve this, he added the part of the storyline where Harold and Nadine construct a bomb, which explodes in a Free Zone committee meeting, killing Nick Andros, Chad Norris, and Susan Stern. Later, Mother Abagail explains on her deathbed that God permitted the bombing because He was dissatisfied with the heroes' focus on petty politics, and not on the ultimate quest of destroying Flagg. When telling this story, King sardonically observed that the bomb saved the book, and that he only had to kill half of the core cast to do this.\n\n== Publication history ==\n\nThe novel was originally published in 1978 in hardcover, with a setting date of 1980, in abridged form. The first paperback release in 1980 changed the setting date to 1985. The novel marks the first appearance of [[Randall Flagg]], King's recurring antagonist, whom King would bring back many times in his later writings.\n\n{{Infobox book|\n| name         = The Stand: The Complete and Uncut Edition\n| title_orig   =\n| translator   =\n| image        = The Stand Uncut.jpg\n| caption      = ''The Complete and Uncut Edition'' cover\n| author       = [[Stephen King]]\n| cover_artist = John Cayea\n| country      = US\n| language     = English\n| series       =\n| genre        = [[Postapocalyptic]]\n| publisher    = [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]\n| release_date = May 1990\n| media_type   = Print\n| pages        = 1,152\n| isbn         = 978-0-385-19957-5\n| preceded_by  =\n| followed_by  =\n}}\n\nIn 1990, an unabridged edition of ''The Stand'' was published, billed as ''The Complete and Uncut Edition''. Published in hardcover by Doubleday in May 1990, this became the longest book published by King at 1,152 pages. When the novel was originally published in 1978, Doubleday warned King that the book's size would make it too expensive for the market to bear.<ref>{{cite book |last= King |first= Stephen |date= 1990 |title= The Stand: The Complete And Uncut Edition |publisher= [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]] |page= xiii |isbn=978-0-307-74368-8 }}</ref> As a result, he cut about 400 pages (around 150,000 words) from the original manuscript. This edition reinstates most of the deleted pages (as selected by King), as well as updates the setting from the 1980s to the 1990s. This new edition features a new preface by King, and illustrations by [[Bernie Wrightson]]. Additionally, Doubleday published a deluxe edition of ''The Stand: The Complete and Uncut Edition'', limited to 1,250 numbered copies and 52 lettered copies. This edition, known as the \"Coffin Box\" edition due to the book being housed in a wooden case, was signed by King and Wrightson.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/03/09/lifetimes/king-stand.html |title=ARMAGEDDON, COMPLETE AND UNCUT|date=1997-03-09| work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.veryfinebooks.com/Stephen_King_The_Stand_Signed_First_Edition_p/sk200.htm |title=Stephen King The Stand Signed Limited Coffin Edition |publisher=VeryFineBooks.com |accessdate=2012-07-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedarktower.org/palaver/showwiki.php?title=Stand+The+-+S+L |title=Stand, The \u2013 S/L \u2013 Palaver |publisher=Thedarktower.org |accessdate=2012-07-02}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n\n''The Stand'' was nominated for the [[World Fantasy Award for Best Novel]] in 1979, and was adapted into both a [[The Stand (1994 miniseries)|television miniseries]] for ABC and a [[The Stand (comics)|graphic novel]] published by [[Marvel Comics]].<ref name=\"rama1\"/><ref name=\"WWE-1979\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.worldswithoutend.com/books_year_index.asp?year=1979\n| title = 1979 Award Winners & Nominees\n| work = Worlds Without End\n| accessdate=2009-07-22\n}}</ref> In 2003, the novel was listed at number 53 on the [[BBC]]'s [[The Big Read]] poll.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/bigread/top100_2.shtml|title=The Big Read \u2013 Top 100 Books |date=April 2003 |access-date=October 3, 2017 |publisher=[[BBC]] }}</ref>\n\n==Adaptations==\n\n=== Television ===\n{{Main|The Stand (1994 miniseries)|The Stand (upcoming miniseries)}}\n\nA movie adaptation of ''The Stand'' was in [[development hell]] for over 10 years. During the 1980s, Stephen King had planned a theatrical film, with [[George A. Romero]] directing and himself writing, not trusting anybody else with the project. However, writing a workable screenplay proved difficult, due to the novel's length. King talked about adapting it for television, but was informed that the television networks did not \"want to see the end of the world, particularly in prime time.\" Eventually King allowed screenwriter [[Rospo Pallenberg]], who was a fan of ''The Stand'', to write his own adaptation of the novel. Pallenberg's script would clock the film in at close to three hours, while still staying true to the novel. Everyone liked the script; however, just as it was about to finally come together, [[Warner Bros.]] backed out of the project.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.subcin.com/risefallstand.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20060708173256/http://www.subcin.com/risefallstand.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 8, 2006 |title=THE RISE AND FALL OF \"THE STAND\" |publisher=subcin.com |author=Hixx, Don Alex |accessdate=2013-04-18 |df=mdy-all }}{{Unreliable source?|date=August 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] eventually offered Stephen King the chance to make ''The Stand'' into an eight-hour [[television miniseries|miniseries]]. King wrote a new screenplay (toned down slightly for television). The [[The Stand (1994 miniseries)|miniseries]] was broadcast in 1994, directed by [[Mick Garris]], and starred such actors as [[Gary Sinise]], [[Adam Storke]], [[Molly Ringwald]], [[Rob Lowe]], [[Miguel Ferrer]], [[Laura San Giacomo]], [[Jamey Sheridan]], [[Ossie Davis]], [[Ruby Dee]], [[Bill Fagerbakke]], and [[Shawnee Smith]], with notable cameos including [[John Landis]], [[Ed Harris]], [[Kathy Bates]], [[Sam Raimi]], and King himself. Parts of the miniseries were shot in [[Salt Lake City]], [[Utah State Prison]], [[Sundance Resort|Sundance]], [[Orem]], [[Provo Canyon]], and [[Salina, Utah|Salina]] in [[Utah]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=D'Arc|first1=James V.|title=When Hollywood came to town: a history of moviemaking in Utah|date=2010|publisher=Gibbs Smith|location=Layton, Utah|isbn=9781423605874|edition=1st}}</ref>\n\nBetween 2011 and 2016, [[Warner Bros. Pictures]] and [[CBS Films]] were developing a feature-length film adaptation of ''The Stand''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/blogs/heat-vision/stephen-kings-stand-heading-big-94805|title=Stephen King's 'The Stand' Heading to the Big Screen (Exclusive) | work=The Hollywood Reporter | first=Borys|last=Kit|date=2011-01-31|accessdate=2014-08-02}}</ref> In August 2011, director [[David Yates]] and screenwriter [[Steve Kloves]], known for their collaboration on the ''[[Harry Potter (film series)|Harry Potter]]'' films, were hired to direct/write a multimovie version of ''The Stand'',<ref>{{cite web|last=McWeeny |first=Drew |url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/motion-captured/posts/exclusive-potter-masterminds-steve-kloves-and-david-yates-reunite-for-the-stand |title=Exclusive: Potter masterminds Steve Kloves and David Yates reunite for The Stand |publisher=Hitfix.com |date=2012-06-28 |accessdate=2012-07-02}}</ref> but left the project in October 2011, as Yates felt it would work better as a miniseries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://whatculture.com/film/david-yates-says-hes-not-making-the-stand-because-it-should-be-tv-mini-series.php |title=David Yates Says He\u2019s Not Making THE STAND Because It Should Be TV Mini-Series |publisher=Whatculture.com |date=2011-11-12 |accessdate=2012-07-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117171113/http://whatculture.com/film/david-yates-says-hes-not-making-the-stand-because-it-should-be-tv-mini-series.php |archivedate=January 17, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Both [[Ben Affleck]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Thompson|first=Anne|title=More Details on Ben Affleck in Snyder's Superman/Batman UPDATED|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/thompsononhollywood/be-affleck-is-the-new-batman-in-snyders-superman-batman|publisher=IndieWire|accessdate=2014-08-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203031502/http://blogs.indiewire.com/thompsononhollywood/be-affleck-is-the-new-batman-in-snyders-superman-batman|archive-date=December 3, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and [[Scott Cooper (director)|Scott Cooper]] dropped out over creative differences with the studio.<ref>{{cite web|last=Shaw|first=Lucas|title=\u2018Crazy Heart\u2019 Director Scott Cooper Exits Warner Bros.\u2019 Stephen King Adaptation (Exclusive)|url=https://www.thewrap.com/crazy-heart-director-scott-cooper-stephen-king|publisher=The Wrap|accessdate=2014-08-02}}</ref> On February 25, 2014, [[Josh Boone (director)|Josh Boone]] was hired to write and direct the adaptation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/fault-stars-director-talks-tackle-682033||title='Fault In Our Stars' Director in Talks to Tackle Stephen King's 'The Stand'|last=Kit|first=Borys|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=2014-02-25|accessdate=2014-09-10}}</ref> He later revealed that he wanted [[Christian Bale]] to play Randall Flagg and [[Matthew McConaughey]] for the role of Stu Redman.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/JoshBooneMovies/status/503313944413761536|title=I have always wanted McConaughey as Stu and Bale as Flagg. Still not sure how that story leaked \u2013 just not true.|author=Josh Boone|date=23 Aug 2014|publisher=Twitter}}</ref> By September 10, 2014, the script had been completed and pre-production was underway.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/the-stand-movie-details-three-hour-cut-josh-boone/|title=Director Josh Boone On THE STAND, Fidelity to the Novel, Script Status, and Whether He'll Direct LESTAT|last=Cook|first=Tommy|work=Collider.com|date=2014-09-10|accessdate=2014-09-10}}/</ref> In November, Boone planned to split his adaptation into four full-length feature films in an effort to remain true to the breadth of King's sprawling novel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://smodcast.com/episodes/hollywood-babble-on-bonus-babble-on-hollywood-josh-boone-the-fault-in-our-stand/|title=Hollywood Babble-On Bonus: Babble on Hollywood: Josh Boone: The Fault In Our Stand|author=|date=|work=smodcast.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141120170433/http://smodcast.com/episodes/hollywood-babble-on-bonus-babble-on-hollywood-josh-boone-the-fault-in-our-stand|archivedate=November 20, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>Fleming Jr., Mike (November 21, 2014). [https://web.archive.org/web/20160221020603/http://deadline.com/2014/11/the-stand-stephen-king-josh-boone-four-films-1201291709/ \"Josh Boone Says Warner Bros Will Turn Stephen King\u2019s \u2018The Stand\u2019 Into Four Films.\"] ''Deadline''.</ref> In June 2015, Warner Bros. proposed an eight-part [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] miniseries to set up the story, which would culminate in Josh Boone's film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/447603-stephen-kings-the-stand-to-begin-as-eight-part-television-miniseries|title=Stephen King's The Stand to Begin as an Eight-Part Television Miniseries! - ComingSoon.net|date=June 5, 2015|work=comingsoon.net|accessdate=February 6, 2017}}</ref> However, in February 2016, ''The Stand'' project was put on hold and the rights reverted to CBS Films.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/josh-boone-stephen-king-revival-the-stand-the-fault-in-our-stars-1201694681/|title=\u2018The Fault In Our Stars\u2019 Helmer Josh Boone Pushes Back Stephen King\u2019s \u2018The Stand\u2019 To Next Direct \u2018Revival\u2019|last=|first=|date=February 2016|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, King talked of doing an extended TV series on Showtime or [[CBS All Access]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2017/09/stephen-king-on-movies-geralds-game-1922-it-the-stand.html|title=Stephen King on His New Netflix Movies, It, and His Big Year|last=Buchanan|first=Kyle|work=[[Vulture.com]]|date=September 25, 2017|accessdate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> In January 2019, a 10-hour limited series was ordered by CBS Television Studios to be broadcast on CBS All Access.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/stephen-king-stand-series-order-cbs-1203123968/|title=Stephen King\u2019s \u2018The Stand\u2019 Gets Series Order at CBS All Access|last=Low|first=Elaine|work=[[Variety.com]]|date=January 30, 2019|accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref> [[James Marsden]], [[Amber Heard]], [[Whoopi Goldberg]], [[Greg Kinnear]], [[Odessa Young]], and [[Henry Zaga]] were all in consideration for the roles of Stu Redman, Nadine Cross, Mother Abagail, Glen Bateman, Frannie Goldsmith, and Nick Andros, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/stephen-kings-the-stand-casting-rumors/|title=Stephen King's The Stand TV Adaptation Reportedly Eyeing Some Huge Stars|last=Solis|first=Jorge|work=[[cbr.com]]|date=June 22, 2019|accessdate=June 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Comics===\n{{Main|The Stand (comics)}}\n[[Marvel Comics]] adapted ''The Stand'' into a series of six five-issue comic book [[Limited series (comics)|miniseries]].<ref name=\"rama1\">[http://forum.newsarama.com/showthread.php?t=150380 King: Marvel to Adapt The Stand as a graphic novel]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [[Newsarama]], March 17, 2008</ref> The series was written by [[Roberto Aguirre-Sacasa]] and illustrated by [[Mike Perkins]]. Colorist [[Laura Martin]], letterer [[Chris Eliopoulos]], and cover artist [[Lee Bermejo]] were also on the staff. The first issue of ''[[The Stand: Captain Trips]]'' was released on September 10, 2008.<ref name=\"MarvelAnnounces\">{{cite web |url=http://marvel.com/news/comicstories.3768.WW_Philly_2008%7Ecolon%7E_The_Stand |title=Wizard World Philadelphia 2008: Stephen King's The Stand |author=Stevens, Tim |date=2008-05-31 |publisher=Marvel.com |accessdate=2014-08-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100818014514/http://marvel.com/news/comicstories.3768.WW_Philly_2008~colon~_The_Stand |archive-date=August 18, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n[[Metallica]] derived the title for its song \"Ride the Lightning\" from a quote from ''The Stand''.<ref name=\"HowWeMade\">{{cite web |url=https://www.loudersound.com/features/metallica-how-we-made-ride-the-lightning |title=How We Made Ride the Lightning |author=Everley, Dave |date=2016-05-19 |publisher=loudersound.com |accessdate=2019-06-03|df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[The Alarm]] had a song on the album ''[[Declaration (The Alarm album)|Declaration]]''  called \"The Stand (Prophecy)\" as an homage to the book. The song contained certain lyrics directly related to the book, such as \"I met the walking dude, religious, with his worn out cowboy boots,\" and \"Hey Trashcan, where you going boy?\"   \nThe main chorus of the song was \"Come on down and meet your maker, come on down and make the stand.\"{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nThe title track to the album ''[[Among the Living]]'' by the band [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]] is based on the novel.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{isfdb title|id=1148|title=The Stand}}\n* [http://www.bookpoi.com/the_stand_by_stephen_king_first_edition_identification.html Bookpoi]\u2014How to identify first edition copies of ''The Stand'' by Stephen King.\n\n{{The Stand}}\n{{Stephen King}}\n{{DarkTower}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stand, The}}\n[[Category:The Stand]]\n[[Category:1978 American novels]]\n[[Category:American post-apocalyptic novels]]\n[[Category:American horror novels]]\n[[Category:Biological weapons in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Novels about dreams]]\n[[Category:Novels about nightmares]]\n[[Category:Novels about religion]]\n[[Category:Fictional events]]\n[[Category:Novels by Stephen King]]\n[[Category:Novels set in the 1980s]]\n[[Category:Novels set in the 1990s]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Boulder, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Novels set in the Las Vegas Valley]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Maine]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Novels set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Novels set in New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Texas]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Vermont]]\n[[Category:Novels about viral outbreaks]]\n[[Category:Doubleday (publisher) books]]\n[[Category:Novels adapted into television programs]]\n[[Category:Demon novels]]\n[[Category:Novels adapted into comics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1978 novel by Stephen King}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox book| <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name         = The Stand\n| title_orig   =\n| translator   =\n| image        = The Stand cover.jpg\n| caption      = First edition cover\n| author       = [[Stephen King]]\n| cover_artist = John Cayea\n| country      = United States\n| language     = English\n| series       =\n| genre        = [[Apocalyptic and post-apocalyptic fiction|Post-apocalyptic]], [[Fantasy literature|fantasy]], [[horror fiction|horror]]\n| publisher    = [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]\n| release_date = October 3, 1978\n| media_type   = Print ([[hardcover]] and [[paperback]])\n| pages        = 823\n| isbn         = 978-0-385-12168-2\n| preceded_by  =\n| followed_by  =\n}}\n\n'''''The Stand''''' is a [[Apocalyptic and post-apocalyptic fiction|post-apocalyptic]] [[dark fantasy]] novel written by American author [[Stephen King]] and first published in 1978 by [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]. The plot centers on a [[pandemic]] of a weaponized strain of [[influenza]] that kills almost the entire world population. The few survivors, united in groups, establish a new social system and engage in confrontation with each other. In writing the book, King sought to create an epic in the spirit of ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]'' that was set in contemporary America. The book was difficult for King to write because of the large number of characters and storylines.\n\nIn 1990, ''The Stand'' was reprinted as a ''Complete and Uncut Edition''. King restored some fragments of texts that were initially reduced, revised the order of the chapters, shifted the novel's setting from 1980 to 10 years forward, and accordingly corrected a number of cultural references. The ''Complete and Uncut Edition'' of ''The Stand'' is considered to be King's longest stand-alone work. The book has sold 4.5 million copies.\n\n''The Stand'' was highly appreciated by literary critics and is considered one of King's best novels. It has been included in lists of the best books of all time by ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', the [[Modern Library]], [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] and the [[BBC]]. Reviewers praised the believability of the story, the relevance of the issues raised and the liveliness of the characters, but criticized the protractedness of individual episodes, the plot dualism and the deliberate denouement. A [[The Stand (1994 miniseries)|self-titled miniseries]] based on the novel was broadcast on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] in 1994. From 2008 to 2012, [[Marvel Comics]] published a [[The Stand (comics)|series of comics]] written by [[Roberto Aguirre-Sacasa]] and illustrated by [[Mike Perkins]]. A [[The Stand (upcoming miniseries)|miniseries]] to air on [[CBS All Access]] is in development.\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Plot==\nAn extremely contagious and lethal strain of [[influenza]], resistant to antibodies and vaccines, is developed as a [[Biological warfare|biological weapon]] within a secret [[United States Department of Defense|U.S. Department of Defense]] laboratory, and is accidentally released. The ''Complete and Uncut Edition'' includes a prologue detailing the development of the virus and the security breach that causes its release. The laboratory staff die, but security guard Charles Campion manages to escape and takes his family out of state. After a couple of days, his car crashes at a gas station in Arnette, Texas. The gas station employees and ambulance workers are infected when they take the dying Campion out of his car and to a hospital. The gas station owner infects his cousin, a highway patrolman, and the virus rapidly spreads uncontrollably from there. The [[United States Army]] attempts to isolate Arnette, going as far as to execute unarmed civilians, but the efforts are in vain \u2013 the virus, christened by journalists as the \"superflu\" or \"Captain Trips\", spreads across the country and travels beyond its borders, triggering a global [[pandemic]] of apocalyptic proportions. Approximately 99.4% of the world's population is infected and killed within a month. A prism of several personal tragedies describes the collapse of society, explosions of violence, the inability of the government and [[martial law]] to stop the pandemic, and the near-extinction of humanity. Many survivors of the virus also die, unable to accept the loss of their loved ones or survive in a world where they must fend for themselves.\n\nStuart Redman, one of the gas station employees, proves immune to the virus. He is forcibly held in a specialized center in Stovington, Vermont, in the hope that a treatment can be made. Redman escapes after the center's staff dies; he is forced to kill one of the members in self-defense. He meets with sociology professor Glen Bateman, pregnant college student Frannie Goldsmith, and teenage outcast Harold Lauder. Larry Underwood, a disillusioned pop singer, joins the group in the wake of his mother's death. Stuart and Frannie are drawn to each other and become lovers, to Harold's disappointment and resentment. The group share a common dream in which they see a 108-year-old black woman living in [[Hemingford, Nebraska|Hemingford Home, Nebraska]].<ref>King used Hemingford, NE for both novels, ''The Stand'', and ''It'', America's heartland location for Mother Abagail. '''The Denver Post''', ''USA Weekend'', March 19\u201320, 2010, usaweekend.com, page 2.</ref> The woman, Abagail Freemantle \u2013 better known as \"Mother Abagail\" \u2013 becomes the group's spiritual leader. She brings the group to [[Boulder, Colorado]], to which other survivors are attracted by her telepathic appeals. New additions to the group include Nick Andros, a [[deaf-mute]] deputy from Shoyo, Arkansas; Tom Cullen, a kind-hearted, mentally challenged man from May, Oklahoma; Nadine Cross, a teacher from New Hampshire; and Ralph Brentner, a good-natured farmer from Oklahoma. The group attempts to build a new society. They call their land the \"Free Zone\", organize funeral brigades and restore a supply of electricity.\n\nMeanwhile, in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]], [[Randall Flagg]], a \"dark man\" possessing supernatural abilities, creates his own society from people called by his visions. The people worship Flagg as a messiah and joyfully submit to his fascist dictatorship, in which drug addicts are crucified. Flagg rescues potentially cannibalistic prisoner Lloyd Henreid and makes him his right-hand man. A [[Pyromania|pyromaniac]] nicknamed \"the Trashcan Man\", after destroying oil tanks in [[Gary, Indiana]] and meeting a madman named \"the Kid\", joins Flagg's group and becomes a weapons specialist. Flagg prepares for war with Boulder. Mother Abagail, feeling that she has become prideful due to her pleasure at being a public figure, disappears into the wilderness on a journey of spiritual reconciliation. During her absence, the Free Zone's leadership committee decides to secretly send three people to Flagg's territory to act as spies. Harold and Nadine, tempted by Flagg through their dreams, stage an attack on the committee with a bomb. The explosion kills several people, but most of the committee members avoid the explosion thanks to Mother Abagail's return. Before dying of exhaustion, Mother Abagail reports God's will \u2013 Stuart, Glen, Larry and Ralph must go to Las Vegas and destroy Flagg.\n\nStuart breaks his leg en route and persuades the others to go on without him, telling them that God will provide for him if that is what is meant to happen. The remaining three are soon taken prisoner by Flagg's army. When Glen refuses to grovel before Flagg, he is killed by Lloyd. Flagg gathers his entire collective to witness the execution of Ralph and Larry. Moments before they are to be killed, the Trashcan Man arrives with a retrieved [[nuclear warhead]]. Flagg conjures a magical ball of energy in an attempt to silence a dissenter, but it is transformed into a giant glowing hand \u2014 \"the Hand of God\" \u2014 which detonates the bomb, destroying Las Vegas and killing all of Flagg's followers, in addition to Larry and Ralph. The inhabitants of Boulder anxiously await the birth of Frannie's baby. They fear that the child may not possess an immunity to the superflu and may die, implying a permanent end to humanity. Soon after she gives birth to her son, Stuart returns to Boulder, having been rescued first by a dog, Kojak, and then by Tom, the only survivor of the three Free Zone spies. The baby, Peter, manages to fight off the superflu. Stuart and Frannie decide to leave Boulder and move to [[Ogunquit]] as society is slowly reestablished. The ''Complete and Uncut Edition'' includes an [[epilogue]] in which Flagg, having survived the nuclear explosion, wakes up somewhere in the Southern Hemisphere. Regaining his former strength, he begins recruiting adherents among a preliterate, dark-skinned people.\n\n==Characters==\n{{Main|List of The Stand characters}}\n\n== Background ==\nIn [[Danse Macabre (book)|''Danse Macabre'']], King writes about the origins of ''The Stand'' at some length. One source was [[Patty Hearst]]'s case. The original idea was to create a novel about the episode because \"it seemed that only a novel might really succeed in explaining all the contradictions\".\n\nThe author also mentions [[George R. Stewart]]'s novel ''[[Earth Abides]]'', which describes the odyssey of one of the last human survivors after the population is nearly annihilated by a plague, as one of the main inspirations:\n\n<blockquote>\nWith my Patty Hearst book, I never found the right way in... and during that entire six-week period, something else was nagging very quietly at the back of my mind. It was a news story I had read about an accidental CBW spill in Utah. (...) This article called up memories of a novel called ''Earth Abides'', by George R. Stewart.\n</blockquote>\n\n<blockquote>\n(...) and one day while sitting at my typewriter, (...) I wrote\u2014just to write something: The world comes to an end but everybody in the SLA is somehow immune. Snake bit them. I looked at that for a while and then typed: No more gas shortages. That was sort of cheerful, in a horrible sort of way.\n<ref>{{Cite book\n  | last = King\n  | first = Stephen\n  | authorlink = Stephen King\n  | title = Stephen King's Danse Macabre\n  | publisher = Berkeley Trade\n  | page = 370\n  | isbn = 0-425-18160-X }}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n''The Stand'' was also planned by King as an epic ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]''\u2013type story in a contemporary American setting:\n\n<blockquote>For a long time\u2014ten years, at least\u2014I had wanted to write a fantasy epic like ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]'', only with an American setting. I just couldn't figure out how to do it. Then . . . after my wife and kids and I moved to Boulder, Colorado, I saw a ''[[60 Minutes]]'' segment on CBW (chemical-biological warfare). I never forgot the gruesome footage of the test mice shuddering, convulsing, and dying, all in twenty seconds or less. That got me remembering a chemical spill in Utah, that [[Dugway sheep incident|killed a bunch of sheep]] (these were canisters on their way to some burial ground; they fell off the truck and ruptured). I remembered a news reporter saying, 'If the winds had been blowing the other way, there was [[Salt Lake City]].' This incident later served as the basis of a movie called ''[[Rage (1972 film)|Rage]]'', starring [[George C. Scott]], but before it was released, I was deep into ''The Stand'', finally writing my American fantasy epic, set in a plague-decimated USA. Only instead of a hobbit, my hero was a Texan named Stu Redman, and instead of a Dark Lord, my villain was a ruthless drifter and supernatural madman named [[Randall Flagg]]. The land of [[Mordor]] ('where the shadows lie,' according to [[Tolkien]]) was played by Las Vegas.<ref>{{cite web\n  | last = King\n  | first = Stephen\n  | title = ''Stand: The Complete and Uncut Edition'': The Inspiration\n  | url=http://www.stephenking.com/library/novel/stand:_the_complete__uncut_edition_the_inspiration.html\n  | accessdate = 2008-08-24 }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nWhile writing ''The Stand'', King nearly stopped because of [[writer's block]].<ref>''On Writing'', Stephen King, 2000.</ref> Eventually, he reached the conclusion that the heroes were becoming too complacent, and were beginning to repeat all the same mistakes of their old society. In an attempt to resolve this, he added the part of the storyline where Harold and Nadine construct a bomb, which explodes in a Free Zone committee meeting, killing Nick Andros, Chad Norris, and Susan Stern. Later, Mother Abagail explains on her deathbed that God permitted the bombing because He was dissatisfied with the heroes' focus on petty politics, and not on the ultimate quest of destroying Flagg. When telling this story, King sardonically observed that the bomb saved the book, and that he only had to kill half of the core cast to do this.\n\n== Publication history ==\n\nThe novel was originally published in 1978 in hardcover, with a setting date of 1980, in abridged form. The first paperback release in 1980 changed the setting date to 1985. The novel marks the first appearance of [[Randall Flagg]], King's recurring antagonist, whom King would bring back many times in his later writings.\n\n{{Infobox book|\n| name         = The Stand: The Complete and Uncut Edition\n| title_orig   =\n| translator   =\n| image        = The Stand Uncut.jpg\n| caption      = ''The Complete and Uncut Edition'' cover\n| author       = [[Stephen King]]\n| cover_artist = John Cayea\n| country      = US\n| language     = English\n| series       =\n| genre        = [[Postapocalyptic]]\n| publisher    = [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]\n| release_date = May 1990\n| media_type   = Print\n| pages        = 1,152\n| isbn         = 978-0-385-19957-5\n| preceded_by  =\n| followed_by  =\n}}\n\nIn 1990, an unabridged edition of ''The Stand'' was published, billed as ''The Complete and Uncut Edition''. Published in hardcover by Doubleday in May 1990, this became the longest book published by King at 1,152 pages. When the novel was originally published in 1978, Doubleday warned King that the book's size would make it too expensive for the market to bear.<ref>{{cite book |last= King |first= Stephen |date= 1990 |title= The Stand: The Complete And Uncut Edition |publisher= [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]] |page= xiii |isbn=978-0-307-74368-8 }}</ref> As a result, he cut about 400 pages (around 150,000 words) from the original manuscript. This edition reinstates most of the deleted pages (as selected by King), as well as updates the setting from the 1980s to the 1990s. This new edition features a new preface by King, and illustrations by [[Bernie Wrightson]]. Additionally, Doubleday published a deluxe edition of ''The Stand: The Complete and Uncut Edition'', limited to 1,250 numbered copies and 52 lettered copies. This edition, known as the \"Coffin Box\" edition due to the book being housed in a wooden case, was signed by King and Wrightson.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/03/09/lifetimes/king-stand.html |title=ARMAGEDDON, COMPLETE AND UNCUT|date=1997-03-09| work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.veryfinebooks.com/Stephen_King_The_Stand_Signed_First_Edition_p/sk200.htm |title=Stephen King The Stand Signed Limited Coffin Edition |publisher=VeryFineBooks.com |accessdate=2012-07-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedarktower.org/palaver/showwiki.php?title=Stand+The+-+S+L |title=Stand, The \u2013 S/L \u2013 Palaver |publisher=Thedarktower.org |accessdate=2012-07-02}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n\n''The Stand'' was nominated for the [[World Fantasy Award for Best Novel]] in 1979, and was adapted into both a [[The Stand (1994 miniseries)|television miniseries]] for ABC and a [[The Stand (comics)|graphic novel]] published by [[Marvel Comics]].<ref name=\"rama1\"/><ref name=\"WWE-1979\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.worldswithoutend.com/books_year_index.asp?year=1979\n| title = 1979 Award Winners & Nominees\n| work = Worlds Without End\n| accessdate=2009-07-22\n}}</ref> In 2003, the novel was listed at number 53 on the [[BBC]]'s [[The Big Read]] poll.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/bigread/top100_2.shtml|title=The Big Read \u2013 Top 100 Books |date=April 2003 |access-date=October 3, 2017 |publisher=[[BBC]] }}</ref>\n\n==Adaptations==\n\n=== Television ===\n{{Main|The Stand (1994 miniseries)|The Stand (upcoming miniseries)}}\n\nA movie adaptation of ''The Stand'' was in [[development hell]] for over 10 years. During the 1980s, Stephen King had planned a theatrical film, with [[George A. Romero]] directing and himself writing, not trusting anybody else with the project. However, writing a workable screenplay proved difficult, due to the novel's length. King talked about adapting it for television, but was informed that the television networks did not \"want to see the end of the world, particularly in prime time.\" Eventually King allowed screenwriter [[Rospo Pallenberg]], who was a fan of ''The Stand'', to write his own adaptation of the novel. Pallenberg's script would clock the film in at close to three hours, while still staying true to the novel. Everyone liked the script; however, just as it was about to finally come together, [[Warner Bros.]] backed out of the project.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.subcin.com/risefallstand.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20060708173256/http://www.subcin.com/risefallstand.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 8, 2006 |title=THE RISE AND FALL OF \"THE STAND\" |publisher=subcin.com |author=Hixx, Don Alex |accessdate=2013-04-18 |df=mdy-all }}{{Unreliable source?|date=August 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] eventually offered Stephen King the chance to make ''The Stand'' into an eight-hour [[television miniseries|miniseries]]. King wrote a new screenplay (toned down slightly for television). The [[The Stand (1994 miniseries)|miniseries]] was broadcast in 1994, directed by [[Mick Garris]], and starred such actors as [[Gary Sinise]], [[Adam Storke]], [[Molly Ringwald]], [[Rob Lowe]], [[Miguel Ferrer]], [[Laura San Giacomo]], [[Jamey Sheridan]], [[Ossie Davis]], [[Ruby Dee]], [[Bill Fagerbakke]], and [[Shawnee Smith]], with notable cameos including [[John Landis]], [[Ed Harris]], [[Kathy Bates]], [[Sam Raimi]], and King himself. Parts of the miniseries were shot in [[Salt Lake City]], [[Utah State Prison]], [[Sundance Resort|Sundance]], [[Orem]], [[Provo Canyon]], and [[Salina, Utah|Salina]] in [[Utah]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=D'Arc|first1=James V.|title=When Hollywood came to town: a history of moviemaking in Utah|date=2010|publisher=Gibbs Smith|location=Layton, Utah|isbn=9781423605874|edition=1st}}</ref>\n\nBetween 2011 and 2016, [[Warner Bros. Pictures]] and [[CBS Films]] were developing a feature-length film adaptation of ''The Stand''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/blogs/heat-vision/stephen-kings-stand-heading-big-94805|title=Stephen King's 'The Stand' Heading to the Big Screen (Exclusive) | work=The Hollywood Reporter | first=Borys|last=Kit|date=2011-01-31|accessdate=2014-08-02}}</ref> In August 2011, director [[David Yates]] and screenwriter [[Steve Kloves]], known for their collaboration on the ''[[Harry Potter (film series)|Harry Potter]]'' films, were hired to direct/write a multimovie version of ''The Stand'',<ref>{{cite web|last=McWeeny |first=Drew |url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/motion-captured/posts/exclusive-potter-masterminds-steve-kloves-and-david-yates-reunite-for-the-stand |title=Exclusive: Potter masterminds Steve Kloves and David Yates reunite for The Stand |publisher=Hitfix.com |date=2012-06-28 |accessdate=2012-07-02}}</ref> but left the project in October 2011, as Yates felt it would work better as a miniseries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://whatculture.com/film/david-yates-says-hes-not-making-the-stand-because-it-should-be-tv-mini-series.php |title=David Yates Says He\u2019s Not Making THE STAND Because It Should Be TV Mini-Series |publisher=Whatculture.com |date=2011-11-12 |accessdate=2012-07-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117171113/http://whatculture.com/film/david-yates-says-hes-not-making-the-stand-because-it-should-be-tv-mini-series.php |archivedate=January 17, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Both [[Ben Affleck]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Thompson|first=Anne|title=More Details on Ben Affleck in Snyder's Superman/Batman UPDATED|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/thompsononhollywood/be-affleck-is-the-new-batman-in-snyders-superman-batman|publisher=IndieWire|accessdate=2014-08-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203031502/http://blogs.indiewire.com/thompsononhollywood/be-affleck-is-the-new-batman-in-snyders-superman-batman|archive-date=December 3, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and [[Scott Cooper (director)|Scott Cooper]] dropped out over creative differences with the studio.<ref>{{cite web|last=Shaw|first=Lucas|title=\u2018Crazy Heart\u2019 Director Scott Cooper Exits Warner Bros.\u2019 Stephen King Adaptation (Exclusive)|url=https://www.thewrap.com/crazy-heart-director-scott-cooper-stephen-king|publisher=The Wrap|accessdate=2014-08-02}}</ref> On February 25, 2014, [[Josh Boone (director)|Josh Boone]] was hired to write and direct the adaptation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/fault-stars-director-talks-tackle-682033||title='Fault In Our Stars' Director in Talks to Tackle Stephen King's 'The Stand'|last=Kit|first=Borys|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=2014-02-25|accessdate=2014-09-10}}</ref> He later revealed that he wanted [[Christian Bale]] to play Randall Flagg and [[Matthew McConaughey]] for the role of Stu Redman.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/JoshBooneMovies/status/503313944413761536|title=I have always wanted McConaughey as Stu and Bale as Flagg. Still not sure how that story leaked \u2013 just not true.|author=Josh Boone|date=23 Aug 2014|publisher=Twitter}}</ref> By September 10, 2014, the script had been completed and pre-production was underway.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/the-stand-movie-details-three-hour-cut-josh-boone/|title=Director Josh Boone On THE STAND, Fidelity to the Novel, Script Status, and Whether He'll Direct LESTAT|last=Cook|first=Tommy|work=Collider.com|date=2014-09-10|accessdate=2014-09-10}}/</ref> In November, Boone planned to split his adaptation into four full-length feature films in an effort to remain true to the breadth of King's sprawling novel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://smodcast.com/episodes/hollywood-babble-on-bonus-babble-on-hollywood-josh-boone-the-fault-in-our-stand/|title=Hollywood Babble-On Bonus: Babble on Hollywood: Josh Boone: The Fault In Our Stand|author=|date=|work=smodcast.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141120170433/http://smodcast.com/episodes/hollywood-babble-on-bonus-babble-on-hollywood-josh-boone-the-fault-in-our-stand|archivedate=November 20, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>Fleming Jr., Mike (November 21, 2014). [https://web.archive.org/web/20160221020603/http://deadline.com/2014/11/the-stand-stephen-king-josh-boone-four-films-1201291709/ \"Josh Boone Says Warner Bros Will Turn Stephen King\u2019s \u2018The Stand\u2019 Into Four Films.\"] ''Deadline''.</ref> In June 2015, Warner Bros. proposed an eight-part [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] miniseries to set up the story, which would culminate in Josh Boone's film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/447603-stephen-kings-the-stand-to-begin-as-eight-part-television-miniseries|title=Stephen King's The Stand to Begin as an Eight-Part Television Miniseries! - ComingSoon.net|date=June 5, 2015|work=comingsoon.net|accessdate=February 6, 2017}}</ref> However, in February 2016, ''The Stand'' project was put on hold and the rights reverted to CBS Films.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/josh-boone-stephen-king-revival-the-stand-the-fault-in-our-stars-1201694681/|title=\u2018The Fault In Our Stars\u2019 Helmer Josh Boone Pushes Back Stephen King\u2019s \u2018The Stand\u2019 To Next Direct \u2018Revival\u2019|last=|first=|date=February 2016|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, King talked of doing an extended TV series on Showtime or [[CBS All Access]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2017/09/stephen-king-on-movies-geralds-game-1922-it-the-stand.html|title=Stephen King on His New Netflix Movies, It, and His Big Year|last=Buchanan|first=Kyle|work=[[Vulture.com]]|date=September 25, 2017|accessdate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> In January 2019, a 10-hour limited series was ordered by CBS Television Studios to be broadcast on CBS All Access.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/stephen-king-stand-series-order-cbs-1203123968/|title=Stephen King\u2019s \u2018The Stand\u2019 Gets Series Order at CBS All Access|last=Low|first=Elaine|work=[[Variety.com]]|date=January 30, 2019|accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref> [[James Marsden]], [[Amber Heard]], [[Whoopi Goldberg]], [[Greg Kinnear]], [[Odessa Young]], and [[Henry Zaga]] were all in consideration for the roles of Stu Redman, Nadine Cross, Mother Abagail, Glen Bateman, Frannie Goldsmith, and Nick Andros, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/stephen-kings-the-stand-casting-rumors/|title=Stephen King's The Stand TV Adaptation Reportedly Eyeing Some Huge Stars|last=Solis|first=Jorge|work=[[cbr.com]]|date=June 22, 2019|accessdate=June 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Comics===\n{{Main|The Stand (comics)}}\n[[Marvel Comics]] adapted ''The Stand'' into a series of six five-issue comic book [[Limited series (comics)|miniseries]].<ref name=\"rama1\">[http://forum.newsarama.com/showthread.php?t=150380 King: Marvel to Adapt The Stand as a graphic novel]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [[Newsarama]], March 17, 2008</ref> The series was written by [[Roberto Aguirre-Sacasa]] and illustrated by [[Mike Perkins]]. Colorist [[Laura Martin]], letterer [[Chris Eliopoulos]], and cover artist [[Lee Bermejo]] were also on the staff. The first issue of ''[[The Stand: Captain Trips]]'' was released on September 10, 2008.<ref name=\"MarvelAnnounces\">{{cite web |url=http://marvel.com/news/comicstories.3768.WW_Philly_2008%7Ecolon%7E_The_Stand |title=Wizard World Philadelphia 2008: Stephen King's The Stand |author=Stevens, Tim |date=2008-05-31 |publisher=Marvel.com |accessdate=2014-08-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100818014514/http://marvel.com/news/comicstories.3768.WW_Philly_2008~colon~_The_Stand |archive-date=August 18, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n[[Metallica]] derived the title for its song \"Ride the Lightning\" from a quote from ''The Stand''.<ref name=\"HowWeMade\">{{cite web |url=https://www.loudersound.com/features/metallica-how-we-made-ride-the-lightning |title=How We Made Ride the Lightning |author=Everley, Dave |date=2016-05-19 |publisher=loudersound.com |accessdate=2019-06-03|df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[The Alarm]] had a song on the album ''[[Declaration (The Alarm album)|Declaration]]''  called \"The Stand (Prophecy)\" as an homage to the book. The song contained certain lyrics directly related to the book, such as \"I met the walking dude, religious, with his worn out cowboy boots,\" and \"Hey Trashcan, where you going boy?\"   \nThe main chorus of the song was \"Come on down and meet your maker, come on down and make the stand.\"{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nThe title track to the album ''[[Among the Living]]'' by the band [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]] is based on the novel.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{isfdb title|id=1148|title=The Stand}}\n* [http://www.bookpoi.com/the_stand_by_stephen_king_first_edition_identification.html Bookpoi]\u2014How to identify first edition copies of ''The Stand'' by Stephen King.\n\n{{The Stand}}\n{{Stephen King}}\n{{DarkTower}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stand, The}}\n[[Category:The Stand]]\n[[Category:1978 American novels]]\n[[Category:American post-apocalyptic novels]]\n[[Category:American horror novels]]\n[[Category:Biological weapons in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Novels about dreams]]\n[[Category:Novels about nightmares]]